ovies of 2019|date=December 31, 2019|website=Film School Rejects}}</ref>\n* 3rd{{snd}} Katie Rife \u2013 ''The A.V. Club''<ref name=\"auto3\"/>\n* 3rd{{snd}} Roxana Hadadi \u2013 ''The A.V. Club''<ref name=\"auto3\"/>\n* 3rd{{snd}} [[Stephanie Zacharek]] \u2013 ''[[Time (magazine)|Time]]''<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://time.com/5737103/best-movies-2019/|title=The 10 Best Movies of 2019|website=Time}}</ref>\n* 3rd{{snd}} Clayton Dillard \u2013 ''Slant''<ref name=\"auto5\"/>\n* 3rd{{snd}} Michael Barker \u2013 [[Film at Lincoln Center]]<ref name=\"auto2\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.indiewire.com/2019/12/best-movies-2019-indie-film-community-1202198566/|title=The Best Films of 2019, According to the Independent Film Community|first1=Eric|last1=Kohn|first2=Eric|last2=Kohn|date=December 24, 2019}}</ref>\n* 3rd{{snd}} Wes Greene \u2013 ''Slant''<ref name=\"auto5\"/>\n* 3rd{{snd}} Bob Strauss \u2013 ''[[Los Angeles Daily News]]''<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.dailynews.com/2019-was-a-terrific-year-for-movies-here-are-12-films-you-have-to-see|title=2019 was a terrific year for movies. Here are 12 films you have to see|date=December 17, 2019}}</ref>\n* 3rd{{snd}} [[Online Film Critics Society]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://ofcs.org/ofcs-presents-22nd-annual-nominations-for-2018-2-2/|title=OFCS Presents: 23rd Annual Awards for 2019|first=Governing|last=Committee|date=January 7, 2020}}</ref>\n* 4th{{snd}} [[Kyle Smith]] \u2013 ''[[National Review]]''<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nationalreview.com/2019/12/movie-review-ten-best-films-2019/|title=The Ten Best Films of 2019|date=December 23, 2019}}</ref>\n* 4th{{snd}} Tomris Laffly \u2013 RogerEbert.com<ref name=\"auto4\"/>\n* 4th{{snd}} IndieWire (300+ Critics Survey)<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.indiewire.com/2019/12/best-movies-2019-critics-survey-poll-performances-parasite-adam-driver-lupita-nyongo-1202197615/|title=2019 Critics Poll: The Best Films and Performances According to Over 300 Critics From Around the World|first1=Eric|last1=Kohn|first2=Eric|last2=Kohn|date=December 16, 2019}}</ref>\n* 4th{{snd}} Ignatiy Vishnevetsky \u2013 ''The A.V. Club''<ref name=\"auto3\"/>\n* 4th{{snd}} David Sims \u2013 ''[[The Atlantic]]''<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theatlantic.com/entertainment/archive/2019/12/10-best-films-2019/602797/|title=The 10 Best Films of 2019|first=David|last=Sims|date=December 5, 2019|website=The Atlantic}}</ref>\n* 4th{{snd}} Vinnie Mancuso \u2013 [[Collider (website)|Collider]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://collider.com/best-movies-of-the-year-2019/|title=Vinnie Mancuso's Top 10 Films of 2019|first=Vinnie|last=Mancuso|date=December 10, 2019}}</ref>\n* 4th{{snd}} [[Sight & Sound]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://theplaylist.net/souvenir-parasite-sight-sounds-top-20-films-2019-20191201/|title='The Souvenir,' 'Parasite' Top Sight & Sound's Top 20 Films Of 2019|website=theplaylist.net}}</ref>\n* 4th{{snd}} ''[[Complex (magazine)|Complex]]''<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.complex.com/pop-culture/best-movies-of-2019/|title=The Best Movies of 2019'Once Upon a Time... in Hollywood'|website=Complex}}</ref>\n* 5th{{snd}} Alissa Wilkinson \u2013 [[Vox (website)|Vox]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.vox.com/2019/12/5/20983881/best-movies-2019-streaming-how-to-watch|title=The 21 best films of 2019|first=Alissa|last=Wilkinson|date=December 5, 2019|website=Vox}}</ref>\n* 5th{{snd}} Kate Erbland \u2013 IndieWire<ref name=\"auto1\"/>\n* 5th{{snd}} Christopher Gray \u2013 ''Slant''<ref name=\"auto5\"/>\n* 5th{{snd}} Keith Watson \u2013 ''Slant''<ref name=\"auto5\"/>\n* 5th{{snd}} Dan Jackson \u2013 [[Thrillist]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thrillist.com/entertainment/nation/best-movies-of-2019|title=The 50 Best Movies of 2019, Ranked|first=Dan|last=Jackson|date=January 3, 2020|website=Thrillist}}</ref>\n* 5th{{snd}} Charles Bramesco \u2013 ''The A.V. Club''<ref name=\"auto3\"/>\n* 6th{{snd}} Adam Chitwood \u2013 Collider<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://collider.com/best-2019-movies/|title=Adam Chitwood's Top 10 Films of 2019|first=Adam|last=Chitwood|date=December 13, 2019}}</ref>\n* 6th{{snd}} Chuck Bowen \u2013 ''Slant''<ref name=\"auto5\"/>\n* 6th{{snd}} Samuel R. Murian \u2013 ''[[Parade (magazine)|Parade]]''<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://parade.com/967301/samuelmurrian/best-movies-of-2019-ranked/|title=The 25 Best Movies of 2019, Ranked|first=Samuel R.|last=Murrian|date=December 18, 2019|website=Parade}}</ref>\n* 6th{{snd}} Andr\u00e9a Picard \u2013 Film at Lincoln Center<ref name=\"auto2\"/>\n* 7th{{snd}} Monica Castillo \u2013 RogerEbert.com<ref name=\"auto4\"/>\n* 7th{{snd}} Guy Lodge \u2013 ''[[The Guardian]]''<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/film/2019/dec/03/50-best-films-of-2019-in-the-us|title=The 50 best films of 2019 in the US: the full list|date=December 20, 2019|via=www.theguardian.com}}</ref>\n* 7th{{snd}} Derek Smith \u2013 ''Slant''<ref name=\"auto5\"/>\n* 7th{{snd}} ''[[Sydney Morning Herald]]''\n* 8th{{snd}} Mark Hughes \u2013 ''[[Forbes]]''<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/markhughes/2020/12/30/the-top-20-best-films-of-2019/|title=The Top 20 Best Films Of 2019|first=Mark|last=Hughes|website=Forbes}}</ref>\n* 8th{{snd}} Glenn Kenny \u2013 RogerEbert.com<ref name=\"auto4\"/>\n* 8th{{snd}} Matt Fagerholm \u2013 RogerEbert.com<ref name=\"auto4\"/>\n* 8th{{snd}} [[Yahoo! Entertainment]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bostonglobe.com/2019/12/20/arts/ty-burrs-best-movies-2019/|title=Ty Burr's best movies of 2019 - The Boston Globe|website=BostonGlobe.com}}</ref>\n* 8th{{snd}} [[Justin Chang]] \u2013 ''[[Los Angeles Times]]''<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.latimes.com/entertainment-arts/movies/story/2019-12-06/2019-best-movies-justin-chang|title=Justin Chang's best movies of 2019: 'Parasite,' 'Knives Out' stand at the head of the class|date=December 6, 2019|website=Los Angeles Times}}</ref>\n* 8th{{snd}} Alex Biese \u2013 ''[[Asbury Park Press]]''<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.app.com/story/entertainment/movies/2019/12/12/best-movies-2019-midsommar-irishman-parasite/4309923002/|title=Best movies of 2019: The Irishman, Parasite and Midsommar among the year's instant classics|first=Alex|last=Biese|website=Asbury Park Press}}</ref>\n* 8th{{snd}} [[Eugene Hernandez]] \u2013 Film at Lincoln Center<ref name=\"auto2\"/>\n* 9th{{snd}} Mike D'Angelo \u2013 ''The A.V. Club''<ref name=\"auto3\"/>\n* 9th{{snd}} Robert Daniels \u2013 RogerEbert.com<ref name=\"auto4\"/>\n* 9th{{snd}} Ben Kenigsberg \u2013 RogerEbert.com<ref name=\"auto4\"/>\n* 9th{{snd}} Caroline Siede \u2013 ''[[The A.V. Club]]''<ref name=\"auto3\"/>\n* 9th{{snd}} [[A. O. Scott]] \u2013 ''[[The New York Times]]''<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/12/04/movies/best-films.html|title=Best Movies of 2019|first1=A. O.|last1=Scott|first2=Manohla|last2=Dargis|date=December 4, 2019|via=NYTimes.com}}</ref>\n* 10th{{snd}} [[Tom Brook]] \u2013 ''[[Talking Movies]]''<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/av/entertainment-arts-50837255/what-are-talking-movies-top-10-films-for-2019|title=What are Talking Movies' Top 10 films for 2019?|website=BBC News}}</ref>\n* 10th{{snd}} Joshua Rothkopf \u2013 ''[[Time Out (magazine)#Time Out New York|Time Out New York]]''<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.timeout.com/newyork/movies/best-movies-of-2019|title=The 20 best movies of 2019|website=[[Time Out (magazine)#Time Out New York|Time Out New York]]}}</ref>\n{{div col end}}\n\n== Pop culture references ==\nThe title is a reference to director [[Sergio Leone]]'s second western/American trilogy, ''[[Once Upon a Time in the West]]'', ''Once Upon a Time\u2026 the Revolution'' (which producers insisted on retitling ''[[Duck, You Sucker!]]'' ), and ''[[Once Upon a Time in America]]''.<ref name=easter-eggs/>\n\nArchive footage from many films is included in ''Once Upon a Time in Hollywood'', including ''[[C.C. and Company]]'', ''[[Lady in Cement]]'', ''[[Three in the Attic]]'', and ''[[The Wrecking Crew (1968 film)|The Wrecking Crew]]'', in which [[Sharon Tate]] appears as Freya Carlson. Three scenes were digitally altered, replacing the original actors with Rick Dalton. One from an episode of ''[[The F.B.I. (TV series)|The F.B.I.]]'', entitled \"All the Streets Are Silent,\" in which Dalton appears as a character originally portrayed by [[Burt Reynolds]]. Another from ''[[Death on the Run]]'', with Dalton's face imposed over [[Ty Hardin]]'s. The third is from ''[[The Great Escape (film)|The Great Escape]]'', with Dalton appearing as Virgil Hilts, the role made famous by [[Steve McQueen]].<ref name=easter-eggs>{{cite news |url=https://screenrant.com/once-upon-time-hollywood-movie-easter-eggs-cameos/ |title=Once Upon a Time in Hollywood: Every Easter Egg, Tarantino Reference & Cameo |website=[[Screen Rant]] |last=Hunt |first=James |access-date=August 16, 2019 |date=August 16, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190816180441/https://screenrant.com/once-upon-time-hollywood-movie-easter-eggs-cameos/ |archive-date=August 16, 2019 |url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=FakeMovies>{{cite news |url=https://www.thewrap.com/once-upon-a-time-in-hollywood-what-real-movies-inspired-rick-daltons-fake-films/ |title='Once Upon a Time in Hollywood': What Real Movies Inspired Rick Dalton's Fake Films? |work=[[TheWrap]] |last=Welk |first=Brian |access-date=August 13, 2019 |date=July 26, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190814094933/https://www.thewrap.com/once-upon-a-time-in-hollywood-what-real-movies-inspired-rick-daltons-fake-films/ |archive-date=August 14, 2019 |url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"Archive footage\"/> For ''The 14 Fists of McCluskey'', a WWII film within the film starring Dalton, footage and music from ''[[Hell River]]'' is used.<ref>{{cite web |last=Tate |first=James M. |url=http://www.cultfilmfreaks.com/2019/08/hell-river.html |title=How 'Hell River' Connects 'Once Upon a Time in Hollywood' |website=cult film freak |access-date=September 4, 2019 |date=August 26, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190905020522/http://www.cultfilmfreaks.com/2019/08/hell-river.html |archive-date=September 5, 2019 |url-status=live}}</ref> Additionally, Martin Abrahams, [[Brioni Farrell]], Victor Freitag, [[Nancy Kwan]], [[Dean Martin]], [[Hannes Messemer]], [[Gordon Mitchell]], [[Rod Taylor]], [[Burt Ward]], and [[Adam West]] appear via archive footage and sound.\n\nThe 1959 [[Ford Galaxie]] driven by the Manson Family is a detailed replica of the car used in the Tate\u2013LaBianca murders. Car coordinator Steven Butcher found the actual car, but after a meeting with Tarantino, they decided using it would be \"too creepy.\"<ref name=vintage-cars>{{cite news |url=https://www.thewrap.com/once-upon-a-time-in-hollywood-cars-reservoir-dogs/ |title=Quentin Tarantino used an 'Absurd Amount of Vintage Cars in 'Once Upon a Time in Hollywood'{{'}} |website=[[TheWrap]] |last=Welk |first=Brian |access-date=August 14, 2019 |date=July 31, 2019 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190814161623/https://www.thewrap.com/once-upon-a-time-in-hollywood-cars-reservoir-dogs/ |archive-date=August 14, 2019}}</ref>\n\n[[Mark Lindsay]], lead singer of [[Paul Revere & the Raiders]], whose music is featured in the film, once lived at [[10050 Cielo Drive]], the address of the Tate murders. On the poster of Dalton's film ''Red Blood Red Skin'', inspired by ''[[Land Raiders (film)|Land Raiders]]'', he appears with [[Telly Savalas]]. The posters for the two films are the same, except with Dalton replacing [[George Maharis]]. The movie Voytek Frykowski is watching is ''[[Teenage Monster]]'', presented by horror host [[Larry Vincent|Seymour]].<ref name=FakeMovies/><ref name=annotated>{{cite news |url=https://film.avclub.com/once-upon-a-time-in-hollywood-annotated-1836793225 |title=Once Upon a Time... in Hollywood... annotated |website=[[The A.V. Club]] |access-date=September 1, 2019 |date=August 2, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190804014912/https://film.avclub.com/once-upon-a-time-in-hollywood-annotated-1836793225 |archive-date=August 4, 2019 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n=== Connections to other Tarantino films ===\nCliff Booth is a reference to Brad Pitt's character in ''Inglourious Basterds'', Aldo Raine, who takes the cover of a stuntman.<ref name=easter-eggs/> Dalton stars in a Spaghetti Western directed by Antonio Margheriti which is a reference to an alias used by the Basterds.<ref>https://www.indiewire.com/2019/07/once-upon-a-time-in-hollywood-inglourious-basterds-easter-egg-explained-1202160949/</ref> When Dalton and Booth get back from Italy they walk by the blue mosaic wall in [[LAX]], the same wall that the title character in Tarantino's ''[[Jackie Brown]]'' ([[Pam Grier]]) moves past in the opening credits of that film.<ref name=39-details>{{cite news |last=Snyder |first=Chris |url=https://www.businessinsider.com/quentin-tarantino-once-upon-time-hollywood-details-you-missed-2019-7 |title=39 details you may have missed in Tarantino's \"Once Upon a Time in Hollywood\" |website=Business Insider |access-date=September 15, 2019 |date=August 2, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190803025838/https://www.businessinsider.com/quentin-tarantino-once-upon-time-hollywood-details-you-missed-2019-7 |archive-date=August 3, 2019 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nIn the film, Lee engages in a fight with Cliff Booth on the set of ''The Green Hornet''.<ref name=39-details/><ref name=controversial-scene/> The ''Green Hornet'' [[Flight of the Bumblebee|theme song]] is featured in Tarantino's ''[[Kill Bill: Volume 1]]''.<ref name=39-details/> The masks worn by the Crazy 88 gang in that film are the same as Lee's mask as Kato in ''The Green Hornet''.<ref>{{cite web |last=Siller |first=Alexandra |title=O-Ren Ishii: Samurai of The Underworld |url=https://medium.com/@acs58312/in-the-eyes-of-kill-bill-s-o-ren-ishii-311c7f5bffe8 |website=Medium |date=April 3, 2016 |access-date=September 28, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170113182430/https://medium.com/@acs58312/in-the-eyes-of-kill-bill-s-o-ren-ishii-311c7f5bffe8 |archive-date=January 13, 2017 |url-status=live}}</ref> The car Booth drives is a 1964 blue [[Volkswagen Karmann Ghia]] convertible. It is the same year, color, make and model of the car that [[The Bride (Kill Bill)|Beatrix \"the Bride\" Kiddo]] ([[Uma Thurman]]) drives in ''[[Kill Bill: Volume 2]]''.<ref name=geek-easter-eggs>{{cite news |last=Crow |first=David |url=https://www.denofgeek.com/us/movies/282478/once-upon-a-time-in-hollywood-easter-eggs-references |title=Once Upon a Time in Hollywood Easter Eggs Guide |website=[[Den of Geek]] |access-date=August 31, 2019 |date=August 17, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190831010250/https://www.denofgeek.com/us/movies/282478/once-upon-a-time-in-hollywood-easter-eggs-references |archive-date=August 31, 2019 |url-status=live}}</ref> Similarly, Rick Dalton's 1966 [[Cadillac de Ville series|Cadillac de Ville]] is the same as the car driven by Mr. Blonde ([[Michael Madsen]]) in ''[[Reservoir Dogs]]''. It is owned by Madsen.<ref name=vintage-cars/>\n\nTarantino-invented fast food chain [[Big Kahuna Burger]] appears on a billboard. The final scene features Rick Dalton in a commercial for fictional Red Apple cigarettes, which appear in many Tarantino films.<ref name=gamespot-easter-eggs/><ref name=easter-eggs/><ref name=\"Archive footage\"/><ref name=geek-easter-eggs/>\n\n== Historical accuracy ==\nIn a scene, Sharon Tate goes into Larry Edmunds Bookshop and purchases a copy of ''[[Tess of the d'Urbervilles]]''. In real life, Tate gave a copy to Roman Polanski shortly before her death. Years later, Polanski directed the film adaptation, ''[[Tess (1979 film)|Tess]]'', dedicating it to Tate. Dalton mentions he owns his house on advice from \"[[Edmond O'Brien|Eddie O'Brien]].\" Tate and Polanski's [[Yorkie Terrier]] in the film is named \"Dr. Sapirstein,\" as was Tate's Yorkie in real life, named after the doctor portrayed by [[Ralph Bellamy]] in ''Rosemary's Baby''. The carrier she puts the dog in is the same one the real Tate actually owned. The outfit Margot Robbie wears in the Bruin Theater scene is the same one Tate wore in ''[[Eye of the Devil]]''.<ref name=geek-easter-eggs/>\n\n[[File:Fox Bruin Theater (Westwood).jpg|thumb|upright=1.2|The [[Fox Bruin Theater]]]]\n\nIn the film, Tate goes to see ''[[The Wrecking Crew (1968 film)|The Wrecking Crew]]'' at the [[Bruin Theater]]. She convinces the theater's employees that she stars in the movie after they fail to recognize her. Tarantino stated the idea came to him from an experience he had. When ''[[True Romance]]'' was released, he saw it at the same theater, where he eventually convinced its employees that he wrote the script.<ref name=cinema-blend>{{cite news |last=O'Connell |first=Sean |url=https://www.cinemablend.com/podcast/2476541/will-quentin-tarantinos-last-movie-be-star-trek-the-director-talks-about-a-loophole |title=Will Quentin Tarantino's Last Movie Be Star Trek? The Director Talks About A 'Loophole' |website=CinemaBlend |access-date=August 26, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190814190145/https://www.cinemablend.com/podcast/2476541/will-quentin-tarantinos-last-movie-be-star-trek-the-director-talks-about-a-loophole |archive-date=August 14, 2019 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nOn the set of ''[[Batman (TV show)|Batman]]'', for a crossover episode with ''[[The Green Hornet (TV series)|The Green Hornet]]'', a fight was scripted with Kato losing to [[Robin (character)|Robin]] ([[Burt Ward]]). When Lee received the script, he refused to do it, so it was changed to a draw. When the cameras rolled, Lee stalked Ward until Ward backed away. Lee laughed and told him he was \"lucky it is a TV show.\"<ref name=Kato-show>{{cite news |url=https://www.newsweek.com/bruce-lee-king-fu-martial-arts-390811 |title=The Kato Show: Bruce Lee as the Green Hornet's Sidekick |website=[[Newsweek]] |access-date=August 26, 2019 |date=November 20, 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190831111350/https://www.newsweek.com/bruce-lee-king-fu-martial-arts-390811 |archive-date=August 31, 2019 |url-status=live}}</ref> In the film, Cliff Booth reminisces about fighting Lee on the set of ''The Green Hornet''; the imaginary fight also ends in a draw. Booth refers to Lee as \"Kato.\"<ref name=controversial-scene/>\n\nAccording to Rudolph Altobelli, who rented the house to Polanski and Tate, in March 1969, Charles Manson showed up looking for [[Terry Melcher]]. Polanski's friend Shahrokh Hatami also said he saw Manson enter the grounds. Hatami approached Manson, asking him what he wanted. He told Hatami he was looking for Melcher. Hatami responded the house was the Polanski residence and perhaps Melcher lived in the guest house. Altobelli told Manson that Melcher no longer lived there.<ref>{{cite news |last=Caldwell |first=Earl |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1970/10/22/archives/manson-put-at-tate-home-5-months-before-killings.html |title=Manson Put at Tate Home 5 Months Before Killings |website=[[The New York Times]] |access-date=August 26, 2019 |date=October 22, 1970 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190826230558/https://www.nytimes.com/1970/10/22/archives/manson-put-at-tate-home-5-months-before-killings.html |archive-date=August 26, 2019 |url-status=live}}</ref> This happens in the film, with Sebring in place of Altobelli and Hatami.\n\nOn the night of August 8, 1969, Patricia Krenwinkel, Charles Watson, and Susan Atkins broke into Polanski's and Tate's house, leading to the murders of Tate (eight-and-a-half months pregnant), Sebring, Wojciech Frykowski, and Abigail Folger. In the film, they go to Tate's house to commit the murders but instead end up breaking into Dalton's house after he interrupts them.<ref name=helter-skelter/> Linda Kasabian went along that night as she was the only Family member with a valid driver's license, though she did not murder anyone and stayed outside the whole time. In the film, she also goes along but does not participate.<ref name=helter-skelter/> Watson told his victims, \"I'm the [[Devil]], and I came to do the Devil's business.\" In the film, he says it to Cliff Booth.<ref name=devils-business>{{cite news |last=Romano |first=Evan |url=https://www.menshealth.com/entertainment/a28521042/once-upon-a-time-in-hollywood-devil-line-real-tex-watson/ |title=Was that Creepy Line from Once Upon a Time...in Hollywood Real? |website=[[Men's Health]] |access-date=August 20, 2019 |date=July 26, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190820181956/https://www.menshealth.com/entertainment/a28521042/once-upon-a-time-in-hollywood-devil-line-real-tex-watson/ |archive-date=August 20, 2019 |url-status=live}}</ref> In the film, Atkins convinces the others to seek revenge by killing Rick Dalton, star of a TV western. Since TV taught them to kill, it is fitting they kill the guy from TV, and \"My idea is to kill the people who taught us to kill!\"<ref name=how-true-to-life>{{cite news |last=Rao |first=Sonia |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/arts-entertainment/2019/07/29/how-true-life-is-once-upon-time-hollywood-ending/ |title=How true to life is the 'Once Upon a Time in Hollywood' ending? |website=[[The Washington Post]]|access-date=August 22, 2019 |date=July 29, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190803170857/https://www.washingtonpost.com/arts-entertainment/2019/07/29/how-true-life-is-once-upon-time-hollywood-ending/ |archive-date=August 3, 2019 |url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=twist-ending>{{cite news |last=Wilkinson |first=Alissa |url=https://www.vox.com/culture/2019/7/25/8906839/tarantino-once-upon-a-time-in-hollywood-spoilers-ending-manson |title=The twist ending of Quentin Tarantino's Once Upon a Time in Hollywood, explained |website=[[Vox (website)|Vox]]|access-date=August 22, 2019 |date=July 25, 2019}}</ref> In real life, Manson Family member [[Nancy Pitman]] said: \"We are what you have made us. We were brought up on your TV. We were brought up watching ''[[Gunsmoke]]'' and ''[[Have Gun \u2013 Will Travel]]''.\"<ref name=five-things>{{cite news |url=https://www.geeklygood.com/blogs/news/five-things-you-didnt-know-about-tarantinos-once-upon-a-time-in-hollywood |title=Five Things You Didn't Know About Tarantino's Once Upon a Time in Hollywood |website=geeklygoods |access-date=August 22, 2019 |date=July 29, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190823045625/https://geeklygood.com/blogs/news/five-things-you-didnt-know-about-tarantinos-once-upon-a-time-in-hollywood |archive-date=August 23, 2019 |url-status=live}}</ref> [[Sandra Good]] said: \"You want to talk about devils and demonic and immorals and evil, go to Hollywood. We don't touch the evil of that world. We don't even skim it.\"<ref>{{cite news |last=Kilkenny |first=Katie |url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/manson-women-followers-recall-leaders-manipulation-1230616 |title=Former Manson Followers Debate Family's Culpability: 'How Can You Point the Finger at Us?' |website=[[The Hollywood Reporter]] |access-date=August 28, 2019 |date=August 10, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190813210823/https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/manson-women-followers-recall-leaders-manipulation-1230616 |archive-date=August 13, 2019 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nThe next night, the same four, along with Leslie Van Houten, Manson, and Steve Grogan, drove to Leno and Rosemary LaBianca's house, murdering the couple. Afterwards, Manson directed Kasabian to drive to an apartment complex to commit more murders. Once there, Manson left in the car alone, leaving the others to hitchhike back to Spahn Ranch. In the film, it is Kasabian who drives off, deserting others. Watson says they can hitchhike back.<ref name=helter-skelter/> Grogan was convicted of the murder of stuntman [[Donald Shea|Donald \"Shorty\" Shea]] on Spahn Ranch, whom he repeatedly beat with a lead pipe. In the film, Grogan is instead beaten by a stuntman, Booth.<ref name=helter-skelter>{{cite book|last1=Bugliosi|first1=Vincent|first2=Curt|last2=Gentry|title=Helter Skelter \u2013 The True Story of the Manson Murders|edition=25th Anniversary|publisher=W.W. Norton & Company|year=1994|ISBN=0-393-08700-X|url-access=registration|url=https://archive.org/details/helterskeltertru00bugl_0}}</ref>\n\n[[Boeing 747]]s are used in several airliner scenes, but they were not in commercial use until 1970 even though the film is set a year earlier in 1969.<ref name=\"Time_Jumbo-Gremlins\">[http://www.time.com/time/magazine/article/0,9171,878184,00.html \"Jumbo and the Gremlins.\"] ''TIME'', February 2, 1970. Retrieved: December 20, 2007.</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.boeing.com/commercial/747family/background.html |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121002063408/http://www.boeing.com/commercial/747family/background.html |title=Boeing: Commercial Airplanes - 747 - About the 747 Family |archivedate=October 2, 2012 |work=Boeing}}</ref>\n\n=== The Manson Family in Hollywood ===\nCharles Manson once approached [[Steve McQueen]] with a script he wrote, to get him to produce it. When McQueen turned him down, an altercation happened, in which McQueen broke Manson's nose.<ref name=mcqueen-manson>{{cite news |url=https://www.esquire.com/uk/culture/film/news/a13833/steve-mcqueen-infidelity-charles-manson-murder/ |title=Steve McQueen's Womanizing Ways Stopped Him From Being Murdered By Charles Manson |website=[[Esquire (magazine)|Esquire]] |access-date=August 18, 2019 |date=March 21, 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180208003429/http://www.esquire.com/uk/culture/film/news/a13833/steve-mcqueen-infidelity-charles-manson-murder/ |archive-date=February 8, 2018 |url-status=live}}</ref> On the night of the Tate murders, Jay Sebring invited McQueen over to Tate's house; however, his date wanted to stay in.<ref>{{cite book |last=Eliot |first=Marc |title=Steve McQueen: A Biography |publisher=[[Crown Publishing Group]] |year=2011 |isbn=978-0-307-45323-5}}</ref> After the murders, it was reported that police found a Manson Family hit list with McQueen's name.<ref>{{cite book|last=Dunne|first=Dominick|title=The Way We Lived Then: Recollections of a Well Known Name Dropper|year=1999|location=New York City|publisher=[[Crown Publishing Group]]|ISBN=0-609-60388-4|url-access=registration|url=https://archive.org/details/waywelivedthenr00dunn}}</ref>\n\nBobby Beausoleil was an actor and [[porn star]]. He appeared in the documentary film ''[[Mondo Hollywood]]'', also featuring Sebring. [[Catherine Share]] met Beausoleil on the set of the [[softcore porn]] film ''Ramrodder''. Beausoleil introduced Share to Manson.<ref>{{cite book |title=Sinister Forces \u2013 The Manson Secret: A Grimoire of American Political Witchcraft |first=Peter |last=Lavenda |publisher=Trine Day |date=June 1, 2011 |isbn=978-0-9841858-3-2}}</ref> Atkins met Manson in San Francisco, where she had worked as an actress, portraying a [[vampire]] on [[Anton LaVey]]'s Witches Sabbath Club Show.<ref name=Guinn>{{cite book |last=Guinn |first=Jeff |title=Manson: The Life and Times of Charles Manson |publisher=[[Simon & Schuster]] |year=2013 |isbn=978-1-4516-4518-7}}</ref> LaVey appeared with Beausoleil in ''[[Lucifer Rising (film)|Lucifer Rising]]'',<ref name=Landis>{{cite book |last=Landis |first=Bill |title=Anger: An Unauthorized Biography of Kenneth Anger |publisher=[[Harper Collins]] |year=1995 |isbn=978-0-06-016700-4}}</ref> and claimed to have been a consultant on and appeared as the Devil in Polanski's ''Rosemary's Baby''.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://variety.com/1997/scene/people-news/anton-szandor-lavey-1116674361/ |title=Anton Szandor LaVey |website=Variety |access-date=August 28, 2019 |date=November 19, 1997 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190828233810/https://variety.com/1997/scene/people-news/anton-szandor-lavey-1116674361/ |archive-date=August 28, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Moffitt |first=Mike |url=https://www.sfchronicle.com/bayarea/article/When-the-Devil-lived-in-the-Richmond-7382271.php |title=When the Devil lived in the Richmond |website=[[San Francisco Chronicle]] |access-date=August 28, 2019 |date=May 4, 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190829002747/https://www.sfchronicle.com/bayarea/article/When-the-Devil-lived-in-the-Richmond-7382271.php |archive-date=August 29, 2019 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n== Portrayals of real-life figures==\n=== Bruce Lee ===\n[[File:Bruce Lee 1973.jpg|thumb|upright=0.84|[[Bruce Lee]], portrayed in the film by [[Mike Moh]]. The appearance of Lee in the film was criticized by Asian-Americans and former friends and family of him, who considered it offensive and inaccurate.]]Although its context is a daydream of Cliff Booth's rather than a \"real\" event in the narrative, the depiction of [[Bruce Lee]] drew criticism. Fans and contemporaries of Lee took issue with his portrayal.<ref name=daughter-saddened>{{Cite web |last=Molloy |first=Tim |url=https://www.thewrap.com/bruce-lee-daughter-mockery-once-upon-a-time-in-hollywood-shannon-lee/ |title=Bruce Lee's Daughter Saddened by 'Mockery' in Once Upon a Time...in Hollywood |work=[[TheWrap]]|accessdate=August 17, 2019 |date=July 29, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190816174854/https://www.thewrap.com/bruce-lee-daughter-mockery-once-upon-a-time-in-hollywood-shannon-lee/ |archive-date=August 16, 2019 |url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"shutup\">{{Cite magazine |last=Yap |first=Audrey Cleo |url=https://variety.com/2019/film/news/bruce-lee-quentin-tarantino-shannon-lee-interview-1203302850/ |magazine=Variety |title=Bruce Lee's Daughter Says Quentin Tarantino 'Could Shut Up' About Her Father's Portrayal |accessdate=August 17, 2019 |date=August 14, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190816201453/https://variety.com/2019/film/news/bruce-lee-quentin-tarantino-shannon-lee-interview-1203302850/ |archive-date=August 16, 2019 |url-status=live}}</ref> Lee's daughter, [[Shannon Lee|Shannon]], stated: \"[Lee] was continuously marginalized and treated like kind of a nuisance of a human being by white Hollywood, which is how he's treated in the film by [Tarantino].\"<ref name=inosanto>{{cite magazine |last=Yap |first=Audrey Cleo |url=https://variety.com/2019/film/features/bruce-lee-once-upon-a-time-in-hollywood-dan-inosanto-1203287237/ |title=Bruce Lee's Protege Recalls His Humility Amid 'Once Upon a Time' Criticism |magazine=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]] |accessdate=August 17, 2019 |date=July 31, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190816130517/https://variety.com/2019/film/features/bruce-lee-once-upon-a-time-in-hollywood-dan-inosanto-1203287237/ |archive-date=August 16, 2019 |url-status=live}}</ref> [[Kareem Abdul-Jabbar]], with whom Lee trained and appeared in ''[[Game of Death]]'', stated: \"Of course, Tarantino has the artistic right to portray Bruce any way he wants. But to do so in such a sloppy and somewhat racist way is a failure both as an artist and as a human being.\"<ref>{{Cite web |last=Abdul-Jabbar |first=Kareem |url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/kareem-abdul-jabbar-bruce-lee-was-my-friend-tarantinos-movie-disrespects-him-1232544 |title=Kareem Abdul-Jabbar:Bruce Lee Was My Friend, & Tarantino's Movie Disrespects Him |accessdate=August 17, 2019 |date=August 16, 2019 |website=[[The Hollywood Reporter]] |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190816194616/https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/kareem-abdul-jabbar-bruce-lee-was-my-friend-tarantinos-movie-disrespects-him-1232544 |archive-date=August 16, 2019 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n[[Mike Moh]], who played Lee, said he was conflicted at first: \"Bruce in my mind was literally a god. ... Bruce didn't always have the most affection for stuntmen; he didn't respect all of them.\"<ref name=Bruce-Lee-actor>{{cite news |last=Galbraith |first=Alex |url=https://www.complex.com/pop-culture/2019/08/bruce-lee-actor-once-upon-a-time-in-hollywood-fight-scene |title=Bruce Lee Actor Defends 'Once Upon A Time In Hollywood' Fight Scene |website=[[Complex (magazine)|Complex]] |accessdate=August 17, 2019 |date=August 4, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190817182856/https://www.complex.com/pop-culture/2019/08/bruce-lee-actor-once-upon-a-time-in-hollywood-fight-scene |archive-date=August 17, 2019 |url-status=live}}</ref> He stated, \"Tarantino loves Bruce Lee; he reveres him.\"<ref name=\"Mike-Moh-Bruce-Lee\">{{cite news |url=https://www.indiewire.com/2019/08/once-upon-a-time-in-hollywood-bruce-lee-mike-moh-1202163256/ |title='Once Upon a Time in Hollywood': Bruce Lee Actor Explains Why the Martial Arts King Loses to Brad Pitt |last=Lattanzio |first=Ryan |date=August 4, 2019 |access-date=August 17, 2019 |website=[[IndieWire]] |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190808113755/https://www.indiewire.com/2019/08/once-upon-a-time-in-hollywood-bruce-lee-mike-moh-1202163256/ |archive-date=August 8, 2019 |url-status=live}}</ref> Brad Pitt objected to an extended version of the fight, stating \"It's Bruce Lee, man!\" according to stunt coordinator Robert Alonzo.<ref name=\"jacobshuffington\">{{cite news |last1=Jacobs |first1=Matthew |title=Tarantino's Secrets, Brad's Pitt And Leo's Flames: Tales From 'Once Upon A Time In Hollywood' |url=https://www.huffingtonpost.co.uk/entry/once-upon-a-time-in-hollywood-tarantino-behind-the-scenes_n_5d434018e4b0acb57fc97dfa?guccounter=1 |accessdate=March 3, 2020 |work=Huffington Post |date=August 6, 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"sharfindiewire\">{{cite news |last1=Sharf |first1=Zack |title=Brad Pitt Objected to Extended Bruce Lee Fight Scene in \u2018Once Upon a Time in Hollywood\u2019 Script |url=https://www.indiewire.com/2019/08/brad-pitt-rejected-extended-bruce-lee-fight-once-upon-a-time-in-hollywood-1202163376/ |accessdate=March 3, 2020 |work=IndieWire |date=August 5, 2019}}</ref> According to Lee's friend and ''[[The Green Hornet (TV series)|The Green Hornet]]'' stuntman [[Gene LeBell]], Lee had a reputation for \"kicking the shit out of the stuntmen. They couldn't convince him that he could go easy and it would still look great on film.\"<ref name=\"Debunking Mockery\"/> Lee biographer Matthew Polly stated, \"Bruce was very famous for being very considerate of the people below him on film sets, particularly the stuntmen. ... So in this scene, Bruce Lee is essentially calling out a stuntman and getting him fired because he's the big star.\"<ref name=\"controversial-scene\">{{cite news |last=Bruney |first=Gabrielle |url=https://www.esquire.com/entertainment/a28607548/mike-moh-bruce-lee-once-upon-a-time-in-hollywood-controversy |title=Why the Bruce Lee Fight in Once Upon a Time in Hollywood Has Become the Movie's Most Controversial Scene |website=[[Esquire (magazine)|Esquire]] |accessdate=August 18, 2019 |date=August 7, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190807002649/https://www.esquire.com/entertainment/a28607548/mike-moh-bruce-lee-once-upon-a-time-in-hollywood-controversy/ |archive-date=August 7, 2019 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nTarantino responded, saying Lee was \"kind of an arrogant guy,\" and that Lee's widow [[Linda Lee Cadwell|Linda]] wrote in ''[[Bruce Lee: The Man Only I Knew]]'' that he could beat [[Muhammad Ali]].<ref name=shutup/> However, the book in question has a quote from a film critic stating so, not Linda.<ref name=\"fuster2019\">{{cite news |last1=Fuster |first1=Jeremy |title=Quentin Tarantino Defends \u2018Hollywood\u2019 Depiction of Bruce Lee: \u2018He Was Kind of an Arrogant Guy\u2019 |url=https://www.thewrap.com/tarantino-defends-bruce-lee-portrayal/ |accessdate=March 8, 2020 |work=The Wrap |date=August 19, 2019}}</ref> In 1972, Lee himself stated: \"Everybody says I must fight Ali some day. ... Look at my hand. That's a little Chinese hand. He'd kill me.\"<ref>{{cite book |last=Clouse |first=Robert |date=1988 |title=Bruce Lee: The Biography |publisher=Unique Publications |page=112 |isbn=978-0-86568-133-0}}</ref>\n\n=== Sharon Tate ===\nTarantino gave an early script to a representative of [[Roman Polanski]], Tate's husband, to assure him that \"he didn't have anything to worry about\". Tarantino stated: \"When it comes to Polanski, we're talking about a tragedy that would be unfathomable for most human beings.\"<ref name=Polanski-contacted>{{cite news |last=Sharf |first=Zack |url=https://www.indiewire.com/2019/07/roman-polanski-tarantino-once-upon-a-time-in-hollywood-talks-1202159276/ |title=Roman Polanski Contacted Tarantino With Questions About 'Once Upon a Time in Hollywood' |website=[[Indiewire]] |accessdate=August 17, 2019 |date=July 19, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190720130648/https://www.indiewire.com/2019/07/roman-polanski-tarantino-once-upon-a-time-in-hollywood-talks-1202159276/ |archive-date=July 20, 2019 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nDebra Tate, Sharon's sister, initially opposed the film, saying it was exploitative and perpetuated mistruths: \"To celebrate the killers and the darkest portion of society as being sexy or acceptable in any way, shape or form is just perpetuating the worst of our society.\"<ref name=\"debra-tate\"/> After Tarantino contacted her and showed her the script, she withdrew opposition, saying: \"This movie is not what people would expect it to be when you combine the Tarantino and Manson names.\" She felt that Tarantino was a \"very stand-up guy\"; after visiting the set, she was especially impressed with Robbie, and lent her some of Sharon's jewelry and perfume to wear in the film.<ref name=\"debra-tate\">{{cite news |url=https://www.bustle.com/p/what-does-sharon-tates-family-think-of-once-upon-a-time-in-hollywood-her-sister-has-spoken-out-18226104 |title=What Does Sharon Tate's Family Think Of 'Once Upon a Time in Hollywood'? Her Sister Had Spoken Out |last=Brayson |first=Johnny |accessdate=August 20, 2019 |website=[[Bustle (magazine)|Bustle]] |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190820153629/https://www.bustle.com/p/what-does-sharon-tates-family-think-of-once-upon-a-time-in-hollywood-her-sister-has-spoken-out-18226104 |archive-date=August 20, 2019 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nAfter the premiere, a journalist mentioned to Tarantino that Robbie had few lines. Tarantino responded: \"I reject your hypothesis.\" Robbie elaborated, \"I think the moments on screen show those wonderful sides of [Tate] could be adequately done without speaking.\"<ref>{{cite news |title=Quentin Tarantino Passes on Question About Screen Treatment of Margot Robbie |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/05/22/movies/quentin-tarantino-margot-robbie.html?smtyp=cur&smid=tw-nytimes |date=May 22, 2019 |first=Farah |last=Nayeri |newspaper=[[The New York Times]] |accessdate=August 22, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/film/2019/may/22/once-upon-a-time-in-hollywood-tarantino-lashes-out-at-criticism-over-female-actors |title='I reject your hypothesis': Tarantino lashes out at criticism over female actors |last=Mumford |first=Gwilym |date=May 22, 2019 |work=[[The Guardian]] |access-date=August 21, 2019 |issn=0261-3077 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190821233029/https://www.theguardian.com/film/2019/may/22/once-upon-a-time-in-hollywood-tarantino-lashes-out-at-criticism-over-female-actors |archive-date=August 21, 2019 |url-status=live}}</ref> Tarantino stated: \"I thought it would both be touching and pleasurable and also sad and melancholy to just spend a little time with [Tate], just existing... I wanted you to see Sharon a lot.\"<ref name=Tarantino-Deadline-Interview/>\n\n=== The Manson Family ===\nCharles Manson was convicted of the murders of Tate and four others, despite not being present, due mostly to a theory stating he was trying to instigate an [[apocalypticism|apocalyptic]] race war, in the end leaving only black Muslims and the Manson Family. The black Muslims would eventually look to Manson to lead them. According to some, Manson referred to the race war as [[Helter Skelter (scenario)|Helter Skelter]], getting the name from the [[Helter Skelter (song)|song of the same name]].<ref name=helter-skelter/><ref name=watkins>{{cite book |last=Watkins |first=Paul and Guillermo Soledad |title=My Life With Charles Manson|publisher=Bantam |year=1979 |isbn=978-0-553-12788-1}}</ref> Musician and filmmaker [[Boots Riley]] criticized the film for not portraying Helter Skelter or depicting the Family as [[white supremacy|white supremacists]].<ref>{{cite web |last=Sharf |first=Zack |url=https://www.indiewire.com/2019/08/boots-riley-calls-out-tarantino-manson-family-white-supremacists-1202168736/ |title=Boots Riley Calls Out Tarantino's Hollywood for Not Depicting Manson Family as White Supremacists |website=[[IndieWire]] |access-date=August 30, 2019 |date=August 26, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190829013429/https://www.indiewire.com/2019/08/boots-riley-calls-out-tarantino-manson-family-white-supremacists-1202168736/ |archive-date=August 29, 2019 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nHowever, according to members of the Family, the murders were not committed to start Helter Skelter but as copycat murders of [[Gary Hinman]], to convince police his killer was still at large. Bobby Beausoleil was in jail, charged with the murder. The Family was attempting to get him released.<ref>{{cite news |last=Bardach |first=Ann Louise |url=http://www.bardachreports.com/articles/oa_19811100.htm |title=Jailhouse Interview: Bobby Beausoleil |access-date=August 26, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181119004534/http://www.bardachreports.com/articles/oa_19811100.htm |archive-date=November 19, 2018 |url-status=live}}</ref> According to Jay Sebring's protege and business partner [[Jim Markham]], the murders were about a drug deal gone bad, not a race war. He believes Manson was at Tate's house the day before the murders to sell drugs to Sebring and Voytek Frykowski, which resulted in the two beating Manson up.<ref>{{cite news |last=Siegel |first=Tatiana |url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/manson-family-murder-victims-friend-posits-alternative-motive-1227729 |title=Manson Victim's Friend Posits Alternative Motive: 'I Never Bought Into the Race War Theory' |website=[[The Hollywood Reporter]]|access-date=August 29, 2019 |date=July 30, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190731034053/https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/manson-family-murder-victims-friend-posits-alternative-motive-1227729 |archive-date=July 31, 2019 |url-status=live}}</ref> In his interview with [[Truman Capote]], Beausoleil said, \"They burned people on dope deals. Sharon Tate and that gang.\"<ref>{{cite book |last=Capote |first=Truman |title=A Capote Reader |publisher=[[Random House]]|year=1987 |isbn=978-0-394-55647-5 |url-access=registration |url=https://archive.org/details/capotereader00trum }}</ref>\n\n== ''Bounty Law'' ==\nIn January 2020, Tarantino confirmed that he is creating a real television series titled ''Bounty Law'',<ref name=\":0\"/><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.gq.com.au/entertainment/film-tv/quentin-tarantino-plans-to-turn-fictional-western-bounty-law-into-a-real-series/news-story/a2e81c7d1d29df7e5782eb19e1f2d87b|title=Quentin Tarantino Plans To Turn Fictional Western Bounty Law Into A Real Series|last=Nash|first=Brad|date=2020-01-21|website=GQ|language=en|access-date=2020-02-13}}</ref> stating he has already written five episodes and will direct them.<ref>{{Citation|title=Quentin Tarantino Will Write and Direct Once Upon a Time in Hollywood Spin-Off TV Series Bounty Law - IGN|url=https://www.ign.com/articles/quentin-tarantino-will-write-and-direct-once-upon-a-time-in-hollywood-spin-off-tv-series-bounty-law|language=en|access-date=2020-02-13}}</ref>\n\n== Notes ==\n{{Notelist}}\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist|refs=\n\n<ref name=FirsReportedTHR>{{cite news |last1=Kit |first1=Borys |title=Quentin Tarantino Prepping New Movie Tackling Manson Murders (Exclusive) |url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/heat-vision/quentin-tarantino-prepping-new-movie-tackling-manson-murders-1020165 |accessdate=July 12, 2017 |website=[[The Hollywood Reporter]] |date=July 11, 2017 |language=en|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170712024235/http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/heat-vision/quentin-tarantino-prepping-new-movie-tackling-manson-murders-1020165|archive-date=July 12, 2017|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=FirsReportedDeadline>{{cite news |last1=Fleming Jr. |first1=Mike|title=Quentin Tarantino Met With Margot Robbie For Sharon Tate: Sources |url=https://deadline.com/2017/07/quentin-tarantino-margot-robbie-sharon-tate-manson-murders-brad-pitt-1202127045/ |accessdate=July 12, 2017 |website=[[Deadline Hollywood]] |date=July 11, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170712165131/http://deadline.com/2017/07/quentin-tarantino-margot-robbie-sharon-tate-manson-murders-brad-pitt-1202127045/|archive-date=July 12, 2017|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"HeymanProducer\">{{cite news |last1=Jr |first1=Mike Fleming |title=Bidding Heats on Quentin Tarantino Script As David Heyman Boards As Producer |url=https://deadline.com/2017/11/quentin-tarantino-movie-bidding-david-heyman-producer-margot-robbie-tom-cruise-brad-pitt-leonaro-dicaprio-1202208169/ |accessdate=November 15, 2017 |website=[[Deadline Hollywood]] |date=November 14, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171114232804/http://deadline.com/2017/11/quentin-tarantino-movie-bidding-david-heyman-producer-margot-robbie-tom-cruise-brad-pitt-leonaro-dicaprio-1202208169/|archive-date=November 14, 2017|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"Archive footage\">{{cite web |last=Fretts |first=Bruce |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/07/30/movies/once-upon-a-time-in-hollywood-glossary.html |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20190731040507/https://www.nytimes.com/2019/07/30/movies/once-upon-a-time-in-hollywood-glossary.html |title=A Pop-Culture Glossary for 'Once Upon a Time ... in Hollywood' |website=[[The New York Times]] |date=July 30, 2019 |archivedate=July 31, 2019 |accessdate=August 2, 2019 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"True story characters\">{{cite web |url=https://www.vulture.com/2019/08/the-true-story-of-once-upon-a-time-in-hollywood-characters.html |title=Who's Who in Once Upon a Time in Hollywood: A Character Guide |last=Alter |first=Rebecca |date=August 2, 2019 |website=[[New York (magazine)#Digital expansion and blogs|Vulture]] |access-date= |quote=|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190802193255/https://www.vulture.com/2019/08/the-true-story-of-once-upon-a-time-in-hollywood-characters.html |archive-date=August 2, 2019 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{wikiquote}}\n* {{official website}}\n* {{IMDb title|7131622}}\n\n{{Quentin Tarantino}}\n{{Navboxes\n|title = [[List of accolades received by Once Upon a Time in Hollywood|Awards for ''Once Upon a Time in Hollywood'']]\n|list =\n{{Broadcast Film Critics Association Award for Best Film}}\n{{Golden Globe Award Best Motion Picture Musical or Comedy}}\n{{Satellite Award Best Motion Picture}}\n}}\n{{Manson Family}}\n\n[[Category:2019 films]]\n[[Category:2010s serial killer films]]\n[[Category:2010s comedy-drama films]]\n[[Category:American films]]\n[[Category:American alternate history films]]\n[[Category:American black comedy films]]\n[[Category:American comedy-drama films]]\n[[Category:BAFTA winners (films)]]\n[[Category:Best Musical or Comedy Picture Golden Globe winners]]\n[[Category:Bipolar disorder in fiction]]\n[[Category:British films]]\n[[Category:British alternative history films]]\n[[Category:British black comedy films]]\n[[Category:British comedy-drama films]]\n[[Category:Columbia Pictures films]]\n[[Category:Cultural depictions of actors]]\n[[Category:Cultural depictions of Bruce Lee]]\n[[Category:Cultural depictions of Charles Manson]]\n[[Category:English-language films]]\n[[Category:Films about actors]]\n[[Category:Films about cults]]\n[[Category:Films about Hollywood]]\n[[Category:Films about stunt performers]]\n[[Category:Films directed by Quentin Tarantino]]\n[[Category:Films featuring a Best Supporting Actor Academy Award-winning performance]]\n[[Category:Films featuring a Best Supporting Actor Golden Globe winning performance]]\n[[Category:Films produced by Quentin Tarantino]]\n[[Category:Films set in 1969]]\n[[Category:Films set in Los Angeles]]\n[[Category:Films shot in Los Angeles]]\n[[Category:Heyday Films films]]\n[[Category:Films with screenplays by Quentin Tarantino]]\n[[Category:Films whose art director won the Best Art Direction Academy Award]]\n", "name_user": "Volubilis90", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eFilming and design", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Once_Upon_a_Time_in_Hollywood"}
{"title_page": "Companhia Antarctica Paulista", "text_new": "{{notability}}\n{{Expand Portuguese|date=February 2012|Companhia Antarctica Paulista}}\n{{Expand Spanish}}\n'''Companhia Antarctica Paulista''' was originally a Brazilian beer brewing company producing the ''Antarctica'' beer,<ref>[http://www.ambev.com.br/eng/pro_02_en.htm Antarctica's Family] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080926165940/http://www.ambev.com.br/eng/pro_02_en.htm |date=2008-09-26 }} (Ambev website)</ref> that later started to produce sodas such as the [[Guaran\u00e1 Antarctica]]. For several years its main rival on the beer market was [[Brahma (beer)|Brahma]]. In 1999 the companies merged to form [[Ambev]].\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [http://www.antarctica.com.br Official website]\n\n{{Anheuser-Busch InBev}}\n\n[[Category:Beer in Brazil]]\n[[Category:Defunct companies of Brazil]]\n\n\n{{beer-stub}}\n{{Brazil-company-stub}}\n{{Brazil-cuisine-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{notability}}\n{{Expand Portuguese|date=February 2012|Companhia Antarctica Paulista}}\n{{Expand Portuguese|Spanish}}\n'''Companhia Antarctica Paulista''' was originally a Brazilian beer brewing company producing the ''Antarctica'' beer,<ref>[http://www.ambev.com.br/eng/pro_02_en.htm Antarctica's Family] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080926165940/http://www.ambev.com.br/eng/pro_02_en.htm |date=2008-09-26 }} (Ambev website)</ref> that later started to produce sodas such as the [[Guaran\u00e1 Antarctica]]. For several years its main rival on the beer market was [[Brahma (beer)|Brahma]]. In 1999 the companies merged to form [[Ambev]].\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [http://www.antarctica.com.br Official website]\n\n{{Anheuser-Busch InBev}}\n\n[[Category:Beer in Brazil]]\n[[Category:Defunct companies of Brazil]]\n\n\n{{beer-stub}}\n{{Brazil-company-stub}}\n{{Brazil-cuisine-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Piotrus", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Companhia_Antarctica_Paulista"}
{"title_page": "George French Flowers", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2019}}\n'''George French Flowers''' (1811 \u2013 14 June 1872) was an English composer and musical theorist. He founded a society to promote [[counterpoint]], and a music school for young singers.\n\n==Early career==\nFlowers was born in [[Boston, Lincolnshire]], the fourth son of the Rev. Field Flowers. He studied music in Germany with [[Christian Heinrich Rinck]] and [[Franz Xaver Schnyder von Wartensee]], and went on to graduate BMus from [[Lincoln College, Oxford]], in 1839. In 1865 he obtained DMus.<ref name=\"dnb\">{{cite DNB|first=Louisa M.|last=Middleton|wstitle=Flowers, George French|volume=19|pages=342\u2013343}}</ref>\n\nHe was organist successively at the Chapel of the British Embassy in Paris, at [[St Mark's Church, Myddelton Square]], and at St John's, Paddington.<ref name=\"dnb\"/>\n\n==Contrapuntist's Society and publications==\nFlowers founded the Contrapuntists' Society in 1843.<ref name=\"dnb\"/> In a letter to the ''Musical Examiner'' he wrote that the object of the society \"will be the encouragement and promotion of a more scientific feeling in regard to music than hitherto has existed in England. My notion is ... that, to obtain admittance into the ranks of the society, a candidate shall compose a fugue, of at least one hundred and fifty bars in length, in each bar of which the subject shall be introduced.... A more generally scientific feeling infused among musicians, would go far to gain from them that respect from the members of other professions, which assuredly they do not now enjoy.... It will bring the most accomplished members of the profession together....<ref>{{cite journal |title=Original correspondence|date=23 September 1843|url=http://www.ripmfulltext.org/RIPM/Source/ImageLinks/1445632|journal=The Musical Examiner|issue=47|pages=351\u2013352|url-access=subscription|via=[[RIPM]]}}</ref>\n\nHe was responsible for some contrapuntal and musical reviews in the ''[[Literary Gazette]]'' about that time, and was author of an analysis of [[John Goss (composer)|John Goss]]'s ''An Introduction to Harmony and Thorough-Bass'' in the ''Fine Arts Journal'' (1847, p. 445 et seq.).<ref name=\"dnb\"/>\n\nHis ''Essay on the Construction of Fugue'' appeared in London in 1846.<ref name=\"dnb\"/> It was reviewed in the ''Musical World'': \"Mr. Flowers has fought most manfully in support of counterpoint and fugal compositions.... his object was to draw the attention of students to the works of Sebastian Bach and other classical writers.... The essay under notice is an endeavour on the part of Mr. Flowers to carry his point, by giving examples and musical illustrations. There are 44 pages... containing a vast amount of detail on the subject.... There are several fugues... all worthy of the best attention of students, to whom we recommend the essay.\"<ref>{{cite journal |title=Miscellaneous|date=5 December 1846|url=http://www.ripmfulltext.org/RIPM/Source/ImageLinks/1298147|journal=The Musical World|volume=21|issue=49|page=630|url-access=subscription|via=[[RIPM]]}}</ref>\n\nHis ''Pictorial Representation of the Science of Harmony'', a translation of Basler's ''Reisekarte'', appeared in 1850, and a poem on ''Muscular Vocalisation'' in 1861.<ref name=\"dnb\"/>\n\nFlowers introduced and developed [[Georg Joseph Vogler]]'s system of progressive cadences. He contributed opinions on musical matters for many years to the ''Musical Examiner'' and ''Musical World''.<ref name=\"dnb\"/>\n\n==School of vocalization==\nIn 1850 (''Musical World'', p.&nbsp;650) Flowers announced that he would cultivate and bring forward English vocal talent by means of a British school of vocalization. He later organized concerts for his pupils.<ref name=\"dnb\"/> One of the concerts, in the [[Hanover Square Rooms]], was reviewed in the ''Musical World'' in 1852: \"This gentleman, having devoted his attention to the study of the voice, and the philosophy of the art of singing, has founded a class of vocalization, from which he invites the public to anticipate the most important results. His first practical appeal consisted of an entertainment in which his pupils, under his own direction, performed a selection of music from the most classical master. There were choruses, duets and solos.... Of Mr. Flowers' system we are not yet enabled to give an opinion; but it is fair to state that he has discovered and brought forward some very remarkable voices.\"<ref>{{cite journal |title=Mr. George French Flowers' concert|date=26 June 1852|url=http://www.ripmfulltext.org/RIPM/Source/ImageLinks/1314169|journal=The Musical World|volume=30|issue=26|page=405|url-access=subscription|via=[[RIPM]]}}</ref>\n\nThe school of vocalization did not endure. [[Mrs Howard Paul]] may be cited as having been its most distinguished member.<ref name=\"dnb\"/>\n\n==Compositions==\nHis compositions include organ fugues and choral fugues. His elaborate first mass, of about 1860, probably marks the date of his reception in the church of Rome.<ref name=\"dnb\"/>\n\nFlowers died of cholera on 14 June 1872.<ref name=\"dnb\"/>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n'''Attribution'''\n\n* {{DNB|first=Louisa M.|last=Middleton|wstitle=Flowers, George French|volume=19|pages=342\u2013343}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Flowers, George French}}\n[[Category:1811 births]]\n[[Category:1872 deaths]]\n[[Category:People from Boston, Lincolnshire]]\n[[Category:English male classical composers]]\n[[Category:English classical composers]]\n[[Category:19th-century classical composers]]\n[[Category:19th-century English musicians]]\n[[Category:19th-century British composers]]\n[[Category:19th-century male musicians]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2019}}\n'''George French Flowers''' (1811 \u2013 14 June 1872) was an English composer and musical theorist. He founded a society to promote [[counterpoint]], and a music school for young singers.\n\n==Early career==\nFlowers was born in [[Boston, Lincolnshire]], the fourth son of the Rev. Field Flowers. He studied music in Germany with [[Christian Heinrich Rinck]] and {{Interlanguage link multi|Franz Xaver Schnyder von Wartensee|de}}, and went on to graduate BMus from [[Lincoln College, Oxford]], in 1839. In 1865 he obtained DMus.<ref name=\"dnb\">{{cite DNB|first=Louisa M.|last=Middleton|wstitle=Flowers, George French|volume=19|pages=342\u2013343}}</ref>\n\nHe was organist successively at the Chapel of the British Embassy in Paris, at [[St Mark's Church, Myddelton Square]], and at St John's, Paddington.<ref name=\"dnb\"/>\n\n==Contrapuntist's Society and publications==\nFlowers founded the Contrapuntists' Society in 1843.<ref name=\"dnb\"/> In a letter to the ''Musical Examiner'' he wrote that the object of the society \"will be the encouragement and promotion of a more scientific feeling in regard to music than hitherto has existed in England. My notion is ... that, to obtain admittance into the ranks of the society, a candidate shall compose a fugue, of at least one hundred and fifty bars in length, in each bar of which the subject shall be introduced.... A more generally scientific feeling infused among musicians, would go far to gain from them that respect from the members of other professions, which assuredly they do not now enjoy.... It will bring the most accomplished members of the profession together....<ref>{{cite journal |title=Original correspondence|date=23 September 1843|url=http://www.ripmfulltext.org/RIPM/Source/ImageLinks/1445632|journal=The Musical Examiner|issue=47|pages=351\u2013352|url-access=subscription|via=[[RIPM]]}}</ref>\n\nHe was responsible for some contrapuntal and musical reviews in the ''[[Literary Gazette]]'' about that time, and was author of an analysis of [[John Goss (composer)|John Goss]]'s ''An Introduction to Harmony and Thorough-Bass'' in the ''Fine Arts Journal'' (1847, p. 445 et seq.).<ref name=\"dnb\"/>\n\nHis ''Essay on the Construction of Fugue'' appeared in London in 1846.<ref name=\"dnb\"/> It was reviewed in the ''Musical World'': \"Mr. Flowers has fought most manfully in support of counterpoint and fugal compositions.... his object was to draw the attention of students to the works of Sebastian Bach and other classical writers.... The essay under notice is an endeavour on the part of Mr. Flowers to carry his point, by giving examples and musical illustrations. There are 44 pages... containing a vast amount of detail on the subject.... There are several fugues... all worthy of the best attention of students, to whom we recommend the essay.\"<ref>{{cite journal |title=Miscellaneous|date=5 December 1846|url=http://www.ripmfulltext.org/RIPM/Source/ImageLinks/1298147|journal=The Musical World|volume=21|issue=49|page=630|url-access=subscription|via=[[RIPM]]}}</ref>\n\nHis ''Pictorial Representation of the Science of Harmony'', a translation of Basler's ''Reisekarte'', appeared in 1850, and a poem on ''Muscular Vocalisation'' in 1861.<ref name=\"dnb\"/>\n\nFlowers introduced and developed [[Georg Joseph Vogler]]'s system of progressive cadences. He contributed opinions on musical matters for many years to the ''Musical Examiner'' and ''Musical World''.<ref name=\"dnb\"/>\n\n==School of vocalization==\nIn 1850 (''Musical World'', p.&nbsp;650) Flowers announced that he would cultivate and bring forward English vocal talent by means of a British school of vocalization. He later organized concerts for his pupils.<ref name=\"dnb\"/> One of the concerts, in the [[Hanover Square Rooms]], was reviewed in the ''Musical World'' in 1852: \"This gentleman, having devoted his attention to the study of the voice, and the philosophy of the art of singing, has founded a class of vocalization, from which he invites the public to anticipate the most important results. His first practical appeal consisted of an entertainment in which his pupils, under his own direction, performed a selection of music from the most classical master. There were choruses, duets and solos.... Of Mr. Flowers' system we are not yet enabled to give an opinion; but it is fair to state that he has discovered and brought forward some very remarkable voices.\"<ref>{{cite journal |title=Mr. George French Flowers' concert|date=26 June 1852|url=http://www.ripmfulltext.org/RIPM/Source/ImageLinks/1314169|journal=The Musical World|volume=30|issue=26|page=405|url-access=subscription|via=[[RIPM]]}}</ref>\n\nThe school of vocalization did not endure. [[Mrs Howard Paul]] may be cited as having been its most distinguished member.<ref name=\"dnb\"/>\n\n==Compositions==\nHis compositions include organ fugues and choral fugues. His elaborate first mass, of about 1860, probably marks the date of his reception in the church of Rome.<ref name=\"dnb\"/>\n\nFlowers died of cholera on 14 June 1872.<ref name=\"dnb\"/>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n'''Attribution'''\n\n* {{DNB|first=Louisa M.|last=Middleton|wstitle=Flowers, George French|volume=19|pages=342\u2013343}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Flowers, George French}}\n[[Category:1811 births]]\n[[Category:1872 deaths]]\n[[Category:People from Boston, Lincolnshire]]\n[[Category:English male classical composers]]\n[[Category:English classical composers]]\n[[Category:19th-century classical composers]]\n[[Category:19th-century English musicians]]\n[[Category:19th-century British composers]]\n[[Category:19th-century male musicians]]\n", "name_user": "AtticTapestry", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eEarly career:Link toFranz Xaver Schnyder von Wartensee", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/George_French_Flowers"}
{"title_page": "All the Birds, Singing", "text_new": "{{Infobox book | \n| name          = All the Birds, Singing\n| title_orig    = \n| translator    = \n| image         = All_the_Birds_Singing_book_cover.png\n| caption       = \n| author        = [[Evie Wyld]]\n| illustrator   = \n| cover_artist  = \n| country       = [[Australia]]\n| language      = [[English language|English]]\n| series        = \n| genres         = [[Literary]]\n| publisher     = [[Random House]], Australia\n| release_date  = 2013\n| english_release_date =\n| media_type    = Print ([[Paperback]])\n| pages         = 240 pp\n| isbn          = 9781742757308\n| oclc          = \n| preceded_by   = [[After the Fire, A Still Small Voice]]\n| followed_by   = \n}}\n\n'''''All the Birds, Singing''''' is a 2013 [[novel]] by [[Australian literature|Australian author]] [[Evie Wyld]]. It won the 2014 [[Miles Franklin Award]] and the 2014 [[Encore Award]].\n\n==Description==\nThe novel, using [[reverse chronology]] techniques, tells the story of Jake Whyte who lives on an unnamed island off the coast of Britain tending her flock of sheep with her dog, Dog. Someone, or something, is killing her sheep, and her investigations lead her and the reader back to her time in Australia \"to the 'original sin' that sets everything in motion\".<ref name=clothier >[http://www.huffingtonpost.com/peter-clothier/all-the-birds-singing-boo_b_5589700.html \" ''All the Birds, Singing'': book review\" by Peter Clothier]</ref>\n\n==Awards==\n* 2013 winner [[Encore Award]]\n* 2014 shortlisted [[Queensland Literary Awards]] \u2013 Fiction Book\n* 2014 winner [[Miles Franklin Award]]\n* 2014 shortlisted [[Western Australian Premier's Book Awards]] \u2013 Fiction\n* 2014 longlisted [[Stella Prize]]\n* 2014 longlisted [[Baileys Women's Prize for Fiction]]\n\n==Reviews==\n\n* Peter Clothier in ''The Huffington Post'': \"Wyld's prose is as muscular, sinewy, unsparing as this remarkable character. It has the precision of poetry, but without adornment, unnecessary wordage, or concession to literary conceit. The story, a hero's journey patterned on descent, ordeal--and redemption of a kind--is as compelling as the character who tells it.\"<ref name=clothier />\n* Tim Lewis in ''The Guardian'': \" ''All the Birds, Singing'' should enhance her reputation as one of our most gifted novelists. Her pacing is impeccable and the trickle of information she marshals lends tension and compassion to Jake's troubled, solitary existence.\"<ref>[https://www.theguardian.com/books/2013/jun/30/evie-wyld-birds-singing-review \"All the Birds, Singing by Evie Wyld - review\" by Tim Lewis]</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-ach}}\n{{succession box|title=[[Miles Franklin Award|Miles Franklin Award recipient]]|before=''[[Questions of Travel]]''|after=''[[The Eye of the Sheep]]''|years=[[2014 in literature|2014]]}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:All the Birds Singing}}\n[[Category:2013 Australian novels]]\n[[Category:Miles Franklin Award-winning works]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox book | \n| name          = All the Birds, Singing\n| title_orig    = \n| translator    = \n| image         = All_the_Birds_Singing_book_cover.png\n| caption       = \n| author        = [[Evie Wyld]]\n| illustrator   = \n| cover_artist  = \n| country       = [[Australia]]\n| language      = [[English language|English]]\n| series        = \n| genres         = [[Literary]]\n| publisher     = [[Random House]], Australia\n| release_date  = 2013\n| english_release_date =\n| media_type    = Print ([[Paperback]])\n| pages         = 240 pp\n| isbn          = 9781742757308\n| oclc          = \n| preceded_by   = [[After the Fire, A Still Small Voice]]\n| followed_by   = \n}}\n\n'''''All the Birds, Singing''''' is a 2013 [[novel]] by [[Australian literature|Australian author]] [[Evie Wyld]]. It won the 2014 [[Miles Franklin Award]] and the 2014 [[Encore Award]].\n\n==Description==\nThe novel tells the story of Jake Whyte who lives on an unnamed island off the coast of Britain tending her flock of sheep with her dog, Dog. Someone, or something, is killing her sheep, and her investigations lead her and the reader back to her time in Australia \"to the 'original sin' that sets everything in motion\".<ref name=clothier >[http://www.huffingtonpost.com/peter-clothier/all-the-birds-singing-boo_b_5589700.html \" ''All the Birds, Singing'': book review\" by Peter Clothier]</ref>\n\n==Awards==\n* 2013 winner [[Encore Award]]\n* 2014 shortlisted [[Queensland Literary Awards]] \u2013 Fiction Book\n* 2014 winner [[Miles Franklin Award]]\n* 2014 shortlisted [[Western Australian Premier's Book Awards]] \u2013 Fiction\n* 2014 longlisted [[Stella Prize]]\n* 2014 longlisted [[Baileys Women's Prize for Fiction]]\n\n==Reviews==\n\n* Peter Clothier in ''The Huffington Post'': \"Wyld's prose is as muscular, sinewy, unsparing as this remarkable character. It has the precision of poetry, but without adornment, unnecessary wordage, or concession to literary conceit. The story, a hero's journey patterned on descent, ordeal--and redemption of a kind--is as compelling as the character who tells it.\"<ref name=clothier />\n* Tim Lewis in ''The Guardian'': \" ''All the Birds, Singing'' should enhance her reputation as one of our most gifted novelists. Her pacing is impeccable and the trickle of information she marshals lends tension and compassion to Jake's troubled, solitary existence.\"<ref>[https://www.theguardian.com/books/2013/jun/30/evie-wyld-birds-singing-review \"All the Birds, Singing by Evie Wyld - review\" by Tim Lewis]</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-ach}}\n{{succession box|title=[[Miles Franklin Award|Miles Franklin Award recipient]]|before=''[[Questions of Travel]]''|after=''[[The Eye of the Sheep]]''|years=[[2014 in literature|2014]]}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:All the Birds Singing}}\n[[Category:2013 Australian novels]]\n[[Category:Miles Franklin Award-winning works]]\n", "name_user": "Sfjohna", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eDescription", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/All_the_Birds,_Singing"}
{"title_page": "Marine food web", "text_new": "[[File:Oceanic Food Web.jpg|thumb|upright=2|{{center|The pelagic [[food web]], showing the central involvement of [[marine microorganism]]s in how the ocean imports nutrients from and then exports them back to the atmosphere and ocean floor.}}]]\n{{marine life sidebar}}\n\nCompared to terrestrial environments, marine environments have [[biomass pyramid]]s which are inverted at the base. In particular, the biomass of consumers (copepods, krill, shrimp, forage fish) is larger than the biomass of [[primary producer]]s. This happens because the ocean's primary producers are tiny [[phytoplankton]] which grow and reproduce rapidly, so a small mass can have a fast rate of [[primary production]]. In contrast, terrestrial primary producers, such as [[climax forest|mature forests]], grow and reproduce slowly, so a much larger mass is needed to achieve the same rate of primary production.\n\nBecause of this inversion, it is the [[zooplankton]] that make up most of the marine animal [[Biomass (ecology)|biomass]]. As [[primary consumer]]s, zooplankton  are the crucial link between the primary producers (mainly phytoplankton) and the rest of the marine food web ([[secondary consumer]]s).<ref>U S Department of Energy (2008) [https://public.ornl.gov/site/gallery/detail.cfm?id=326 ''Carbon Cycling and Biosequestration''] page 81, Workshop report DOE/SC-108, U.S. Department of Energy Office of Science.</ref>\n\nIf phytoplankton dies before it is eaten, it descends through the [[euphotic zone]] as part of the [[marine snow]] and settles into the depths of sea. In this way, phytoplankton sequester about 2 billion tons of carbon dioxide into the ocean each year, causing the ocean to become a sink of carbon dioxide holding about 90% of all sequestered carbon.<ref name=\"EarthTimes\">{{cite web|url=http://www.earthtimes.org/scitech/role-marine-plankton-sequestration-carbon/1062/|title=The role of marine plankton in sequestration of carbon |author=Campbell, Mike |date=22 June 2011 |website=EarthTimes|accessdate=22 August 2014}}</ref> The ocean produces about half of the world's oxygen and stores 50 times more carbon dioxide than the atmosphere.<ref>[https://oceanservice.noaa.gov/facts/why-care-about-ocean.html Why should we care about the ocean?] ''NOAA: National Ocean Service''. Updated: 7 January 2020. Retrieved 1 March 2020.</ref>\n\nAn ecosystem cannot be understood without knowledge of how its food web determines the flow of materials and energy. Phytoplankton autotrophically produces biomass by converting [[inorganic compound]]s into [[organic compound|organic]] ones. In this way, phytoplankton functions as the foundation of the marine food web by supporting all other life in the ocean. The second central process in the marine food web is the [[microbial loop]]. This loop degrades [[marine bacteria]] and [[marine archaea|archaea]], [[remineralise]]s organic and inorganic matter, and then recycles the products either within the pelagic food web or by depositing them as sediment on the seafloor.<ref>Heinrichs, M.E., Mori, C. and Dlugosch, L. (2020) [https://link.springer.com/chapter/10.1007/978-3-030-20389-4_15 \"Complex Interactions Between Aquatic Organisms and Their Chemical Environment Elucidated from Different Perspectives\"]. In: Jungblut S., Liebich V., Bode-Dalby M. (Eds) ''YOUMARES 9-The Oceans: Our Research, Our Future '', pages 279\u2013297. Springer. {{doi|10.1007/978-3-030-20389-4_15}}.</ref>\n\n__TOC__\n\n==Trophic levels and food chains==\n{{main|trophic levels}}\n{{marine food chain}}\n\nAll life forms in the sea have the potential to become food for something else. In the ocean, the [[food chain]] typically starts with [[phytoplankton]] and follows a course such as:\n<blockquote>\nPhytoplankton \u2192 herbivorous zooplankton \u2192 carnivorous zooplankton \u2192 [[filter feeder]] \u2192 predatory vertebrate\n</blockquote>\n \n[[File:Grey seal food web.png|thumb|left| {{center|Classic food web for [[grey seal]]s in the [[Baltic Sea]] containing several typical marine food chains <ref>Karlson, A.M., Gorokhova, E., G\u00e5rdmark, A., Pekcan-Hekim, Z., Casini, M., Albertsson, J., Sundelin, B., Karlsson, O. and Bergstr\u00f6m, L. (2020). \"Linking consumer physiological status to food-web structure and prey food value in the Baltic Sea\". ''Ambio'', '''49'''(2): 391\u2013406. {{doi|10.1007/s13280-019-01201-1}}</ref>}}]]\n\n[[Phytoplankton]] are the main [[primary producer]]s at the bottom of the marine food chain. Since they are at the first level in the food chain they are said to have a [[trophic level]] of 1 (from the [[Greek language|Greek]] ''troph\u0113'' meaning food). Phytoplankton use [[photosynthesis]] to convert inorganic carbon into [[protoplasm]]. They are then consumed by microscopic animals called zooplankton.\n\n[[File:Graphical network.png|thumb|upright=1| A food web is network of food chains, and as such can be represented graphically and analysed using techniques from [[network theory]].<ref>Dunne, J.A., Williams, R.J. and Martinez, N.D. (2002) \"Food-web structure and network theory: the role of connectance and size\". ''Proceedings of the National Academy of Sciences'', '''99'''(20): 12917\u201312922. {{doi|10.1073/pnas.192407699}}.</ref><ref>Dunne, J.A. (2006) [https://books.google.com/books?id=qe-04Y2gKscC&pg=PA27&dq=%22The+network+structure+of+food+webs%22&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjO9e-z7dDoAhXCgeYKHcuHDmEQ6AEIMDAB#v=onepage&q=%22The%20network%20structure%20of%20food%20webs%22&f=false \"The network structure of food webs\"]. In: M Pascual and J. A. Dunne (Eds.) ''Ecological networks: linking structure to dynamics in food webs'', pages 27\u201386. {{ISBN|9780199775057}}.</ref>]]\n\n[[Zooplankton]] comprise the second trophic level in the food chain, and include microscopic one-celled organisms called [[protozoa]] as well as small [[crustacean]]s, such as [[copepod]]s and [[krill]], and the [[larva]] of fish, squid, lobsters and crabs.\n\nIn turn, small zooplankton are consumed by both larger predatory zooplankters, such as [[krill]], and by [[forage fish]], which are small, schooling, [[filter feeding|filter-feeding]] fish. This makes up the third trophic level in the food chain.\n\nThe fourth trophic level consists of predatory fish, marine mammals and seabirds that consume forage fish. Examples are [[swordfish]], [[Pinniped|seals]] and [[gannet]]s.\n\nApex predators, such as [[orca]]s, which can consume seals, and [[shortfin mako shark]]s, which can consume swordfish, make up a fifth trophic level. [[Baleen whale]]s can consume zooplankton and krill directly, leading to a food chain with only three or four trophic levels.\n\nIn practice, trophic levels are [[Trophic level#Fractional trophic levels|not always simple integers]] because the same consumer species often feeds across more than one trophic level.<ref>[[William Eugene Odum|Odum, W. E.]]; Heald, E. J. (1975) \"The detritus-based food web of an estuarine mangrove community\". Pages 265\u2013286 in L. E. Cronin, ed. ''Estuarine research''. Vol. 1. Academic Press, New York.</ref><ref>{{Cite journal | doi=10.1038/275542a0 | last1=Pimm | first1=S. L. | last2=Lawton | first2=J. H. | year=1978 | title=On feeding on more than one trophic level | journal=Nature | volume=275 | issue=5680| pages=542\u2013544 }}</ref> For example a large [[marine vertebrate]] may eat smaller predatory fish but may also eat filter feeders; the [[stingray]] eats [[crustacean]]s, but the [[hammerhead shark|hammerhead]] eats both crustaceans and stingrays. Animals can also eat each other; the [[cod]] eats smaller cod as well as [[crayfish]], and crayfish eat cod larvae. The feeding habits of a juvenile animal, and, as a consequence, its trophic level, can change as it grows up.\n\nThe fisheries scientist [[Daniel Pauly]] sets the values of trophic levels to one in plants and detritus, two in herbivores and detritivores (primary consumers), three in secondary consumers, and so on. The definition of the trophic level, TL, for any consumer species is:<ref name=Pauly&Palomares>{{Cite journal | last1=Pauly | first1=D. | last2=Palomares | first2=M. L. | year=2005 | title=Fishing down marine food webs: it is far more pervasive than we thought | url=http://www.seaaroundus.org/Journal/2005/FishingDownMarineFoodWebItisfarMorePervasive.pdf | journal=Bulletin of Marine Science | volume=76 | issue=2 | pages=197\u2013211 | url-status=dead | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130514091440/http://www.seaaroundus.org/Journal/2005/FishingDownMarineFoodWebItisfarMorePervasive.pdf | archivedate=2013-05-14 }}</ref>\n\n:: <math> TL_i=1 + \\sum_j (TL_j \\cdot DC_{ij})\\! </math>\n\nwhere <math>TL_j</math> is the fractional trophic level of the prey ''j'', and <math>DC_{ij}</math> represents the fraction of ''j'' in the diet of ''i''. In the case of marine ecosystems, the trophic level of most fish and other marine consumers takes value between\n2.0 and 5.0. The upper value, 5.0, is unusual, even for large fish,<ref name=r1>{{Cite journal | doi=10.1006/jmsc.1999.0489 | last1=Cort\u00e9s | first1=E. | year=1999 | title=Standardized diet compositions and trophic levels of sharks | journal=ICES J. Mar. Sci. | volume=56 | issue=5| pages=707\u2013717 }}</ref> though it occurs in apex predators of marine mammals, such as polar bears and killer whales.<ref name=Pauly1998b>{{Cite journal | doi=10.1006/jmsc.1997.0280 | last1=Pauly | first1=D. | last2=Trites | first2=A. | last3=Capuli | first3=E. | last4=Christensen | first4=V. | year=1998 | title=Diet composition and trophic levels of marine mammals | journal=ICES J. Mar. Sci. | volume=55 | issue=3| pages=467\u2013481 }}</ref> As a point of contrast, humans have a mean trophic level of about 2.21, about the same as a pig or an anchovy.<ref>[https://phys.org/news/2013-12-human-trophic.html Researchers calculate human trophic level for first time] ''Phys.org ''. 3 December 2013.</ref><ref>Bonhommeau, S., Dubroca, L., Le Pape, O., Barde, J., Kaplan, D.M., Chassot, E. and Nieblas, A.E. (2013) \"Eating up the world\u2019s food web and the human trophic level\". ''Proceedings of the National Academy of Sciences'', '''110'''(51): 20617\u201320620. {{doi|10.1073/pnas.1305827110}}.</ref>\n\n{{clear}}\n\n==Primary producers==\nAt the base of the ocean food web are single-celled algae and other plant-like organisms known as [[phytoplankton]]. Like plants on land, phytoplankton use [[chlorophyll]] and other [[light-harvesting pigment]]s to carry out [[photosynthesis]], absorbing atmospheric carbon dioxide to produce sugars for fuel. Chlorophyll in the water changes the way it reflects and absorbs sunlight, allowing scientists to map the amount and location of phytoplankton. These measurements give scientists valuable insights into the health of the ocean environment, and help scientists study the [[ocean carbon cycle]].<ref name=NASAO2019 />\n\n[[File:Global ocean chlorophyll concentration October 2019.png|thumb|upright=2| {{center|'''Ocean chlorophyll concentration October 2019'''}} Green indicates where there are a lot of phytoplankton, while blue indicates where there are few phytoplankton. \u2013 NASA Earth Observatory 2019.<ref name=NASAO2019>[https://earthobservatory.nasa.gov/global-maps/MY1DMM_CHLORA Chlorophyll] NASA Earth Observatory. Accessed 30 November 2019.</ref>]]\n\n[[File:Prochlorococcus marinus.jpg|thumb|150px|left| {{center|''[[Prochlorococcus]]'', an influential bacterium which produces much of the world's oxygen}}]]\n\nAmong the phytoplankton are members from a phylum of bacteria called [[cyanobacteria]]. Marine cyanobacteria include the smallest known photosynthetic organisms. The smallest of all, ''[[Prochlorococcus]]'', is just 0.5 to 0.8 micrometres across.<ref>{{cite journal | vauthors = Kettler GC, Martiny AC, Huang K, Zucker J, Coleman ML, Rodrigue S, Chen F, Lapidus A, Ferriera S, Johnson J, Steglich C, Church GM, Richardson P, Chisholm SW | title = Patterns and implications of gene gain and loss in the evolution of Prochlorococcus | journal = PLoS Genetics | volume = 3 | issue = 12 | pages = e231 | date = December 2007 | pmid = 18159947 | pmc = 2151091 | doi = 10.1371/journal.pgen.0030231 }}</ref> In terms of individual numbers, ''Prochlorococcus'' is possibly the most plentiful species on Earth: a single millilitre of surface seawater can contain 100,000 cells or more. Worldwide there are estimated to be several [[octillion]] (~10<sup>27</sup>) individuals.<ref>{{Cite APOD |date=27 September 2006 |title=Earth from Saturn |access-date=}}</ref> ''Prochlorococcus'' is ubiquitous between 40\u00b0N and 40\u00b0S and dominates in the [[oligotroph]]ic (nutrient poor) regions of the oceans.<ref>{{cite journal | vauthors = Partensky F, Hess WR, Vaulot D | title = Prochlorococcus, a marine photosynthetic prokaryote of global significance | journal = Microbiology and Molecular Biology Reviews | volume = 63 | issue = 1 | pages = 106\u201327 | date = March 1999 | pmid = 10066832 | pmc = 98958 }}</ref> The bacterium accounts for about 20% of the oxygen in the Earth's atmosphere.<ref name=\"npr\">{{cite web|url=https://www.npr.org/templates/story/story.php?storyId=91448837|title=The Most Important Microbe You've Never Heard Of|author=|date=|website=npr.org}}</ref>\n\nIn oceans, most [[primary production]] is performed by [[algae]]. This is a contrast to on land, where most primary production is performed by [[vascular plants]]. Algae ranges from single floating cells to attached [[seaweeds]], while vascular plants are represented in the ocean by groups such as the [[seagrass]]es. Larger producers, such as seagrasses and seaweeds, are mostly confined to the [[littoral]] zone and shallow waters, where they [[holdfast|attach]] to the underlying substrate and are still within the [[photic zone]]. But most of the primary production by algae is performed by the phytoplankton.\n\n{{clear right}}\n\n<gallery mode=packed heights=138px style=\"float:right;\" caption=\"Phytoplankton form the base of the ocean foodchain\">\nFile:phytopla.gif|Phytoplankton\nFile:Noctiluca scintillans unica.jpg|Dinoflagellate\nFile:Diatoms through the microscope.jpg|Diatoms\n</gallery>\n\nThus, in ocean environments, the first bottom trophic level is occupied principally by [[phytoplankton]], microscopic drifting organisms, mostly [[one-celled]] [[algae]], that float in the sea. Most phytoplankton are too small to be seen individually with the [[naked eye|unaided eye]]. They can appear as a green discoloration of the water when they are present in high enough numbers. Since they increase their biomass mostly through photosynthesis they live in the sun-lit surface layer ([[Photic zone|euphotic zone]]) of the sea.\n\nThe most important groups of phytoplankton include the [[diatom]]s and [[dinoflagellate]]s. Diatoms are especially important in oceans, where according to some estimates they contribute up to 45% of the total ocean's primary production.<ref name=mann99>{{cite journal | doi = 10.2216/i0031-8884-38-6-437.1 | last1 = Mann | first1 = D. G. | year = 1999 | title = The species concept in diatoms | journal = Phycologia | volume = 38 | issue =  | pages = 437\u2013495 }}</ref> Diatoms are usually [[microscope|microscopic]], although some species can reach up to 2 millimetres in length.\n\n==Primary consumers==\nThe second trophic level ([[primary consumer]]s) is occupied by [[zooplankton]] which feed off the [[phytoplankton]]. Together with the phytoplankton, they form the base of the food pyramid that supports most of the world's great fishing grounds. Zooplankton are tiny animals found with the phytoplankton in [[ocean]]ic [[photic zone|surface waters]], and include tiny [[crustacean]]s, and fish larvae and [[spawn (biology)#Fry|fry]] (recently hatched fish). Most zooplankton are [[filter feeder]]s, and they use appendages to strain the phytoplankton in the water. Some larger zooplankton also feed on smaller zooplankton. Some zooplankton can jump about a bit to avoid predators, but they can't really swim. Like phytoplankton, they float with the currents, tides and winds instead. Zooplanktons can reproduce rapidly, their populations can increase up to thirty percent a day under favourable conditions. Many live short and productive lives and reach maturity quickly.\n\n<gallery mode=packed heights=160px, style=\"float:right;\" caption=\"Zooplankton form a second level in the ocean food chain\">\nFile:Tomopteriskils.jpg|Segmented worm\nFile:Hyperia.jpg|Tiny shrimp-like crustaceans\nFile:Squidu.jpg|Juvenile planktonic squid\n</gallery>\n\nParticularly important groups of zooplankton are the [[copepod]]s and [[krill]]. [[Copepod]]s are a group of small [[crustacean]]s found in ocean and [[fresh water|freshwater]] [[habitat (ecology)|habitats]]. They are the biggest source of protein in the sea,<ref>[http://www.uni-oldenburg.de/zoomorphology/Biology.html Biology of Copepods] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090101205840/http://www.uni-oldenburg.de/zoomorphology/Biology.html |date=2009-01-01 }} at [[Carl von Ossietzky University of Oldenburg]]</ref> and are important prey for forage fish. [[Krill]] constitute the next biggest source of protein. Krill are particularly large predator zooplankton which feed on smaller zooplankton. This means they really belong to the third trophic level, secondary consumers, along with the forage fish.\n\nTogether, [[phytoplankton]] and [[zooplankton]] make up most of the [[plankton]] in the sea. Plankton is the term applied to any small drifting [[organism]]s that float in the sea ([[Greek language|Greek]] ''planktos'' = wanderer or drifter). By definition, organisms classified as plankton are unable to swim against ocean currents; they cannot resist the ambient current and control their position. In ocean environments, the first two trophic levels are occupied mainly by [[plankton]]. Plankton are divided into producers and consumers. The producers are the phytoplankton (Greek ''phyton'' = plant) and the consumers, who eat the phytoplankton, are the zooplankton (Greek ''zoon'' = animal).\n\n[[File:Jellyfish swarm.jpg|thumb|upright=1.15| Jellyfish are easy to capture and digest and may be more important as food sources than was previously thought.<ref name=Hays2018 />]]\n\nTraditionally [[jellyfish]] have been viewed as trophic dead ends, minor players in the marine food web, gelatinous organisms with a [[body plan]] largely based on water that offers little nutritional value for other organisms apart from a few specialised predators such as the [[ocean sunfish]] and the [[leatherback sea turtle]].<ref name=Hamilton2016>Hamilton, G. (2016) [https://www.nature.com/news/polopoly_fs/1.19613!/menu/main/topColumns/topLeftColumn/pdf/531432a.pdf \"The secret lives of jellyfish: long regarded as minor players in ocean ecology, jellyfish are actually important parts of the marine food web\"]. ''Nature'', '''531'''(7595): 432-435. {{doi|10.1038/531432a}}</ref><ref name=Hays2018>Hays, G.C., Doyle, T.K. and Houghton, J.D. (2018) \"A paradigm shift in the trophic importance of jellyfish?\" ''Trends in ecology & evolution'', '''33'''(11): 874-884. {{doi|10.1016/j.tree.2018.09.001}}</ref> That view has recently been challenged. Jellyfish, and more generally [[gelatinous zooplankton]] which include [[salp]]s and [[ctenophore]]s, are very diverse, fragile with no hard parts, difficult to see and monitor, subject to rapid population swings and often live inconveniently far from shore or deep in the ocean. It is difficult for scientists to detect and analyse jellyfish in the guts of predators, since they turn to mush when eaten and are rapidly digested.<ref name=Hamilton2016/> But jellyfish bloom in vast numbers, and it has been shown they form major components in the diets of [[tuna]], [[spearfish]] and [[swordfish]] as well as various birds and invertebrates such as [[octopus]], [[sea cucumber]]s, [[crab]]s and [[amphipod]]s.<ref>Cardona, L., De Quevedo, I.\u00c1., Borrell, A. and Aguilar, A. (2012) \"Massive consumption of gelatinous plankton by Mediterranean apex predators\". ''PloS one'', '''7'''(3): e31329. {{doi|10.1371/journal.pone.0031329}}</ref><ref name=Hays2018 /> \"Despite their low energy density, the contribution of jellyfish to the energy budgets of predators may be much greater than assumed because of rapid digestion, low capture costs, availability, and selective feeding on the more energy-rich components. Feeding on jellyfish may make marine predators susceptible to ingestion of plastics.\"<ref name=Hays2018 />\n\n==Higher order consumers==\n\n; Marine invertebrates\n\n; Fish\n[[File:Schooling fish.jpg|thumb|upright=1.84| {{center|Predator fish sizing up [[Shoaling and schooling|schooling]] forage fish}}]]\n\n* [[Forage fish]] <ref>[https://www.npr.org/sections/thesalt/2016/04/07/473293477/tiny-forage-fish-at-bottom-of-marine-food-chain-get-new-protections Tiny Forage Fish At Bottom Of Marine Food Web Get New Protections] ''[[National Public Radio]]'', 7 April 2016.</ref>\n\nForage fish occupy central positions in the ocean [[food web]]s. The organisms it eats are at a lower [[trophic level]], and the organisms that eat it are at a higher trophic level. Forage fish occupy middle levels in the food web, serving as a dominant prey to higher level fish, seabirds and mammals.\n\n* [[Predator fish]]\n\n* [[Ground fish]]\n\n; Other marine vertebrates\nIn 2010 researchers found whales carry nutrients from the depths of the ocean back to the surface using a process they called the [[whale pump]].<ref name=\"PLOSOne\">{{cite journal|authors=Roman, J. & McCarthy, J.J.|year= 2010|title=The Whale Pump: Marine Mammals Enhance Primary Productivity in a Coastal Basin|journal=PLoS ONE|volume=5|issue=10|id=e13255|doi=10.1371/journal.pone.0013255|pages=e13255|pmid=20949007|pmc=2952594|bibcode= 2010PLoSO...513255R}}</ref> Whales feed at deeper levels in the ocean where [[krill]] is found, but return regularly to the surface to breathe. There  whales [[Whale faeces|defecate a liquid]] rich in nitrogen and iron. Instead of sinking, the liquid stays at the surface where [[phytoplankton]] consume it. In the Gulf of Maine the whale pump provides more nitrogen than the rivers.<ref name=\"ScienceDaily\">{{cite web|url=https://www.sciencedaily.com/releases/2010/10/101012101255.htm|title=Whale poop pumps up ocean health|author=Brown, Joshua E.|date=12 Oct 2010|website=Science Daily|accessdate=18 August 2014}}</ref>\n\n{{clear right}}\n\n<gallery mode=packed heights=160px style=\"float:right;\">\nFile:Humpback lunge feeding.jpg|[[Humpback whale]]s [[lunge feeding|lunge from below]] to feed on forage fish\nFile:Gannet (Morus bassana), Belmont - geograph.org.uk - 529175.jpg|thumb|[[Northern gannet|Gannets]] [[plunge dive]] from above to catch forage fish\n</gallery>\n\n<gallery mode=packed heights=220px style=\"float:left;\">\nFile:WhalePump.jpg| {{center|Whale pump [[nutrient cycle]]}}\n</gallery>\n\n{{clear}}\n\n==Microorganisms==\n[[File:Microorganisms in a drop of seawater.jpg|thumb| On average there are \"more than one million microbial cells in every drop of seawater, and their collective metabolisms not only recycle nutrients that can then be used by larger organisms but also catalyze key chemical transformations that maintain Earth\u2019s habitability\".<ref>Raina, J.B. (2018) \"The life aquatic at the microscale\". ''mSystems'', '''3'''(2): e00150-17. {{doi|10.1128/mSystems.00150-17}}.</ref>]]\n{{see also|marine microorganisms|microbial loop|microbial food web|viral shunt}}\n\nThere has been increasing recognition in recent years that [[marine microorganism]]s play much bigger roles in marine ecosystems than was previously thought. Developments in [[metagenomics]] gives researchers an ability to reveal previously hidden diversities of microscopic life, offering a powerful lens for viewing the microbial world and the potential to revolutionise understanding of the living world.<ref name= MarcoD2011>{{cite book| editor = Marco, D| year=2011| title=Metagenomics: Current Innovations and Future Trends| publisher=[[Caister Academic Press]]| isbn= 978-1-904455-87-5}}</ref> [[DNA barcoding in diet assessment|Metabarcoding dietary analysis]] techniques are being used to reconstruct food webs at higher levels of taxonomic resolution and are revealing deeper complexities in the web of interactions.<ref name=Roslin2016 />\n\n[[Microorganism]]s play key roles in marine food webs. The [[viral shunt]] pathway is a mechanism that prevents marine microbial [[particulate organic matter]] (POM) from migrating up [[trophic level]]s by recycling them into [[dissolved organic matter]] (DOM), which can be readily taken up by microorganisms.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Wilhelm|first=Steven W.|last2=Suttle|first2=Curtis A.|date=1999|title=Viruses and Nutrient Cycles in the Sea|journal=BioScience|volume=49|issue=10|pages=781\u2013788|doi=10.2307/1313569|issn=1525-3244|jstor=1313569}}</ref> Viral shunting helps maintain diversity within the microbial ecosystem by preventing a single species of marine microbe from dominating the micro-environment.<ref>Weinbauer, Markus G., et al. \"Synergistic and antagonistic effects of viral lysis and protistan grazing on bacterial biomass, production and diversity.\" ''Environmental Microbiology'' 9.3 (2007): 777-788.</ref> The DOM recycled by the viral shunt pathway is comparable to the amount generated by the other main sources of marine DOM.<ref>Robinson, Carol, and Nagappa Ramaiah. \"Microbial heterotrophic metabolic rates constrain the microbial carbon pump.\" The American Association for the Advancement of Science, 2011.</ref>\n\n[[File:POC.png|thumb|upright=1.7|left| {{center|Ocean particulate organic matter (POM)<br />as [[Moderate-Resolution Imaging Spectroradiometer|imaged by a satellite]] in 2011}}]]\n\n[[File:Cycling of marine phytoplankton.png|thumb|upright=1.7| Cycling of marine phytoplankton. Phytoplankton live in the photic zone of the ocean, where photosynthesis is possible. During photosynthesis, they assimilate carbon dioxide and release oxygen. If solar radiation is too high, phytoplankton may fall victim to photodegradation. For growth, phytoplankton cells depend on nutrients, which enter the ocean by rivers, continental weathering, and glacial ice meltwater on the poles. Phytoplankton release dissolved organic carbon (DOC) into the ocean. Since phytoplankton are the basis of marine food webs, they serve as prey for zooplankton, fish larvae and other heterotrophic organisms. They can also be degraded by bacteria or by viral lysis. Although some phytoplankton cells, such as dinoflagellates, are able to migrate vertically, they are still incapable of actively moving against currents, so they slowly sink and ultimately fertilize the seafloor with dead cells and detritus.<ref>K\u00e4se L, Geuer JK. (2018) [https://link.springer.com/chapter/10.1007/978-3-319-93284-2_5 \"Phytoplankton Responses to Marine Climate Change \u2013 An Introduction\"].  In Jungblut S., Liebich V., Bode M. (Eds) ''YOUMARES 8\u2013Oceans Across Boundaries: Learning from each other'', pages 55\u201372, Springer. {{doi|10.1007/978-3-319-93284-2_5}}. [[File:CC-BY icon.svg|50px]] Material was copied from this source, which is available under a [https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by/4.0/ Creative Commons Attribution 4.0 International License].</ref>]]\n\n{{multiple image\n | align = left\n | direction = horizontal\n | header            = DOM, POM and the viral shunt\n | header_align      = <!-- left/right/center -->\n | footer            = \n | footer_align      = <!-- left/right/center -->\n | footer_background = \n | background color  = \n | width1    = 315\n | image1    = Marine connections between the living and the nonliving.png\n | alt1      = \n | caption1  = Connections between the different compartments of the living (bacteria/viruses and phyto\u2212/zooplankton) and the nonliving (DOM/POM and inorganic matter) environment <ref>Heinrichs, M.E., Mori, C. and Dlugosch, L. (2020) \"Complex Interactions Between Aquatic Organisms and Their Chemical Environment Elucidated from Different Perspectives\". In: ''YOUMARES 9-The Oceans: Our Research, Our Future '', pages 279\u2013297. Springer. {{doi|10.1007/978-3-030-20389-4_15}}.</ref>\n | width2    = 230\n | image2    = Viral shunt.jpg\n | alt2      = \n | caption2  = The [[viral shunt pathway]] facilitates the flow of [[dissolved organic matter]] (DOM) and [[particulate organic matter]] (POM) through the marine food web\n}}\n\n{{clear}}\n\n==Fungi==\n{{main|Marine fungi}}\n[[File:Roles of fungi in the marine carbon cycle.jpg|thumb|upright=2| {{center| Roles of fungi in the marine carbon cycle <ref>Gutierrez MH, Jara AM, Pantoja S (2016) \"Fungal parasites infect marine diatoms in the upwelling ecosystem of the Humboldt current system off central Chile\". ''Environ Microbiol'', '''18'''(5): 1646\u20131653. {{doi|10.1111/1462-2920.13257}}.</ref>}}]]\n\n* Amend, A., Burgaud, G., Cunliffe, M., Edgcomb, V.P., Ettinger, C.L., Guti\u00e9rrez, M.H., Heitman, J., Hom, E.F., Ianiri, G., Jones, A.C. and Kagami, M. (2019) [https://mbio.asm.org/content/10/2/e01189-18 \"Fungi in the marine environment: Open questions and unsolved problems\"]. ''MBio'', '''10'''(2): e01189-18. {{doi|10.1128/mBio.01189-18}}.\n\n{{clear}}\n\n==Coastal webs==\n{{multiple image\n | align = right\n | direction = horizontal\n | width     = 250\n | header            = Continental shelves\n | header_align      = <!-- left/right/center -->\n | image1    = R\u00e9seau trophique en eaux c\u00f4ti\u00e8res.jpg\n | alt1      = \n | caption1  = Typical food web on a continental shelf\n}}\n\n* Byrnes, J.E., Reynolds, P.L. and Stachowicz, J.J. (2007) \"Invasions and extinctions reshape coastal marine food webs\". ''PloS one'', '''2'''(3): e295. {{doi|10.1371/journal.pone.0000295}}\n\n{{multiple image\n | align = left\n | direction = horizontal\n | width     = 550\n | header            = Chesapeake waterbird food web\n | header_align      = <!-- left/right/center -->\n | image1    = Chesapeake Waterbird Food Web.jpg\n | alt1      = \n | caption1  = {{center|Waterbird food web in [[Chesapeake Bay]]}} Generalized food web for some of the major waterbirds that frequent the Chesapeake Bay. Food sources and habitats of waterbirds are affected by multiple factors, including [[Introduced species|exotic]] and [[invasive species]].<ref>US Geological Survey (USGS). [http://pubs.usgs.gov/circ/circ1316/html/circ1316chap14.html \"Chapter 14: Changes in Food and Habitats of Waterbirds.\" Figure 14.1.] ''Synthesis of U.S. Geological Survey Science for the Chesapeake Bay Ecosystem and Implications for Environmental Management.'' USGS Circular 1316. {{PD-notice}}</ref><ref>Perry, M.C., Osenton, P.C., Wells-Berlin, A.M., and Kidwell, D.M., 2005, Food selection among Atlantic Coast sea ducks in relation to historic food habits, [abs.] in Perry, M.C., Second North American Sea Duck Conference, November 7\u201311, 2005, Annapolis, Maryland, Program and Abstracts, USGS Patuxent Wildlife Research Center, Maryland, 123 p. (p. 105).</ref>\n}}\n\n{{multiple image\n | align = right\n | direction = horizontal\n | width     = 250\n | header            = Puffin and herring food web\n | header_align      = <!-- left/right/center -->\n | image1    = Atlantic puffin and herring food chain.png\n | alt1      = \n | caption1  = [[Machias Seal Island]] [[Atlantic puffin]] and [[Atlantic herring]] food web. Increasing line thickness relates to higher frequency of occurrence in adult (blue), chick (green), and herring (purple) diet.<ref>Bowser, A.K., Diamond, A.W. and Addison, J.A. (2013) \"From puffins to plankton: a DNA-based analysis of a seabird food chain in the northern Gulf of Maine\". ''PLoS One'', '''8'''(12): e83152. {{doi|10.1371/journal.pone.0083152}}</ref>\n}}\n\n{{clear}}\n\n{{multiple image\n | align = right\n | direction = horizontal\n | width     = 440\n | header            = Seabird colonies\n | header_align      = <!-- left/right/center -->\n | image1    = Seabird ornitheutrophication coupling.png\n | alt1      = \n | caption1  = [[Seabird#Breeding and colonies|Seabird colonies]] are nutrient hot spots, especially, for nitrogen and phosphorus.<ref name=Otero2018>Otero, X.L., De La Pe\u00f1a-Lastra, S., P\u00e9rez-Alberti, A., Ferreira, T.O. and Huerta-Diaz, M.A. (2018) \"Seabird colonies as important global drivers in the nitrogen and phosphorus cycles\". ''Nature communications'', '''9'''(1): 1\u20138. {{doi|10.1038/s41467-017-02446-8}}. Material was copied from this source, which is available under a [https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by/4.0/ Creative Commons Attribution 4.0 International License].</ref>\n}}\n\nThe key nutrients determining [[eutrophication]] are nitrogen in coastal waters and phosphorus in lakes. Both are found in high concentrations in [[guano]] (seabird feces), which acts as a fertilizer for the surrounding ocean or an adjacent lake. [[Uric acid]] is the dominant nitrogen compound, and during its mineralization different nitrogen forms are produced. In the diagram on the right: (1) ammonification produces NH3 and NH4+, and (2) nitrification produces NO3\u2212 by NH4+ oxidation. Under the alkaline conditions, typical of the seabird feces, the NH3 is rapidly volatised (3) and transformed to NH4+, which is transported out of the colony, and through wet-deposition exported to distant ecosystems, which are eutrophised (4). The phosphorus cycle is simpler and has reduced mobility. This element is found in a number of chemical forms in the seabird fecal material, but the most mobile and bioavailable is [[orthophosphate]], which can be [[Leaching (chemistry)|leached]] by subterranean or superficial waters (5).<ref name=Otero2018 />\n\n\n\n\n\n\n{{multiple image\n | align = left\n | direction = horizontal\n | width     = 550\n | header            = Estuaries\n | header_align      = <!-- left/right/center -->\n | image1    = Food web of the Venice lagoon.png\n | alt1      = \n | caption1  = Example food web from an [[estuary]], the [[Venice Lagoon]], involving 27 nodes or functional groups. Colors of flows depict different fishing target (artisanal fisheries in blue, and clam fishery in red) and non-target species (for clam harvesting, in green). <ref>Heymans, J.J., Coll, M., Libralato, S., Morissette, L. and Christensen, V. (2014). \"Global patterns in ecological indicators of marine food webs: a modelling approach\". ''PloS one'', '''9'''(4). doi:10.1371/journal.pone.0095845.</ref><ref>Pranovi, F., Libralato, S., Raicevich, S., Granzotto, A., Pastres, R. and Giovanardi, O. (2003). \"Mechanical clam dredging in Venice lagoon: ecosystem effects evaluated with a trophic mass-balance model\". ''Marine Biology'', '''143'''(2): 393\u2013403. doi:10.1007/s00227-003-1072-1.</ref>\n}}\n\n\n{{multiple image\n | align = right\n | direction = horizontal\n | width     = 440\n | header            = Filter feeding bivalves\n | image1    = Nutrient extraction services provided by bivalves.png\n | alt1      = \n | caption1  = [[Ecosystem services]] provided by [[filter feeding]] bivalves often resident in estuaries, in the form of [[Nutrient cycle|nutrient extraction]] from phytoplankton. [[Blue mussel]]s are used in the example but other bivalves like [[oyster]]s also provide these nutrient extraction services.<ref name=Petersen2019>Petersen, J.K., Holmer, M., Termansen, M. and Hasler, B. (2019) \"Nutrient extraction through bivalves\". In: Smaal A., Ferreira J., Grant J., Petersen J., Strand \u00d8. (eds) ''Goods and Services of Marine Bivalves'', pages 179\u2013208. Springer. {{doi|10.1007/978-3-319-96776-9_10}}. {{ISBN|9783319967769}}</ref>\n}}\n\n{{clear}}\n\n{{multiple image\n | align = right\n | direction = horizontal\n | width     = 440\n | header            = Coral reefs\n | header_align      = <!-- left/right/center -->\n | image1    = Food web reconstruction by DNA barcodes.jpg\n | alt1      = \n | caption1  = Food web reconstruction by [[DNA barcoding|DNA barcodes]] at the coral reef of [[Moorea]], French Polynesia. Dietary partitioning among three predatory fish species as detected using [[DNA barcoding in diet assessment|metabarcoding dietary analysis]]. The taxonomic resolution provided by the metabarcoding approach highlights a complex interaction web and demonstrates that levels of trophic partitioning among [[coral reef fishes]] have likely been underestimated.<ref name=Roslin2016>Roslin, T. and Majaneva, S. (2016) \"The use of DNA barcodes in food web construction\u2014terrestrial and aquatic ecologists unite!\". ''Genome'', '''59'''(9): 603\u2013628. {{doi|10.1139/gen-2015-0229}}.</ref><ref>Leray M, Meyer CP, Mills SC. (2015) \"Metabarcoding dietary analysis of coral dwelling predatory fish demonstrates the minor contribution of coral mutualists to their highly partitioned, generalist diet\". ''PeerJ'', '''3''': e1047. {{doi|10.7717/peerj.1047}}.</ref>\n}}\n\n[[DNA barcoding]] can be used to construct food web structures with better taxonomic resolution at the web nodes. This provides more specific species identification and greater clarity about exactly who eats whom. \"DNA barcodes and DNA information may allow new approaches to the construction of larger interaction webs, and overcome some hurdles to achieving adequate sample size\".<ref name=Roslin2016 />\n\n{{multiple image\n | align = left\n | direction = horizontal\n | width     = 300\n | header            = Seagrass meadows\n | header_align      = <!-- left/right/center -->\n | image1    = Visualization of an aggregation of seagrass food webs.png\n | alt1      = \n | caption1  = Cumulative visualization of a number of seagrass food webs from different regions and with different eutrophication levels Different coloured dots represent trophic groups from different trophic levels with black \u200a=\u200a primary producers, dark to light grey \u200a=\u200a secondary producers, and the lightest grey being top predators. The grey links represent feeding links.<ref>Coll, M., Schmidt, A., Romanuk, T. and Lotze, H.K. (2011). \"Food-web structure of seagrass communities across different spatial scales and human impacts\". ''PloS ONE'', '''6'''(7): e22591. {{doi|10.1371/journal.pone.0022591}}. [[File:CC-BY icon.svg|50px]] Material was copied from this source, which is available under a [https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by/4.0/ Creative Commons Attribution 4.0 International License].</ref>\n}}\n\n\n\n* [[Kelp forest]]s\n\n{{clear}}\n\n==Deep ocean webs==\n; The mesopelagic web\n<gallery mode=packed heights=360px style=float:right; caption=\"Mesopelagic food web\">\nFile:Mesopelagic species impact on global carbon budget.png| Impact of  mesopelagic species on the global carbon budget <ref>Wang, F., Wu, Y., Chen, Z., Zhang, G., Zhang, J., Zheng, S. and Kattner, G. (2019) \"Trophic interactions of mesopelagic fishes in the South China Sea illustrated by stable isotopes and fatty acids\". ''Frontiers in Marine Science'', '''5''': 522. {{doi|10.3389/fmars.2018.00522}}.</ref><br /><small>DVM = diel vertical migration &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; NM = non-migration</small>\n</gallery>\n\nScientists are starting to explore in more detail the largely unknown twilight zone of the [[mesopelagic]], 200 to 1,000 metres deep. This layer is responsible for removing about 4 billion tonnes of carbon dioxide from the atmosphere each year. The mesopelagic layer is inhabited by most of the marine fish [[Biomass (ecology)|biomass]].<ref name=Tollefson2020>Tollefson, Jeff (27 February 2020) [https://www.nature.com/articles/d41586-020-00520-8?utm_source=Nature+Briefing&utm_campaign=20a3502704-briefing-dy-20200228&utm_medium=email&utm_term=0_c9dfd39373-20a3502704-43400965 Enter the twilight zone: scientists dive into the oceans\u2019 mysterious middle] ''Nature News''. {{doi|10.1038/d41586-020-00520-8}}.</ref>\n\n<gallery mode=packed heights=180px style=float:left;>\nFile:Sigmops bathyphilus.jpg| Mesopelagic [[bristlemouth]]s may be the most abundant vertebrates on the planet, though little is known about them.<ref name=Tollefson2020 />\nFile:Bathykorus bouilloni.jpg| [[Gelatinous zooplankton|Gelatinous predators]] like this [[narcomedusan]] consume the greatest diversity of mesopelagic prey\n</gallery>\n\n{{clear left}}\n\n* [https://theconversation.com/fish-in-the-twilight-cast-new-light-on-ocean-ecosystem-22987 Fish in the twilight cast new light on ocean ecosystem] ''The Conversation'', 10 February 2014.\n* [https://www.nytimes.com/2015/06/30/science/bristlemouth-ocean-deep-sea-cyclothone.html An Ocean Mystery in the Trillions] ''The New York Times'', 29 June 2015.\n* Mesopelagic fishes - [[Malaspina Expedition 2010|Malaspina circumnavigation expedition]] of 2010.<ref>Irigoien, X., Klevjer, T.A., R\u00f8stad, A., Martinez, U., Boyra, G., Acu\u00f1a, J.L., Bode, A., Echevarria, F., Gonzalez-Gordillo, J.I., Hernandez-Leon, S. and Agusti, S. (2014) \"Large mesopelagic fishes biomass and trophic efficiency in the open ocean\". ''Nature communications'', '''5''': 3271. {{doi|10.1038/ncomms4271}}</ref><ref>[https://www.eurekalert.org/pub_releases/2014-02/snrc-fbi020614.php Fish biomass in the ocean is 10 times higher than estimated] ''EurekAlert'', 7 February 2014.</ref>\n\nAccording to a 2017 study, [[narcomedusae]] consume the greatest diversity of mesopelagic prey, followed by [[physonect]] [[siphonophore]]s, [[ctenophore]]s and [[cephalopod]]s. The importance of the so called \"jelly web\" is only beginning to be understood, but it seems medusae, ctenophores and siphonophores can be key predators in deep pelagic food webs with ecological impacts similar to predator fish and squid. Traditionally gelatinous predators were thought ineffectual providers of marine trophic pathways, but they appear to have substantial and integral roles in deep pelagic food webs.<ref>Choy, C.A., Haddock, S.H. and Robison, B.H. (2017) \"Deep pelagic food web structure as revealed by in situ feeding observations\". ''Proceedings of the Royal Society B: Biological Sciences'', '''284'''(1868): 20172116. {{doi|10.1098/rspb.2017.2116}}.</ref> [[Diel vertical migration]], an important  active transport mechanism, allows [[mesozooplankton]] to sequester carbon dioxide from the atmosphere as well as supply carbon needs for other mesopelagic organisms.<ref>Kelly, T.B., Davison, P.C., Goericke, R., Landry, M.R., Ohman, M. and Stukel, M.R. (2019) \"The importance of mesozooplankton diel vertical migration for sustaining a mesopelagic food web\". ''Frontiers in Marine Science'', '''6''': 508. {{doi|10.3389/fmars.2019.00508}}.</ref>\n\n; The deep pelagic web\n[[File:An in situ perspective of a deep pelagic food web.jpg|thumb|upright=2|right| An ''in situ'' perspective of a deep pelagic food web derived from ROV-based observations of feeding, as represented by 20 broad taxonomic groupings. The linkages between predator to prey are coloured according to predator group origin, and loops indicate within-group feeding. The thickness of the lines or edges connecting food web components is scaled to the log of the number of unique ROV feeding observations across the years 1991\u20132016 between the two groups of animals. The different groups have eight colour-coded types according to main animal types as indicated by the legend and defined here: red, cephalopods; orange, crustaceans; light green, fish; dark green, medusa; purple, siphonophores; blue, ctenophores and grey, all other animals. In this plot, the vertical axis does not correspond to trophic level, because this metric is not readily estimated for all members.<ref>Choy, C.A., Haddock, S.H. and Robison, B.H. (2017) \"Deep pelagic food web structure as revealed by ''in situ'' feeding observations\". ''Proceedings of the Royal Society B: Biological Sciences'', '''284'''(1868): 20172116. {{doi|10.1098/rspb.2017.2116}}. [[File:CC-BY icon.svg|50px]] Material was copied from this source, which is available under a [https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by/4.0/ Creative Commons Attribution 4.0 International License].</ref>]]\n\n[[File:Role of micronekton in pelagic food webs.png|thumb|upright=2|left| Oceanic pelagic food web showing energy flow from micronekton to top predators. Line thickness is scaled to the proportion in the diet.<ref>Choy, C.A., Wabnitz, C.C., Weijerman, M., Woodworth-Jefcoats, P.A. and Polovina, J.J. (2016) \"Finding the way to the top: how the composition of oceanic mid-trophic micronekton groups determines apex predator biomass in the central North Pacific\". ''Marine Ecology Progress Series'', '''549''': 9\u201325. {{doi|10.3354/meps11680}}.</ref>]]\n\n{{clear left}}\n\n; Seeps and vents\n[[File:Hydrothermal Vents and Methane Seeps.jpg|thumb|left|upright=2| {{center|'''Seep and vent interactions with surrounding deep-sea ecosystems'''}} The y axis is meters above bottom on a log scale. DOC: [[Dissolved Organic Carbon]], POC: [[Particulate Organic Carbon]], SMS: [[Seafloor Massive Sulfide]].<ref>Levin LA, Baco AR, Bowden DA, Colaco A, Cordes EE, Cunha MR, Demopoulos AWJ, Gobin J, Grupe BM, Le J, Metaxas A, Netburn AN, Rouse GW, Thurber AR, Tunnicliffe V, Van Dover CL, Vanreusel A and Watling L (2016). \"Hydrothermal Vents and Methane Seeps: Rethinking the Sphere of Influence\". ''Front. Mar. Sci.'' '''3''':72. {{doi|10.3389/fmars.2016.00072}}</ref>]]\n\n[[File:Guaymas seep and vent ecosystems.png|thumb|upright=2| Conceptual diagram of faunal community structure and food-web patterns along fluid-flux gradients within [[Guaymas]] seep and vent ecosystems.<ref>Portail, M., Olu, K., Dubois, S.F., Escobar-Briones, E., Gelinas, Y., Menot, L. and Sarrazin, J. (2016). \"Food-web complexity in Guaymas Basin hydrothermal vents and cold seeps\". ''PloS ONE'', '''11'''(9): p.e0162263. {{doi|10.1371/journal.pone.0162263}}.</ref><ref>Bernardino AF, Levin LA, Thurber AR and Smith CR (2012). \"Comparative Composition, Diversity and Trophic Ecology of Sediment Macrofauna at Vents, Seeps and Organic Falls\". PLoS ONE, 7(4): e33515. pmid:22496753. {{doi|10.1371/journal.pone.0033515}}.</ref><ref>Portail M, Olu K, Escobar-Briones E, Caprais JC, Menot L, Waeles M, et al. (2015). \"Comparative study of vent and seep macrofaunal communities in the Guaymas Basin\". Biogeosciences. 12(18): 5455\u201379. {{doi|10.5194/bg-12-5455-2015}}.</ref>]]\n\n{{clear}}\n\n==Polar webs==\n{{multiple image\n | align = right\n | direction = horizontal\n | width     = 210\n | header            = Polar topographies\n | header_align      = center\n | header_background = \n | footer            = [[File:Pulse of Snow and Sea Ice.ogv|420px]]{{center|The annual pulse of ice and snow at the poles}}\n | footer_align      = \n | footer_background = \n | background color  = \n | image1    = Globe showing Antarctic 2.png\n | alt1      = \n | caption1  = {{center|The [[Antarctica]] is a frozen landmass<br />surrounded by oceans}}\n | image2    = Globe showing Arctic 2.png\n | alt2      = \n | caption2  = {{center|The [[Arctic]] is a frozen ocean<br />surrounded by landmasses}}\n}}\n\nArctic and Antarctic marine systems have very different [[Marine topography|topographical structures]] and as a consequence have very different food web structures.<ref name=IPCC2001>McCarthy, J.J., Canziani, O.F., Leary, N.A., Dokken, D.J. and White, K.S. (Eds.) (2001) [https://books.google.com/books?id=RT7lQ24quc4C&pg=PA807&lpg=PA807&dq=%22the+Arctic+is+a+frozen+ocean+surrounded+by+continental+landmasses+and+open+oceans,+whereas+Antarctica+is+a+frozen+continent+surrounded+solely+by+oceans%22&source=bl&ots=ot_2WsboLX&sig=ACfU3U35AAabEothGkPYK80gfEQycNz6Pg&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwiTmoa666rnAhXS63MBHUl_DpgQ6AEwBHoECAgQAQ#v=onepage&q=%22the%20Arctic%20is%20a%20frozen%20ocean%20surrounded%20by%20continental%20landmasses%20and%20open%20oceans%2C%20whereas%20Antarctica%20is%20a%20frozen%20continent%20surrounded%20solely%20by%20oceans%22&f=false ''Climate Change 2001: Impacts, Adaptation, and Vulnerability: Contribution of Working Group II to the Third Assessment Report of the Intergovernmental Panel on Climate Change''] Page 807, Cambridge University Press. {{ISBN|9780521015004}}</ref> Both Arctic and Antarctic pelagic food webs have characteristic energy flows controlled largely by a few key species. But there is no single generic web for either. Alternative pathways are important for resilience and maintaining energy flows. However, these more complicated alternatives provide less energy flow to upper trophic-level species. \"Food-web structure may be similar in different regions, but the individual species that dominate mid-trophic levels vary across polar regions\".<ref>Murphy, E.J., Cavanagh, R.D., Drinkwater, K.F., Grant, S.M., Heymans, J.J., Hofmann, E.E., Hunt Jr, G.L. and Johnston, N.M. (2016) \"Understanding the structure and functioning of polar pelagic ecosystems to predict the impacts of change\". ''Proceedings of the Royal Society B: Biological Sciences'', '''283'''(1844): 20161646. {{doi|10.1098/rspb.2016.1646}}.</ref>\n\n[[File:Humpback whale NOAA.jpg|thumb|300px|left|Humpback whale straining krill]]\n\n{{multiple image\n | align = left\n | direction = horizontal\n | header = Penguins and polar bears never meet\n | image1    = Kaiserpinguine mit Jungen.jpg\n | width1    = 275\n | alt1      = \n | caption1  = {{center|The Antarctic has penguins but no polar bears}}\n | image2    = Polar Bear 2004-11-15.jpg\n | width2    = 240\n | alt2      = \n | caption2  = {{center|The Arctic has polar bears but no penguins}}\n}}\n\n{{clear}}\n\n; Arctic\n{{multiple image\n | align = right\n | direction = horizontal\n | header            = Polar bear food webs\n | header_align      = <!-- left/right/center -->\n | header_background = \n | footer            = \n | footer_align      = <!-- left/right/center -->\n | footer_background = \n | background color  = \n | width1    = 300\n | image1    = Arctic marine food web.jpg\n | alt1      = \n | caption1  = {{center|Traditional arctic marine food web with a focus on [[wiktionary:macroorganism|macroorganisms]]}}\n | width2    = 270\n | image2    = Arctic marine food web 2.jpg\n | alt2      = \n | caption2  = Contemporary arctic marine food web with a greater focus on the role of [[Marine microorganism|microorganisms]]\n}}\n\nThe Arctic food web is complex. The loss of sea ice can ultimately affect the entire food web, from algae and plankton to fish to mammals. The impact of climate change on a particular species can ripple through a food web and affect a wide range of other organisms... Not only is the decline of sea ice impairing polar bear populations by reducing the extent of their primary habitat, it is also negatively impacting them via food web effects. Declines in the duration and extent of sea ice in the Arctic leads to declines in the abundance of ice algae, which thrive in nutrient-rich pockets in the ice. These algae are eaten by zooplankton, which are in turn eaten by Arctic cod, an important food source for many marine mammals, including seals. Seals are eaten by polar bears. Hence, declines in ice algae can contribute to declines in polar bear populations.<ref>[https://archive.epa.gov/epa/climate-impacts/climate-impacts-ecosystems.html#ref2 Climate Impacts on Ecosystems: Food Web Disruptions] ''EPA''. Accessed 11 February 2020. {{PD-notice}}</ref>\n\n{{multiple image\n | align = left\n | direction = horizontal\n | header = \n | image1 = Sea angel.jpg\n | width1 = 259\n | alt1   = \n | caption1 = {{center|Pteropod ([[sea angel]])}}\n----\n[[File:Nuvola apps kaboodle.svg|16px]] [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=3-40RU3iSkA Pteropods: Swimming snails of the sea]\n | image2 = Marinomonas arctica.jpg\n | width2 = 172\n | alt2  = \n | caption2 = The bacterium ''[[Marinomonas arctica]]'' grows inside Arctic sea ice at subzero temperatures\n | image3 = Walrus's Floating On Bering Sea Ice Alaska.jpg\n | width3 = 259\n | alt3  = \n | caption3 = [[Walrus]] are keystone species in the Arctic but are not found in the Antarctic.\n}}\n\n{{multiple image\n | align = right\n | direction = horizontal\n | width     = 320\n | header            = Arctic food web with mixotrophy\n | header_align      = <!-- left/right/center -->\n | image1    = Arctic food web with mixotrophy.png\n | alt1      = \n | caption1  = Yellow arrows: flow of energy from the sun to photosynthetic organisms ([[autotroph]]s and [[mixotroph]]s)<br />Gray arrows: flow of carbon to heterotrophs<br />Green arrows: major pathways of carbon flow to or from mixotrophs<br />HCIL: [[heterotrophic]] ciliates; MCIL: mixotrophic ciliates; HNF: heterotrophic nanoflagellates; DOC: dissolved organic carbon; HDIN: heterotrophic dinoflagellates <ref>Stoecker, D.K. and Lavrentyev, P.J. (2018). \"Mixotrophic plankton in the polar seas: a pan-arctic review\". ''Frontiers in Marine Science'', '''5''': 292. {{doi|10.3389/fmars.2018.00292}}</ref>\n}}\n\n{{clear left}}\n\n; Antarctic\n<gallery mode=packed style=\"float:left;\">\nFile:Ice planet and antarctic jellyfish (crop).jpg|Antarctic jellyfish ''[[Diplulmaris antarctica ]]'' under the ice\nFile:Phaeocystis.png| Colonies of the alga ''[[Phaeocystis|Phaeocystis antarctica]]'', an important phytoplankter of the Ross Sea that dominates early season blooms after the sea ice retreats and exports significant carbon.<ref>Bender, S.J., Moran, D.M., McIlvin, M.R., Zheng, H., McCrow, J.P., Badger, J., DiTullio, G.R., Allen, A.E. and Saito, M.A. (2018) \"Colony formation in ''Phaeocystis antarctica'': connecting molecular mechanisms with iron biogeochemistry\". ''Biogeosciences'', '''15'''(16): 4923\u20134942. {{doi|10.5194/bg-15-4923-2018}}.</ref>\nFile:Fragilariopsis kerguelensis.jpg| The [[pennales|pennate]] [[diatom]] ''[[Fragilariopsis kerguelensis]]'', found throughout the Antarctic Circumpolar Current, is a key driver of the global [[Silica cycle#Marine silica cycling|silicate pump]].<ref>Pinkernell, S. and Beszteri, B. (2014) \"Potential effects of climate change on the distribution range of the main silicate sinker of the Southern Ocean\". ''Ecology and evolution'', '''4'''(16): 3147\u20133161. {{doi|10.1002/ece3.1138}}</ref>\nFile:Killer Whales Hunting a Crabeater Seal.jpg| A group of [[killer whale]]s attempt to dislodge a [[crabeater seal]] on an [[ice floe]]\n</gallery>\n\n{{multiple image\n | align = left\n | direction = horizontal\n | width     = 400\n | header    = Importance of Antarctic krill in biogeochemical cycles\n | image1    = Importance of Antarctic krill in biogeochemical cycles.png\n | caption1  = {{center|'''Processes in the biological pump'''}}{{center|<small> Numbers given are carbon fluxes (Gt\u2009C\u2009yr\u22121) in white boxes<br />and carbon masses (Gt C) in dark boxes</small>}}\nPhytoplankton convert CO2, which has dissolved from the atmosphere into the surface oceans into particulate organic carbon (POC) during primary production. Phytoplankton are then consumed by krill and small zooplankton grazers, which in turn are preyed upon by higher trophic levels. Any unconsumed phytoplankton form aggregates, and along with zooplankton faecal pellets, sink rapidly and are exported out of the mixed layer. Krill, zooplankton and microbes intercept phytoplankton in the surface ocean and sinking detrital particles at depth, consuming and respiring this POC to CO2 (dissolved inorganic carbon, DIC), such that only a small proportion of surface-produced carbon sinks to the deep ocean (i.e., depths\u2009>\u20091000\u2009m). As krill and smaller zooplankton feed, they also physically fragment particles into small, slower- or non-sinking pieces (via sloppy feeding, coprorhexy if fragmenting faeces), retarding POC export. This releases dissolved organic carbon (DOC) either directly from cells or indirectly via bacterial solubilisation (yellow circle around DOC). Bacteria can then remineralise the DOC to DIC (CO2, microbial gardening). Diel vertically migrating krill, smaller zooplankton and fish can actively transport carbon to depth by consuming POC in the surface layer at night, and metabolising it at their daytime, mesopelagic residence depths. Depending on species life history, active transport may occur on a seasonal basis as well.<ref>Cavan, E.L., Belcher, A., Atkinson, A., Hill, S.L., Kawaguchi, S., McCormack, S., Meyer, B., Nicol, S., Ratnarajah, L., Schmidt, K. and Steinberg, D.K. (2019) \"The importance of Antarctic krill in biogeochemical cycles\". ''Nature communications'', '''10'''(1): 1\u201313. {{doi|10.1038/s41467-019-12668-7}}.  [[File:CC-BY icon.svg|50px]] Material was copied from this source, which is available under a [https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by/4.0/ Creative Commons Attribution 4.0 International License].</ref>\n}}\n\n[[File:Antarctic marine food web - Potter Cove.png|thumb|upright=1.6|right| {{center|'''Antarctic marine food web'''}} Potter Cove 2018. Vertical position indicates trophic level and node widths are proportional to total degree (in and out). Node colors represent functional groups.<ref name=Cordone2018>Cordone, G., Marina, T.I., Salinas, V., Doyle, S.R., Saravia, L.A. and Momo, F.R.(2018). \"Effects of macroalgae loss in an Antarctic marine food web: applying extinction thresholds to food web studies\". ''PeerJ'', '''6''': e5531. {{doi|10.7717/peerj.5531}}</ref><ref>Marina, T.I., Salinas, V., Cordone, G., Campana, G., Moreira, E., Deregibus, D., Torre, L., Sahade, R., Tatian, M., Oro, E.B. and De Troch, M. (2018). \"The food web of Potter Cove (Antarctica): complexity, structure and function\". Estuarine, Coastal and Shelf Science, 200: 141\u2013151. doi:10.1016/j.ecss.2017.10.015.</ref>]]\n\n[[File:Common-enemy graph of food web.png|thumb|upright=1.6|right| {{center|'''Common-enemy graph of Antarctic food web'''}} Potter Cove 2018. Nodes represent basal species and links indirect interactions (shared predators). Node and link widths are proportional to number of shared predators. Node colors represent functional groups.<ref name=Cordone2018 />]]\n\n{{clear}}\n\n[[File:Sea ice food web and the microbial loop.png|thumb|upright=1.6|right| Sea ice food web and the microbial loop. AAnP = aerobic anaerobic phototroph, DOC = dissolved organic carbon, DOM = dissolved organic matter, POC = particulate organic carbon, PR = proteorhodopsins.<ref>Koh, E.Y., Martin, A.R., McMinn, A. and Ryan, K.G. (2012) \"Recent advances and future perspectives in microbial phototrophy in Antarctic sea ice\". ''Biology'', '''1'''(3): 542-556. {{doi|10.3390/biology1030542}}.</ref><ref>The microbial loop here is re-drawn and abridged from:\n*  Azam, F., Fenchel, T., Field, J.G., Gray, J.S., Meyer-Reil, L.A. and Thingstad, F. (1983) [https://www.jstor.org/stable/24814647 \"The ecological role of water-column microbes in the sea\"]. ''Marine ecology progress series'', '''10'''(3): 257\u2013263.\n* Fenchel, T. (2008) \"The microbial loop\u201325 years later\". ''Journal of Experimental Marine Biology and Ecology'', '''366'''(1-2): 99-103. {{doi|10.1016/j.jembe.2008.07.013}}.</ref>]]\n\n{{clear}}\n\n==Terrestrial comparisons==\n[[File:Numbers Pyramid.svg|thumb|340px| {{center|'''[[Biomass pyramid]]s'''<br />Compared to terrestrial biomass pyramids, aquatic pyramids are generally inverted at the base}}]] \n{{multiple image\n | align = right\n | direction = horizontal\n | header            = Marine producers use less biomass than terrestrial producers\n | header_align      = <!-- left/right/center -->\n | footer            = \n | footer_align      = <!-- left/right/center -->\n | footer_background = \n | background color  = \n | width1    = 230\n | image1    = Prochlorococcus marinus (cropped).jpg\n | alt1      = \n | caption1  = The minute but ubiquitous and highly active bacterium [[Prochlorococcus]] runs through its life cycle in one day, collectively generating 20% of all global oxygen.\n | width2    = 230\n | image2    = Gnarly Bristlecone Pine (crop).jpg\n | alt2      = \n | caption2  = By contrast, a single [[bristlecone pine]] can tie up a lot of relatively inert biomass for thousands of years with little photosynthetic activity.<ref name=\"oldest\">{{cite web|url=http://www.rmtrr.org/oldlist.htm|title=Oldlist|publisher=Rocky Mountain Tree Ring Research|access-date=January 8, 2013}}</ref>\n}}\n\nMarine environments can have inversions in their biomass pyramids. In particular, the biomass of consumers (copepods, krill, shrimp, forage fish) is generally larger than the biomass of primary producers. This happens because the ocean's primary producers are mostly tiny phytoplankton which have [[r-strategist]] traits of growing and reproducing rapidly, so a small mass can have a fast rate of primary production. In contrast, many terrestrial primary producers, such as mature forests, have [[K-strategist]] traits of growing and reproducing slowly, so a much larger mass is needed to achieve the same rate of primary production.\n\nExamples: The [[bristlecone pine]] can live for thousands of years, and has a very low production/biomass ratio. The cyanobacterium ''[[Prochlorococcus]]'' lives for about 24 hours, and has a very high production/biomass ratio.\n\n[[File:Misty Forest (227339925).jpeg|thumb|300px|left| {{center|Mature forests have a lot of biomass invested in [[secondary growth]] which has low [[Productivity (ecology)|productivity]]}}]]\n[[File:Biomass by life form.jpg|thumb|300px|left| {{center|Ocean or marine biomass, in a reversal of terrestrial biomass, can increase at higher trophic levels.<ref>Bar-On, Y.M., Phillips, R. and Milo, R. (2018) \"The biomass distribution on Earth\". ''Proceedings of the National Academy of Sciences'', '''115'''(25): 6506\u20136511. {{doi|10.1073/pnas.1711842115}}.</ref>}}]]\n\nIn oceans, most [[primary production]] is performed by [[algae]]. This is a contrast to on land, where most primary production is performed by [[vascular plants]]. \n\nAquatic producers, such as planktonic algae or aquatic plants, lack the large accumulation of [[secondary growth]] that exists in the woody trees of terrestrial ecosystems. However, they are able to reproduce quickly enough to support a larger biomass of grazers. This inverts the pyramid. Primary consumers have longer lifespans and slower growth rates that accumulates more biomass than the producers they consume. Phytoplankton live just a few days, whereas the zooplankton eating the phytoplankton live for several weeks and the fish eating the zooplankton live for several consecutive years.<ref>{{cite book | last= Spellman| first= Frank R.| title= The Science of Water: Concepts and Applications| year= 2008| publisher= CRC Press| page= 167| url= https://books.google.com/?id=Grivqd7tLuAC&pg=PA167&dq=However,+biomass+pyramids+can+sometimes+be+inverted.&cd=1#v=onepage&q=However%2C%20biomass%20pyramids%20can%20sometimes%20be%20inverted.| isbn= 978-1-4200-5544-3}}</ref> Aquatic predators also tend to have a lower death rate than the smaller consumers, which contributes to the inverted pyramidal pattern. Population structure, migration rates, and environmental refuge for prey are other possible causes for pyramids with biomass inverted. [[Energy pyramid]]s, however, will always have an upright pyramid shape if all sources of food energy are included, since this is dictated by the [[second law of thermodynamics]].\"<ref name=\"Odum05\">{{cite book | last1=Odum | first1=E. P. | last2=Barrett | first2=G. W. | title=Fundamentals of Ecology | edition=5th | publisher=Brooks/Cole, a part of Cengage Learning | year=2005 | isbn=978-0-534-42066-6 | url=http://www.cengage.com/aushed/instructor.do?disciplinenumber=1041&product_isbn=9780534420666&courseid=BI03&codeid=2BF6&subTab=&mainTab=About_the_Book&mailFlag=true&topicName= | url-status=dead | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110820163059/http://www.cengage.com/aushed/instructor.do?disciplinenumber=1041&product_isbn=9780534420666&courseid=BI03&codeid=2BF6&subTab=&mainTab=About_the_Book&mailFlag=true&topicName= | archivedate=2011-08-20 }}</ref><ref name=\"Wang09\">{{cite journal | last1=Wang | first1=H. | last2=Morrison | first2=W. | last3=Singh | first3=A. | last4=Weiss | first4=H. | title=Modeling inverted biomass pyramids and refuges in ecosystems | journal=Ecological Modelling | volume=220 | issue=11 | pages=1376\u20131382 | doi=10.1016/j.ecolmodel.2009.03.005 | year=2009 | url=http://people.math.gatech.edu/~weiss/pub/General_Mechanisms_Final.pdf | url-status=dead | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111007214333/http://people.math.gatech.edu/~weiss/pub/General_Mechanisms_Final.pdf | archivedate=2011-10-07 }}</ref>\n\n{|class=\"wikitable\"\n! colspan=4 | {{centre|Comparison of productivity in marine and terrestrial ecosystems <ref>Field, C.B., Behrenfeld, M.J., Randerson, J.T. and Falkowski, P. (1998) \"Primary production of the biosphere: integrating terrestrial and oceanic components\". ''Science'', '''281'''(5374): 237\u2013240. {{doi|10.1126/science.281.5374.237}}.</ref>}}\n|-\n! style=\"background:rgb(110,110,170)\"| <span style=\"color:white;\">Ecosystem</span>\n! Net primary productivity<br /><small>billion tonnes per year</small>\n! Total plant biomass<br /><small>billion tonnes</small>\n! Turnover time<br /><small>years</small>\n|-\n| style=\"background:rgb(110,110,170); color:white;\"| {{center|Marine}}\n| {{center|45\u201355}}\n| {{center|1\u20132}}\n| {{center|0.02\u20130.06}}\n|-\n| style=\"background:rgb(110,110,170); color:white;\"| {{center|Terrestrial}}\n| {{center|55\u201370}}\n| {{center|600\u20131000}}\n| {{center|9\u201320}}\n|}\n\n{{clear}}\n\n==Anthropogenic effects==\n[[File:Fishing down the food web.jpg|thumb|upright=1.7| {{center|[[Fishing down the food web]] <ref>Maureaud, A., Gascuel, D., Coll\u00e9ter, M., Palomares, M.L., Du Pontavice, H., Pauly, D. and Cheung, W.W. (2017) \"Global change in the trophic functioning of marine food webs\". ''PloS one'', '''12'''(8): e0182826. {{doi|10.1371/journal.pone.0182826}}</ref>}}]]\n\n;Overfishing\n\n;Acidification\n[[Pteropoda|Pteropods]] and [[brittle star]]s together form the base of the Arctic [[food web]]s and both are seriously damaged by acidification. Pteropods shells dissolve with increasing acidification and brittle stars lose muscle mass when re-growing appendages.<ref>{{cite web|title=Effects of Ocean Acidification on Marine Species & Ecosystems|url=http://oceana.org/en/our-work/climate-energy/ocean-acidification/learn-act/effects-of-ocean-acidification-on-marine-species-ecosystems|work=Report|publisher=OCEANA|accessdate=13 October 2013}}</ref> Additionally the brittle star's eggs die within a few days when exposed to expected conditions resulting from Arctic acidification.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.cicero.uio.no/webnews/index_e.aspx?id=11909 | title=Comprehensive study of Arctic Ocean acidification | publisher=CICERO | work=Study | accessdate=14 November 2013 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131210231159/http://www.cicero.uio.no/webnews/index_e.aspx?id=11909 | archive-date=10 December 2013 | url-status=dead }}</ref> Acidification threatens to destroy Arctic food webs from the base up. Arctic waters are changing rapidly and are advanced in the process of becoming undersaturated with aragonite.<ref name=\"biogeosciences\">{{cite web | url=http://www.biogeosciences.net/8/919/2011/bg-8-919-2011.pdf | title=Impact of ocean acidification and elevated temperatures on early juveniles of the polar shelled pteropod Limacina helicina : mortality, shell degradation, and shell growth | publisher=Biogeosciences | work=Report |date=15 April 2011 | accessdate=14 November 2013 |author1=Lischka, S. |author2=B\u00fcdenbender J. |author3=Boxhammer T. |author4=Riebesell U. | pages=919\u2013932}}</ref> Arctic food webs are considered simple, meaning there are few steps in the food chain from small organisms to larger predators. For example, pteropods are \"a key prey item of a number of higher predators \u2013 larger plankton, fish, seabirds, whales\".<ref>{{cite web|title=Antarctic marine wildlife is under threat, study finds|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/nature/20461646|publisher=BBC Nature|accessdate=13 October 2013}}</ref>\n\n{{clear left}}\n\n{{multiple image\n | align = left\n | direction = horizontal\n | header = Effects of ocean acidification\n | image1    = Fis01026 (27555118153).jpg\n | width1    = 170\n | alt1      = \n | caption1  = {{center|Unhealthy pteropod showing effects of ocean acidification}}\n | image2    = FMIB 52630 Ophiopholis aculeata.jpeg\n | width2    = 230\n | alt2      = \n | caption2  = {{center|Ocean acidification causes brittle stars to lose muscle mass}}\n | footer            = &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; [[Pteropod]]s and [[brittle star]]s form the base of Arctic food webs\n | footer_align      = center\n}}\n\n{{clear}}\n\n; Climate change\n\"Our results show how future climate change can potentially weaken marine food webs through reduced energy flow to higher trophic levels and a shift towards a more detritus-based system, leading to food web simplification and altered producer\u2013consumer dynamics, both of which have important implications for the structuring of benthic communities.\"<ref>Ullah, H., Nagelkerken, I., Goldenberg, S.U. and Fordham, D.A. (2018) \"Climate change could drive marine food web collapse through altered trophic flows and cyanobacterial proliferation\". ''PLoS biology'', '''16'''(1): e2003446. {{doi|10.1371/journal.pbio.2003446}}</ref><ref name=ScienceDaily2018>[https://www.sciencedaily.com/releases/2018/01/180109150921.htm Climate change drives collapse in marine food webs] ''ScienceDaily''. 9 January 2018.</ref>\n\n\"...increased temperatures reduce the vital flow of energy from the primary food producers at the bottom (e.g. algae), to intermediate consumers (herbivores), to predators at the top of marine food webs. Such disturbances in energy transfer can potentially lead to a decrease in food availability for top predators, which in turn, can lead to negative impacts for many marine species within these food webs... \"Whilst climate change increased the productivity of plants, this was mainly due to an expansion of cyanobacteria (small blue-green algae),\" said Mr Ullah. \"This increased primary productivity does not support food webs, however, because these cyanobacteria are largely unpalatable and they are not consumed by herbivores. Understanding how ecosystems function under the effects of global warming is a challenge in ecological research. Most research on ocean warming involves simplified, short-term experiments based on only one or a few species.\"<ref name=ScienceDaily2018 />\n\n[[File:Global distribution of anthropogenic stressors to marine species.png|thumb|upright=1.7|left| The distribution of anthropogenic stressors faced by marine species threatened with extinction in various marine regions of the world. Numbers in the pie charts indicate the percentage contribution of an anthropogenic stressors\u2019 impact in a specific marine region.<ref>Luypaert, T., Hagan, J.G., McCarthy, M.L. and Poti, M. (2020) \"Status of Marine Biodiversity in the Anthropocene\". In: ''YOUMARES 9-The Oceans: Our Research, Our Future'', pages 57-82, Springer. {{doi|10.1007/978-3-030-20389-4_4}}.</ref><ref>IUCN (2018) [http://www.iucnredlist.org The IUCN Red List of Threatened Species: Version 2018-1]</ref>]]\n\n[[File:Anthropogenic stressors to marine species threatened with extinction.png|thumb|upright=1.7|right| {{center|Anthropogenic stressors to marine species threatened with extinction <ref>Luypaert, T., Hagan, J.G., McCarthy, M.L. and Poti, M. (2020) \"Status of Marine Biodiversity in the Anthropocene\". In: ''YOUMARES 9-The Oceans: Our Research, Our Future'', pages 57-82, Springer. {{doi|10.1007/978-3-030-20389-4_4}}.</ref><ref>IUCN (2018) [http://www.iucnredlist.org The IUCN Red List of Threatened Species: Version 2018-1]</ref>}}]]\n\n{{clear}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Aquatic ecology]]\n[[Category:Ecological connectivity]]\n[[Category:Trophic ecology]]\n", "text_old": "[[File:Oceanic Food Web.jpg|thumb|upright=2|{{center|The pelagic [[food web]], showing the central involvement of [[marine microorganism]]s in how the ocean imports nutrients from and then exports them back to the atmosphere and ocean floor.}}]]\n{{marine life sidebar}}\n\nCompared to terrestrial environments, marine environments have [[biomass pyramid]]s which are inverted at the base. In particular, the biomass of consumers (copepods, krill, shrimp, forage fish) is larger than the biomass of [[primary producer]]s. This happens because the ocean's primary producers are tiny [[phytoplankton]] which grow and reproduce rapidly, so a small mass can have a fast rate of [[primary production]]. In contrast, terrestrial primary producers, such as [[climax forest|mature forests]], grow and reproduce slowly, so a much larger mass is needed to achieve the same rate of primary production.\n\nBecause of this inversion, it is the [[zooplankton]] that make up most of the marine animal [[Biomass (ecology)|biomass]]. As [[primary consumer]]s, zooplankton  are the crucial link between the primary producers (mainly phytoplankton) and the rest of the marine food web ([[secondary consumer]]s).<ref>U S Department of Energy (2008) [https://public.ornl.gov/site/gallery/detail.cfm?id=326 ''Carbon Cycling and Biosequestration''] page 81, Workshop report DOE/SC-108, U.S. Department of Energy Office of Science.</ref>\n\nIf phytoplankton dies before it is eaten, it descends through the [[euphotic zone]] as part of the [[marine snow]] and settles into the depths of sea. In this way, phytoplankton sequester about 2 billion tons of carbon dioxide into the ocean each year, causing the ocean to become a sink of carbon dioxide holding about 90% of all sequestered carbon.<ref name=\"EarthTimes\">{{cite web|url=http://www.earthtimes.org/scitech/role-marine-plankton-sequestration-carbon/1062/|title=The role of marine plankton in sequestration of carbon |author=Campbell, Mike |date=22 June 2011 |website=EarthTimes|accessdate=22 August 2014}}</ref> The ocean produces about half of the world's oxygen and stores 50 times more carbon dioxide than the atmosphere.<ref>[https://oceanservice.noaa.gov/facts/why-care-about-ocean.html Why should we care about the ocean?] ''NOAA: National Ocean Service''. Updated: 7 January 2020. Retrieved 1 March 2020.</ref>\n\nAn ecosystem cannot be understood without knowledge of how its food web determines the flow of materials and energy. Phytoplankton autotrophically produces biomass by converting [[inorganic compound]]s into [[organic compound|organic]] ones. In this way, phytoplankton functions as the foundation of the marine food web by supporting all other life in the ocean. The second central process in the marine food web is the [[microbial loop]]. This loop degrades [[marine bacteria]] and [[marine archaea|archaea]], [[remineralise]]s organic and inorganic matter, and then recycles the products either within the pelagic food web or by depositing them as sediment on the seafloor.<ref>Heinrichs, M.E., Mori, C. and Dlugosch, L. (2020) [https://link.springer.com/chapter/10.1007/978-3-030-20389-4_15 \"Complex Interactions Between Aquatic Organisms and Their Chemical Environment Elucidated from Different Perspectives\"]. In: Jungblut S., Liebich V., Bode-Dalby M. (Eds) ''YOUMARES 9-The Oceans: Our Research, Our Future '', pages 279\u2013297. Springer. {{doi|10.1007/978-3-030-20389-4_15}}.</ref>\n\n__TOC__\n\n==Trophic levels and food chains==\n{{main|trophic levels}}\n{{marine food chain}}\n\nAll life forms in the sea have the potential to become food for something else. In the ocean, the [[food chain]] typically starts with [[phytoplankton]] and follows a course such as:\n<blockquote>\nPhytoplankton \u2192 herbivorous zooplankton \u2192 carnivorous zooplankton \u2192 [[filter feeder]] \u2192 predatory vertebrate\n</blockquote>\n \n[[File:Grey seal food web.png|thumb|left| {{center|Classic food web for [[grey seal]]s in the [[Baltic Sea]] containing several typical marine food chains <ref>Karlson, A.M., Gorokhova, E., G\u00e5rdmark, A., Pekcan-Hekim, Z., Casini, M., Albertsson, J., Sundelin, B., Karlsson, O. and Bergstr\u00f6m, L. (2020). \"Linking consumer physiological status to food-web structure and prey food value in the Baltic Sea\". ''Ambio'', '''49'''(2): 391\u2013406. {{doi|10.1007/s13280-019-01201-1}}</ref>}}]]\n\n[[Phytoplankton]] are the main [[primary producer]]s at the bottom of the marine food chain. Since they are at the first level in the food chain they are said to have a [[trophic level]] of 1 (from the [[Greek language|Greek]] ''troph\u0113'' meaning food). Phytoplankton use [[photosynthesis]] to convert inorganic carbon into [[protoplasm]]. They are then consumed by microscopic animals called zooplankton.\n\n[[File:Graphical network.png|thumb|upright=1| A food web is network of food chains, and as such can be represented graphically and analysed using techniques from [[network theory]].<ref>Dunne, J.A., Williams, R.J. and Martinez, N.D. (2002) \"Food-web structure and network theory: the role of connectance and size\". ''Proceedings of the National Academy of Sciences'', '''99'''(20): 12917\u201312922. {{doi|10.1073/pnas.192407699}}.</ref><ref>Dunne, J.A. (2006) [https://books.google.com/books?id=qe-04Y2gKscC&pg=PA27&dq=%22The+network+structure+of+food+webs%22&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjO9e-z7dDoAhXCgeYKHcuHDmEQ6AEIMDAB#v=onepage&q=%22The%20network%20structure%20of%20food%20webs%22&f=false \"The network structure of food webs\"]. In: M Pascual and J. A. Dunne (Eds.) ''Ecological networks: linking structure to dynamics in food webs'', pages 27\u201386. {{ISBN|9780199775057}}.</ref>]]\n\n[[Zooplankton]] comprise the second trophic level in the food chain, and include microscopic one-celled organisms called [[protozoa]] as well as small [[crustacean]]s, such as [[copepod]]s and [[krill]], and the [[larva]] of fish, squid, lobsters and crabs.\n\nIn turn, small zooplankton are consumed by both larger predatory zooplankters, such as [[krill]], and by [[forage fish]], which are small, schooling, [[filter feeding|filter-feeding]] fish. This makes up the third trophic level in the food chain.\n\nThe fourth trophic level consists of predatory fish, marine mammals and seabirds that consume forage fish. Examples are [[swordfish]], [[Pinniped|seals]] and [[gannet]]s.\n\nApex predators, such as [[orca]]s, which can consume seals, and [[shortfin mako shark]]s, which can consume swordfish, make up a fifth trophic level. [[Baleen whale]]s can consume zooplankton and krill directly, leading to a food chain with only three or four trophic levels.\n\nIn practice, trophic levels are [[Trophic level#Fractional trophic levels|not always simple integers]] because the same consumer species often feeds across more than one trophic level.<ref>[[William Eugene Odum|Odum, W. E.]]; Heald, E. J. (1975) \"The detritus-based food web of an estuarine mangrove community\". Pages 265\u2013286 in L. E. Cronin, ed. ''Estuarine research''. Vol. 1. Academic Press, New York.</ref><ref>{{Cite journal | doi=10.1038/275542a0 | last1=Pimm | first1=S. L. | last2=Lawton | first2=J. H. | year=1978 | title=On feeding on more than one trophic level | journal=Nature | volume=275 | issue=5680| pages=542\u2013544 }}</ref> For example a large [[marine vertebrate]] may eat smaller predatory fish but may also eat filter feeders; the [[stingray]] eats [[crustacean]]s, but the [[hammerhead shark|hammerhead]] eats both crustaceans and stingrays. Animals can also eat each other; the [[cod]] eats smaller cod as well as [[crayfish]], and crayfish eat cod larvae. The feeding habits of a juvenile animal, and, as a consequence, its trophic level, can change as it grows up.\n\nThe fisheries scientist [[Daniel Pauly]] sets the values of trophic levels to one in plants and detritus, two in herbivores and detritivores (primary consumers), three in secondary consumers, and so on. The definition of the trophic level, TL, for any consumer species is:<ref name=Pauly&Palomares>{{Cite journal | last1=Pauly | first1=D. | last2=Palomares | first2=M. L. | year=2005 | title=Fishing down marine food webs: it is far more pervasive than we thought | url=http://www.seaaroundus.org/Journal/2005/FishingDownMarineFoodWebItisfarMorePervasive.pdf | journal=Bulletin of Marine Science | volume=76 | issue=2 | pages=197\u2013211 | url-status=dead | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130514091440/http://www.seaaroundus.org/Journal/2005/FishingDownMarineFoodWebItisfarMorePervasive.pdf | archivedate=2013-05-14 }}</ref>\n\n:: <math> TL_i=1 + \\sum_j (TL_j \\cdot DC_{ij})\\! </math>\n\nwhere <math>TL_j</math> is the fractional trophic level of the prey ''j'', and <math>DC_{ij}</math> represents the fraction of ''j'' in the diet of ''i''. In the case of marine ecosystems, the trophic level of most fish and other marine consumers takes value between\n2.0 and 5.0. The upper value, 5.0, is unusual, even for large fish,<ref name=r1>{{Cite journal | doi=10.1006/jmsc.1999.0489 | last1=Cort\u00e9s | first1=E. | year=1999 | title=Standardized diet compositions and trophic levels of sharks | journal=ICES J. Mar. Sci. | volume=56 | issue=5| pages=707\u2013717 }}</ref> though it occurs in apex predators of marine mammals, such as polar bears and killer whales.<ref name=Pauly1998b>{{Cite journal | doi=10.1006/jmsc.1997.0280 | last1=Pauly | first1=D. | last2=Trites | first2=A. | last3=Capuli | first3=E. | last4=Christensen | first4=V. | year=1998 | title=Diet composition and trophic levels of marine mammals | journal=ICES J. Mar. Sci. | volume=55 | issue=3| pages=467\u2013481 }}</ref> As a point of contrast, humans have a mean trophic level of about 2.21, about the same as a pig or an anchovy.<ref>[https://phys.org/news/2013-12-human-trophic.html Researchers calculate human trophic level for first time] ''Phys.org ''. 3 December 2013.</ref><ref>Bonhommeau, S., Dubroca, L., Le Pape, O., Barde, J., Kaplan, D.M., Chassot, E. and Nieblas, A.E. (2013) \"Eating up the world\u2019s food web and the human trophic level\". ''Proceedings of the National Academy of Sciences'', '''110'''(51): 20617\u201320620. {{doi|10.1073/pnas.1305827110}}.</ref>\n\n{{clear}}\n\n==Primary producers==\nAt the base of the ocean food web are single-celled algae and other plant-like organisms known as [[phytoplankton]]. Like plants on land, phytoplankton use [[chlorophyll]] and other [[light-harvesting pigment]]s to carry out [[photosynthesis]], absorbing atmospheric carbon dioxide to produce sugars for fuel. Chlorophyll in the water changes the way it reflects and absorbs sunlight, allowing scientists to map the amount and location of phytoplankton. These measurements give scientists valuable insights into the health of the ocean environment, and help scientists study the [[ocean carbon cycle]].<ref name=NASAO2019 />\n\n[[File:Global ocean chlorophyll concentration October 2019.png|thumb|upright=2| {{center|'''Ocean chlorophyll concentration October 2019'''}} Green indicates where there are a lot of phytoplankton, while blue indicates where there are few phytoplankton. \u2013 NASA Earth Observatory 2019.<ref name=NASAO2019>[https://earthobservatory.nasa.gov/global-maps/MY1DMM_CHLORA Chlorophyll] NASA Earth Observatory. Accessed 30 November 2019.</ref>]]\n\n[[File:Prochlorococcus marinus.jpg|thumb|150px|left| {{center|''[[Prochlorococcus]]'', an influential bacterium which produces much of the world's oxygen}}]]\n\nAmong the phytoplankton are members from a phylum of bacteria called [[cyanobacteria]]. Marine cyanobacteria include the smallest known photosynthetic organisms. The smallest of all, ''[[Prochlorococcus]]'', is just 0.5 to 0.8 micrometres across.<ref>{{cite journal | vauthors = Kettler GC, Martiny AC, Huang K, Zucker J, Coleman ML, Rodrigue S, Chen F, Lapidus A, Ferriera S, Johnson J, Steglich C, Church GM, Richardson P, Chisholm SW | title = Patterns and implications of gene gain and loss in the evolution of Prochlorococcus | journal = PLoS Genetics | volume = 3 | issue = 12 | pages = e231 | date = December 2007 | pmid = 18159947 | pmc = 2151091 | doi = 10.1371/journal.pgen.0030231 }}</ref> In terms of individual numbers, ''Prochlorococcus'' is possibly the most plentiful species on Earth: a single millilitre of surface seawater can contain 100,000 cells or more. Worldwide there are estimated to be several [[octillion]] (~10<sup>27</sup>) individuals.<ref>{{Cite APOD |date=27 September 2006 |title=Earth from Saturn |access-date=}}</ref> ''Prochlorococcus'' is ubiquitous between 40\u00b0N and 40\u00b0S and dominates in the [[oligotroph]]ic (nutrient poor) regions of the oceans.<ref>{{cite journal | vauthors = Partensky F, Hess WR, Vaulot D | title = Prochlorococcus, a marine photosynthetic prokaryote of global significance | journal = Microbiology and Molecular Biology Reviews | volume = 63 | issue = 1 | pages = 106\u201327 | date = March 1999 | pmid = 10066832 | pmc = 98958 }}</ref> The bacterium accounts for about 20% of the oxygen in the Earth's atmosphere.<ref name=\"npr\">{{cite web|url=https://www.npr.org/templates/story/story.php?storyId=91448837|title=The Most Important Microbe You've Never Heard Of|author=|date=|website=npr.org}}</ref>\n\nIn oceans, most [[primary production]] is performed by [[algae]]. This is a contrast to on land, where most primary production is performed by [[vascular plants]]. Algae ranges from single floating cells to attached [[seaweeds]], while vascular plants are represented in the ocean by groups such as the [[seagrass]]es. Larger producers, such as seagrasses and seaweeds, are mostly confined to the [[littoral]] zone and shallow waters, where they [[holdfast|attach]] to the underlying substrate and are still within the [[photic zone]]. But most of the primary production by algae is performed by the phytoplankton.\n\n{{clear right}}\n\n<gallery mode=packed heights=200px, style=\"float:right;\" caption=\"Phytoplankton form the base of the ocean foodchain\">\nFile:phytopla.gif|Phytoplankton\nFile:Noctiluca scintillans unica.jpg|Dinoflagellate\nFile:Diatoms through the microscope.jpg|Diatoms\n</gallery>\n\nThus, in ocean environments, the first bottom trophic level is occupied principally by [[phytoplankton]], microscopic drifting organisms, mostly [[one-celled]] [[algae]], that float in the sea. Most phytoplankton are too small to be seen individually with the [[naked eye|unaided eye]]. They can appear as a green discoloration of the water when they are present in high enough numbers. Since they increase their biomass mostly through photosynthesis they live in the sun-lit surface layer ([[Photic zone|euphotic zone]]) of the sea.\n\nThe most important groups of phytoplankton include the [[diatom]]s and [[dinoflagellate]]s. Diatoms are especially important in oceans, where according to some estimates they contribute up to 45% of the total ocean's primary production.<ref name=mann99>{{cite journal | doi = 10.2216/i0031-8884-38-6-437.1 | last1 = Mann | first1 = D. G. | year = 1999 | title = The species concept in diatoms | journal = Phycologia | volume = 38 | issue =  | pages = 437\u2013495 }}</ref> Diatoms are usually [[microscope|microscopic]], although some species can reach up to 2 millimetres in length.\n\n==Primary consumers==\nThe second trophic level ([[primary consumer]]s) is occupied by [[zooplankton]] which feed off the [[phytoplankton]]. Together with the phytoplankton, they form the base of the food pyramid that supports most of the world's great fishing grounds. Zooplankton are tiny animals found with the phytoplankton in [[ocean]]ic [[photic zone|surface waters]], and include tiny [[crustacean]]s, and fish larvae and [[spawn (biology)#Fry|fry]] (recently hatched fish). Most zooplankton are [[filter feeder]]s, and they use appendages to strain the phytoplankton in the water. Some larger zooplankton also feed on smaller zooplankton. Some zooplankton can jump about a bit to avoid predators, but they can't really swim. Like phytoplankton, they float with the currents, tides and winds instead. Zooplanktons can reproduce rapidly, their populations can increase up to thirty percent a day under favourable conditions. Many live short and productive lives and reach maturity quickly.\n\n<gallery mode=packed heights=160px, style=\"float:right;\" caption=\"Zooplankton form a second level in the ocean food chain\">\nFile:Tomopteriskils.jpg|Segmented worm\nFile:Hyperia.jpg|Tiny shrimp-like crustaceans\nFile:Squidu.jpg|Juvenile planktonic squid\n</gallery>\n\nParticularly important groups of zooplankton are the [[copepod]]s and [[krill]]. [[Copepod]]s are a group of small [[crustacean]]s found in ocean and [[fresh water|freshwater]] [[habitat (ecology)|habitats]]. They are the biggest source of protein in the sea,<ref>[http://www.uni-oldenburg.de/zoomorphology/Biology.html Biology of Copepods] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090101205840/http://www.uni-oldenburg.de/zoomorphology/Biology.html |date=2009-01-01 }} at [[Carl von Ossietzky University of Oldenburg]]</ref> and are important prey for forage fish. [[Krill]] constitute the next biggest source of protein. Krill are particularly large predator zooplankton which feed on smaller zooplankton. This means they really belong to the third trophic level, secondary consumers, along with the forage fish.\n\nTogether, [[phytoplankton]] and [[zooplankton]] make up most of the [[plankton]] in the sea. Plankton is the term applied to any small drifting [[organism]]s that float in the sea ([[Greek language|Greek]] ''planktos'' = wanderer or drifter). By definition, organisms classified as plankton are unable to swim against ocean currents; they cannot resist the ambient current and control their position. In ocean environments, the first two trophic levels are occupied mainly by [[plankton]]. Plankton are divided into producers and consumers. The producers are the phytoplankton (Greek ''phyton'' = plant) and the consumers, who eat the phytoplankton, are the zooplankton (Greek ''zoon'' = animal).\n\n[[File:Jellyfish swarm.jpg|thumb|upright=1.15| Jellyfish are easy to capture and digest and may be more important as food sources than was previously thought.<ref name=Hays2018 />]]\n\nTraditionally [[jellyfish]] have been viewed as trophic dead ends, minor players in the marine food web, gelatinous organisms with a [[body plan]] largely based on water that offers little nutritional value for other organisms apart from a few specialised predators such as the [[ocean sunfish]] and the [[leatherback sea turtle]].<ref name=Hamilton2016>Hamilton, G. (2016) [https://www.nature.com/news/polopoly_fs/1.19613!/menu/main/topColumns/topLeftColumn/pdf/531432a.pdf \"The secret lives of jellyfish: long regarded as minor players in ocean ecology, jellyfish are actually important parts of the marine food web\"]. ''Nature'', '''531'''(7595): 432-435. {{doi|10.1038/531432a}}</ref><ref name=Hays2018>Hays, G.C., Doyle, T.K. and Houghton, J.D. (2018) \"A paradigm shift in the trophic importance of jellyfish?\" ''Trends in ecology & evolution'', '''33'''(11): 874-884. {{doi|10.1016/j.tree.2018.09.001}}</ref> That view has recently been challenged. Jellyfish, and more generally [[gelatinous zooplankton]] which include [[salp]]s and [[ctenophore]]s, are very diverse, fragile with no hard parts, difficult to see and monitor, subject to rapid population swings and often live inconveniently far from shore or deep in the ocean. It is difficult for scientists to detect and analyse jellyfish in the guts of predators, since they turn to mush when eaten and are rapidly digested.<ref name=Hamilton2016/> But jellyfish bloom in vast numbers, and it has been shown they form major components in the diets of [[tuna]], [[spearfish]] and [[swordfish]] as well as various birds and invertebrates such as [[octopus]], [[sea cucumber]]s, [[crab]]s and [[amphipod]]s.<ref>Cardona, L., De Quevedo, I.\u00c1., Borrell, A. and Aguilar, A. (2012) \"Massive consumption of gelatinous plankton by Mediterranean apex predators\". ''PloS one'', '''7'''(3): e31329. {{doi|10.1371/journal.pone.0031329}}</ref><ref name=Hays2018 /> \"Despite their low energy density, the contribution of jellyfish to the energy budgets of predators may be much greater than assumed because of rapid digestion, low capture costs, availability, and selective feeding on the more energy-rich components. Feeding on jellyfish may make marine predators susceptible to ingestion of plastics.\"<ref name=Hays2018 />\n\n==Higher order consumers==\n\n; Marine invertebrates\n\n; Fish\n[[File:Schooling fish.jpg|thumb|upright=1.84| {{center|Predator fish sizing up [[Shoaling and schooling|schooling]] forage fish}}]]\n\n* [[Forage fish]] <ref>[https://www.npr.org/sections/thesalt/2016/04/07/473293477/tiny-forage-fish-at-bottom-of-marine-food-chain-get-new-protections Tiny Forage Fish At Bottom Of Marine Food Web Get New Protections] ''[[National Public Radio]]'', 7 April 2016.</ref>\n\nForage fish occupy central positions in the ocean [[food web]]s. The organisms it eats are at a lower [[trophic level]], and the organisms that eat it are at a higher trophic level. Forage fish occupy middle levels in the food web, serving as a dominant prey to higher level fish, seabirds and mammals.\n\n* [[Predator fish]]\n\n* [[Ground fish]]\n\n; Other marine vertebrates\nIn 2010 researchers found whales carry nutrients from the depths of the ocean back to the surface using a process they called the [[whale pump]].<ref name=\"PLOSOne\">{{cite journal|authors=Roman, J. & McCarthy, J.J.|year= 2010|title=The Whale Pump: Marine Mammals Enhance Primary Productivity in a Coastal Basin|journal=PLoS ONE|volume=5|issue=10|id=e13255|doi=10.1371/journal.pone.0013255|pages=e13255|pmid=20949007|pmc=2952594|bibcode= 2010PLoSO...513255R}}</ref> Whales feed at deeper levels in the ocean where [[krill]] is found, but return regularly to the surface to breathe. There  whales [[Whale faeces|defecate a liquid]] rich in nitrogen and iron. Instead of sinking, the liquid stays at the surface where [[phytoplankton]] consume it. In the Gulf of Maine the whale pump provides more nitrogen than the rivers.<ref name=\"ScienceDaily\">{{cite web|url=https://www.sciencedaily.com/releases/2010/10/101012101255.htm|title=Whale poop pumps up ocean health|author=Brown, Joshua E.|date=12 Oct 2010|website=Science Daily|accessdate=18 August 2014}}</ref>\n\n{{clear right}}\n\n<gallery mode=packed heights=160px style=\"float:right;\">\nFile:Humpback lunge feeding.jpg|[[Humpback whale]]s [[lunge feeding|lunge from below]] to feed on forage fish\nFile:Gannet (Morus bassana), Belmont - geograph.org.uk - 529175.jpg|thumb|[[Northern gannet|Gannets]] [[plunge dive]] from above to catch forage fish\n</gallery>\n\n<gallery mode=packed heights=220px style=\"float:left;\">\nFile:WhalePump.jpg| {{center|Whale pump [[nutrient cycle]]}}\n</gallery>\n\n{{clear}}\n\n==Microorganisms==\n[[File:Microorganisms in a drop of seawater.jpg|thumb| On average there are \"more than one million microbial cells in every drop of seawater, and their collective metabolisms not only recycle nutrients that can then be used by larger organisms but also catalyze key chemical transformations that maintain Earth\u2019s habitability\".<ref>Raina, J.B. (2018) \"The life aquatic at the microscale\". ''mSystems'', '''3'''(2): e00150-17. {{doi|10.1128/mSystems.00150-17}}.</ref>]]\n{{see also|marine microorganisms|microbial loop|microbial food web|viral shunt}}\n\nThere has been increasing recognition in recent years that [[marine microorganism]]s play much bigger roles in marine ecosystems than was previously thought. Developments in [[metagenomics]] gives researchers an ability to reveal previously hidden diversities of microscopic life, offering a powerful lens for viewing the microbial world and the potential to revolutionise understanding of the living world.<ref name= MarcoD2011>{{cite book| editor = Marco, D| year=2011| title=Metagenomics: Current Innovations and Future Trends| publisher=[[Caister Academic Press]]| isbn= 978-1-904455-87-5}}</ref> [[DNA barcoding in diet assessment|Metabarcoding dietary analysis]] techniques are being used to reconstruct food webs at higher levels of taxonomic resolution and are revealing deeper complexities in the web of interactions.<ref name=Roslin2016 />\n\n[[Microorganism]]s play key roles in marine food webs. The [[viral shunt]] pathway is a mechanism that prevents marine microbial [[particulate organic matter]] (POM) from migrating up [[trophic level]]s by recycling them into [[dissolved organic matter]] (DOM), which can be readily taken up by microorganisms.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Wilhelm|first=Steven W.|last2=Suttle|first2=Curtis A.|date=1999|title=Viruses and Nutrient Cycles in the Sea|journal=BioScience|volume=49|issue=10|pages=781\u2013788|doi=10.2307/1313569|issn=1525-3244|jstor=1313569}}</ref> Viral shunting helps maintain diversity within the microbial ecosystem by preventing a single species of marine microbe from dominating the micro-environment.<ref>Weinbauer, Markus G., et al. \"Synergistic and antagonistic effects of viral lysis and protistan grazing on bacterial biomass, production and diversity.\" ''Environmental Microbiology'' 9.3 (2007): 777-788.</ref> The DOM recycled by the viral shunt pathway is comparable to the amount generated by the other main sources of marine DOM.<ref>Robinson, Carol, and Nagappa Ramaiah. \"Microbial heterotrophic metabolic rates constrain the microbial carbon pump.\" The American Association for the Advancement of Science, 2011.</ref>\n\n[[File:POC.png|thumb|upright=1.7|left| {{center|Ocean particulate organic matter (POM)<br />as [[Moderate-Resolution Imaging Spectroradiometer|imaged by a satellite]] in 2011}}]]\n\n[[File:Cycling of marine phytoplankton.png|thumb|upright=1.7| Cycling of marine phytoplankton. Phytoplankton live in the photic zone of the ocean, where photosynthesis is possible. During photosynthesis, they assimilate carbon dioxide and release oxygen. If solar radiation is too high, phytoplankton may fall victim to photodegradation. For growth, phytoplankton cells depend on nutrients, which enter the ocean by rivers, continental weathering, and glacial ice meltwater on the poles. Phytoplankton release dissolved organic carbon (DOC) into the ocean. Since phytoplankton are the basis of marine food webs, they serve as prey for zooplankton, fish larvae and other heterotrophic organisms. They can also be degraded by bacteria or by viral lysis. Although some phytoplankton cells, such as dinoflagellates, are able to migrate vertically, they are still incapable of actively moving against currents, so they slowly sink and ultimately fertilize the seafloor with dead cells and detritus.<ref>K\u00e4se L, Geuer JK. (2018) [https://link.springer.com/chapter/10.1007/978-3-319-93284-2_5 \"Phytoplankton Responses to Marine Climate Change \u2013 An Introduction\"].  In Jungblut S., Liebich V., Bode M. (Eds) ''YOUMARES 8\u2013Oceans Across Boundaries: Learning from each other'', pages 55\u201372, Springer. {{doi|10.1007/978-3-319-93284-2_5}}. [[File:CC-BY icon.svg|50px]] Material was copied from this source, which is available under a [https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by/4.0/ Creative Commons Attribution 4.0 International License].</ref>]]\n\n{{multiple image\n | align = left\n | direction = horizontal\n | header            = DOM, POM and the viral shunt\n | header_align      = <!-- left/right/center -->\n | footer            = \n | footer_align      = <!-- left/right/center -->\n | footer_background = \n | background color  = \n | width1    = 315\n | image1    = Marine connections between the living and the nonliving.png\n | alt1      = \n | caption1  = Connections between the different compartments of the living (bacteria/viruses and phyto\u2212/zooplankton) and the nonliving (DOM/POM and inorganic matter) environment <ref>Heinrichs, M.E., Mori, C. and Dlugosch, L. (2020) \"Complex Interactions Between Aquatic Organisms and Their Chemical Environment Elucidated from Different Perspectives\". In: ''YOUMARES 9-The Oceans: Our Research, Our Future '', pages 279\u2013297. Springer. {{doi|10.1007/978-3-030-20389-4_15}}.</ref>\n | width2    = 230\n | image2    = Viral shunt.jpg\n | alt2      = \n | caption2  = The [[viral shunt pathway]] facilitates the flow of [[dissolved organic matter]] (DOM) and [[particulate organic matter]] (POM) through the marine food web\n}}\n\n{{clear}}\n\n==Fungi==\n{{main|Marine fungi}}\n[[File:Roles of fungi in the marine carbon cycle.jpg|thumb|upright=2| {{center| Roles of fungi in the marine carbon cycle <ref>Gutierrez MH, Jara AM, Pantoja S (2016) \"Fungal parasites infect marine diatoms in the upwelling ecosystem of the Humboldt current system off central Chile\". ''Environ Microbiol'', '''18'''(5): 1646\u20131653. {{doi|10.1111/1462-2920.13257}}.</ref>}}]]\n\n* Amend, A., Burgaud, G., Cunliffe, M., Edgcomb, V.P., Ettinger, C.L., Guti\u00e9rrez, M.H., Heitman, J., Hom, E.F., Ianiri, G., Jones, A.C. and Kagami, M. (2019) [https://mbio.asm.org/content/10/2/e01189-18 \"Fungi in the marine environment: Open questions and unsolved problems\"]. ''MBio'', '''10'''(2): e01189-18. {{doi|10.1128/mBio.01189-18}}.\n\n{{clear}}\n\n==Coastal webs==\n{{multiple image\n | align = right\n | direction = horizontal\n | width     = 250\n | header            = Continental shelves\n | header_align      = <!-- left/right/center -->\n | image1    = R\u00e9seau trophique en eaux c\u00f4ti\u00e8res.jpg\n | alt1      = \n | caption1  = Typical food web on a continental shelf\n}}\n\n* Byrnes, J.E., Reynolds, P.L. and Stachowicz, J.J. (2007) \"Invasions and extinctions reshape coastal marine food webs\". ''PloS one'', '''2'''(3): e295. {{doi|10.1371/journal.pone.0000295}}\n\n{{multiple image\n | align = left\n | direction = horizontal\n | width     = 550\n | header            = Chesapeake waterbird food web\n | header_align      = <!-- left/right/center -->\n | image1    = Chesapeake Waterbird Food Web.jpg\n | alt1      = \n | caption1  = {{center|Waterbird food web in [[Chesapeake Bay]]}} Generalized food web for some of the major waterbirds that frequent the Chesapeake Bay. Food sources and habitats of waterbirds are affected by multiple factors, including [[Introduced species|exotic]] and [[invasive species]].<ref>US Geological Survey (USGS). [http://pubs.usgs.gov/circ/circ1316/html/circ1316chap14.html \"Chapter 14: Changes in Food and Habitats of Waterbirds.\" Figure 14.1.] ''Synthesis of U.S. Geological Survey Science for the Chesapeake Bay Ecosystem and Implications for Environmental Management.'' USGS Circular 1316. {{PD-notice}}</ref><ref>Perry, M.C., Osenton, P.C., Wells-Berlin, A.M., and Kidwell, D.M., 2005, Food selection among Atlantic Coast sea ducks in relation to historic food habits, [abs.] in Perry, M.C., Second North American Sea Duck Conference, November 7\u201311, 2005, Annapolis, Maryland, Program and Abstracts, USGS Patuxent Wildlife Research Center, Maryland, 123 p. (p. 105).</ref>\n}}\n\n{{multiple image\n | align = right\n | direction = horizontal\n | width     = 250\n | header            = Puffin and herring food web\n | header_align      = <!-- left/right/center -->\n | image1    = Atlantic puffin and herring food chain.png\n | alt1      = \n | caption1  = [[Machias Seal Island]] [[Atlantic puffin]] and [[Atlantic herring]] food web. Increasing line thickness relates to higher frequency of occurrence in adult (blue), chick (green), and herring (purple) diet.<ref>Bowser, A.K., Diamond, A.W. and Addison, J.A. (2013) \"From puffins to plankton: a DNA-based analysis of a seabird food chain in the northern Gulf of Maine\". ''PLoS One'', '''8'''(12): e83152. {{doi|10.1371/journal.pone.0083152}}</ref>\n}}\n\n{{clear}}\n\n{{multiple image\n | align = right\n | direction = horizontal\n | width     = 440\n | header            = Seabird colonies\n | header_align      = <!-- left/right/center -->\n | image1    = Seabird ornitheutrophication coupling.png\n | alt1      = \n | caption1  = [[Seabird#Breeding and colonies|Seabird colonies]] are nutrient hot spots, especially, for nitrogen and phosphorus.<ref name=Otero2018>Otero, X.L., De La Pe\u00f1a-Lastra, S., P\u00e9rez-Alberti, A., Ferreira, T.O. and Huerta-Diaz, M.A. (2018) \"Seabird colonies as important global drivers in the nitrogen and phosphorus cycles\". ''Nature communications'', '''9'''(1): 1\u20138. {{doi|10.1038/s41467-017-02446-8}}. Material was copied from this source, which is available under a [https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by/4.0/ Creative Commons Attribution 4.0 International License].</ref>\n}}\n\nThe key nutrients determining [[eutrophication]] are nitrogen in coastal waters and phosphorus in lakes. Both are found in high concentrations in [[guano]] (seabird feces), which acts as a fertilizer for the surrounding ocean or an adjacent lake. [[Uric acid]] is the dominant nitrogen compound, and during its mineralization different nitrogen forms are produced. In the diagram on the right: (1) ammonification produces NH3 and NH4+, and (2) nitrification produces NO3\u2212 by NH4+ oxidation. Under the alkaline conditions, typical of the seabird feces, the NH3 is rapidly volatised (3) and transformed to NH4+, which is transported out of the colony, and through wet-deposition exported to distant ecosystems, which are eutrophised (4). The phosphorus cycle is simpler and has reduced mobility. This element is found in a number of chemical forms in the seabird fecal material, but the most mobile and bioavailable is [[orthophosphate]], which can be [[Leaching (chemistry)|leached]] by subterranean or superficial waters (5).<ref name=Otero2018 />\n\n\n\n\n\n\n{{multiple image\n | align = left\n | direction = horizontal\n | width     = 550\n | header            = Estuaries\n | header_align      = <!-- left/right/center -->\n | image1    = Food web of the Venice lagoon.png\n | alt1      = \n | caption1  = Example food web from an [[estuary]], the [[Venice Lagoon]], involving 27 nodes or functional groups. Colors of flows depict different fishing target (artisanal fisheries in blue, and clam fishery in red) and non-target species (for clam harvesting, in green). <ref>Heymans, J.J., Coll, M., Libralato, S., Morissette, L. and Christensen, V. (2014). \"Global patterns in ecological indicators of marine food webs: a modelling approach\". ''PloS one'', '''9'''(4). doi:10.1371/journal.pone.0095845.</ref><ref>Pranovi, F., Libralato, S., Raicevich, S., Granzotto, A., Pastres, R. and Giovanardi, O. (2003). \"Mechanical clam dredging in Venice lagoon: ecosystem effects evaluated with a trophic mass-balance model\". ''Marine Biology'', '''143'''(2): 393\u2013403. doi:10.1007/s00227-003-1072-1.</ref>\n}}\n\n\n{{multiple image\n | align = right\n | direction = horizontal\n | width     = 440\n | header            = Filter feeding bivalves\n | image1    = Nutrient extraction services provided by bivalves.png\n | alt1      = \n | caption1  = [[Ecosystem services]] provided by [[filter feeding]] bivalves often resident in estuaries, in the form of [[Nutrient cycle|nutrient extraction]] from phytoplankton. [[Blue mussel]]s are used in the example but other bivalves like [[oyster]]s also provide these nutrient extraction services.<ref name=Petersen2019>Petersen, J.K., Holmer, M., Termansen, M. and Hasler, B. (2019) \"Nutrient extraction through bivalves\". In: Smaal A., Ferreira J., Grant J., Petersen J., Strand \u00d8. (eds) ''Goods and Services of Marine Bivalves'', pages 179\u2013208. Springer. {{doi|10.1007/978-3-319-96776-9_10}}. {{ISBN|9783319967769}}</ref>\n}}\n\n{{clear}}\n\n{{multiple image\n | align = right\n | direction = horizontal\n | width     = 440\n | header            = Coral reefs\n | header_align      = <!-- left/right/center -->\n | image1    = Food web reconstruction by DNA barcodes.jpg\n | alt1      = \n | caption1  = Food web reconstruction by [[DNA barcoding|DNA barcodes]] at the coral reef of [[Moorea]], French Polynesia. Dietary partitioning among three predatory fish species as detected using [[DNA barcoding in diet assessment|metabarcoding dietary analysis]]. The taxonomic resolution provided by the metabarcoding approach highlights a complex interaction web and demonstrates that levels of trophic partitioning among [[coral reef fishes]] have likely been underestimated.<ref name=Roslin2016>Roslin, T. and Majaneva, S. (2016) \"The use of DNA barcodes in food web construction\u2014terrestrial and aquatic ecologists unite!\". ''Genome'', '''59'''(9): 603\u2013628. {{doi|10.1139/gen-2015-0229}}.</ref><ref>Leray M, Meyer CP, Mills SC. (2015) \"Metabarcoding dietary analysis of coral dwelling predatory fish demonstrates the minor contribution of coral mutualists to their highly partitioned, generalist diet\". ''PeerJ'', '''3''': e1047. {{doi|10.7717/peerj.1047}}.</ref>\n}}\n\n[[DNA barcoding]] can be used to construct food web structures with better taxonomic resolution at the web nodes. This provides more specific species identification and greater clarity about exactly who eats whom. \"DNA barcodes and DNA information may allow new approaches to the construction of larger interaction webs, and overcome some hurdles to achieving adequate sample size\".<ref name=Roslin2016 />\n\n{{multiple image\n | align = left\n | direction = horizontal\n | width     = 300\n | header            = Seagrass meadows\n | header_align      = <!-- left/right/center -->\n | image1    = Visualization of an aggregation of seagrass food webs.png\n | alt1      = \n | caption1  = Cumulative visualization of a number of seagrass food webs from different regions and with different eutrophication levels Different coloured dots represent trophic groups from different trophic levels with black \u200a=\u200a primary producers, dark to light grey \u200a=\u200a secondary producers, and the lightest grey being top predators. The grey links represent feeding links.<ref>Coll, M., Schmidt, A., Romanuk, T. and Lotze, H.K. (2011). \"Food-web structure of seagrass communities across different spatial scales and human impacts\". ''PloS ONE'', '''6'''(7): e22591. {{doi|10.1371/journal.pone.0022591}}. [[File:CC-BY icon.svg|50px]] Material was copied from this source, which is available under a [https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by/4.0/ Creative Commons Attribution 4.0 International License].</ref>\n}}\n\n\n\n* [[Kelp forest]]s\n\n{{clear}}\n\n==Deep ocean webs==\n; The mesopelagic web\n<gallery mode=packed heights=360px style=float:right; caption=\"Mesopelagic food web\">\nFile:Mesopelagic species impact on global carbon budget.png| Impact of  mesopelagic species on the global carbon budget <ref>Wang, F., Wu, Y., Chen, Z., Zhang, G., Zhang, J., Zheng, S. and Kattner, G. (2019) \"Trophic interactions of mesopelagic fishes in the South China Sea illustrated by stable isotopes and fatty acids\". ''Frontiers in Marine Science'', '''5''': 522. {{doi|10.3389/fmars.2018.00522}}.</ref><br /><small>DVM = diel vertical migration &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; NM = non-migration</small>\n</gallery>\n\nScientists are starting to explore in more detail the largely unknown twilight zone of the [[mesopelagic]], 200 to 1,000 metres deep. This layer is responsible for removing about 4 billion tonnes of carbon dioxide from the atmosphere each year. The mesopelagic layer is inhabited by most of the marine fish [[Biomass (ecology)|biomass]].<ref name=Tollefson2020>Tollefson, Jeff (27 February 2020) [https://www.nature.com/articles/d41586-020-00520-8?utm_source=Nature+Briefing&utm_campaign=20a3502704-briefing-dy-20200228&utm_medium=email&utm_term=0_c9dfd39373-20a3502704-43400965 Enter the twilight zone: scientists dive into the oceans\u2019 mysterious middle] ''Nature News''. {{doi|10.1038/d41586-020-00520-8}}.</ref>\n\n<gallery mode=packed heights=180px style=float:left;>\nFile:Sigmops bathyphilus.jpg| Mesopelagic [[bristlemouth]]s may be the most abundant vertebrates on the planet, though little is known about them.<ref name=Tollefson2020 />\nFile:Bathykorus bouilloni.jpg| [[Gelatinous zooplankton|Gelatinous predators]] like this [[narcomedusan]] consume the greatest diversity of mesopelagic prey\n</gallery>\n\n{{clear left}}\n\n* [https://theconversation.com/fish-in-the-twilight-cast-new-light-on-ocean-ecosystem-22987 Fish in the twilight cast new light on ocean ecosystem] ''The Conversation'', 10 February 2014.\n* [https://www.nytimes.com/2015/06/30/science/bristlemouth-ocean-deep-sea-cyclothone.html An Ocean Mystery in the Trillions] ''The New York Times'', 29 June 2015.\n* Mesopelagic fishes - [[Malaspina Expedition 2010|Malaspina circumnavigation expedition]] of 2010.<ref>Irigoien, X., Klevjer, T.A., R\u00f8stad, A., Martinez, U., Boyra, G., Acu\u00f1a, J.L., Bode, A., Echevarria, F., Gonzalez-Gordillo, J.I., Hernandez-Leon, S. and Agusti, S. (2014) \"Large mesopelagic fishes biomass and trophic efficiency in the open ocean\". ''Nature communications'', '''5''': 3271. {{doi|10.1038/ncomms4271}}</ref><ref>[https://www.eurekalert.org/pub_releases/2014-02/snrc-fbi020614.php Fish biomass in the ocean is 10 times higher than estimated] ''EurekAlert'', 7 February 2014.</ref>\n\nAccording to a 2017 study, [[narcomedusae]] consume the greatest diversity of mesopelagic prey, followed by [[physonect]] [[siphonophore]]s, [[ctenophore]]s and [[cephalopod]]s. The importance of the so called \"jelly web\" is only beginning to be understood, but it seems medusae, ctenophores and siphonophores can be key predators in deep pelagic food webs with ecological impacts similar to predator fish and squid. Traditionally gelatinous predators were thought ineffectual providers of marine trophic pathways, but they appear to have substantial and integral roles in deep pelagic food webs.<ref>Choy, C.A., Haddock, S.H. and Robison, B.H. (2017) \"Deep pelagic food web structure as revealed by in situ feeding observations\". ''Proceedings of the Royal Society B: Biological Sciences'', '''284'''(1868): 20172116. {{doi|10.1098/rspb.2017.2116}}.</ref> [[Diel vertical migration]], an important  active transport mechanism, allows [[mesozooplankton]] to sequester carbon dioxide from the atmosphere as well as supply carbon needs for other mesopelagic organisms.<ref>Kelly, T.B., Davison, P.C., Goericke, R., Landry, M.R., Ohman, M. and Stukel, M.R. (2019) \"The importance of mesozooplankton diel vertical migration for sustaining a mesopelagic food web\". ''Frontiers in Marine Science'', '''6''': 508. {{doi|10.3389/fmars.2019.00508}}.</ref>\n\n; The deep pelagic web\n[[File:An in situ perspective of a deep pelagic food web.jpg|thumb|upright=2|right| An ''in situ'' perspective of a deep pelagic food web derived from ROV-based observations of feeding, as represented by 20 broad taxonomic groupings. The linkages between predator to prey are coloured according to predator group origin, and loops indicate within-group feeding. The thickness of the lines or edges connecting food web components is scaled to the log of the number of unique ROV feeding observations across the years 1991\u20132016 between the two groups of animals. The different groups have eight colour-coded types according to main animal types as indicated by the legend and defined here: red, cephalopods; orange, crustaceans; light green, fish; dark green, medusa; purple, siphonophores; blue, ctenophores and grey, all other animals. In this plot, the vertical axis does not correspond to trophic level, because this metric is not readily estimated for all members.<ref>Choy, C.A., Haddock, S.H. and Robison, B.H. (2017) \"Deep pelagic food web structure as revealed by ''in situ'' feeding observations\". ''Proceedings of the Royal Society B: Biological Sciences'', '''284'''(1868): 20172116. {{doi|10.1098/rspb.2017.2116}}. [[File:CC-BY icon.svg|50px]] Material was copied from this source, which is available under a [https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by/4.0/ Creative Commons Attribution 4.0 International License].</ref>]]\n\n[[File:Role of micronekton in pelagic food webs.png|thumb|upright=2|left| Oceanic pelagic food web showing energy flow from micronekton to top predators. Line thickness is scaled to the proportion in the diet.<ref>Choy, C.A., Wabnitz, C.C., Weijerman, M., Woodworth-Jefcoats, P.A. and Polovina, J.J. (2016) \"Finding the way to the top: how the composition of oceanic mid-trophic micronekton groups determines apex predator biomass in the central North Pacific\". ''Marine Ecology Progress Series'', '''549''': 9\u201325. {{doi|10.3354/meps11680}}.</ref>]]\n\n{{clear left}}\n\n; Seeps and vents\n[[File:Hydrothermal Vents and Methane Seeps.jpg|thumb|left|upright=2| {{center|'''Seep and vent interactions with surrounding deep-sea ecosystems'''}} The y axis is meters above bottom on a log scale. DOC: [[Dissolved Organic Carbon]], POC: [[Particulate Organic Carbon]], SMS: [[Seafloor Massive Sulfide]].<ref>Levin LA, Baco AR, Bowden DA, Colaco A, Cordes EE, Cunha MR, Demopoulos AWJ, Gobin J, Grupe BM, Le J, Metaxas A, Netburn AN, Rouse GW, Thurber AR, Tunnicliffe V, Van Dover CL, Vanreusel A and Watling L (2016). \"Hydrothermal Vents and Methane Seeps: Rethinking the Sphere of Influence\". ''Front. Mar. Sci.'' '''3''':72. {{doi|10.3389/fmars.2016.00072}}</ref>]]\n\n[[File:Guaymas seep and vent ecosystems.png|thumb|upright=2| Conceptual diagram of faunal community structure and food-web patterns along fluid-flux gradients within [[Guaymas]] seep and vent ecosystems.<ref>Portail, M., Olu, K., Dubois, S.F., Escobar-Briones, E., Gelinas, Y., Menot, L. and Sarrazin, J. (2016). \"Food-web complexity in Guaymas Basin hydrothermal vents and cold seeps\". ''PloS ONE'', '''11'''(9): p.e0162263. {{doi|10.1371/journal.pone.0162263}}.</ref><ref>Bernardino AF, Levin LA, Thurber AR and Smith CR (2012). \"Comparative Composition, Diversity and Trophic Ecology of Sediment Macrofauna at Vents, Seeps and Organic Falls\". PLoS ONE, 7(4): e33515. pmid:22496753. {{doi|10.1371/journal.pone.0033515}}.</ref><ref>Portail M, Olu K, Escobar-Briones E, Caprais JC, Menot L, Waeles M, et al. (2015). \"Comparative study of vent and seep macrofaunal communities in the Guaymas Basin\". Biogeosciences. 12(18): 5455\u201379. {{doi|10.5194/bg-12-5455-2015}}.</ref>]]\n\n{{clear}}\n\n==Polar webs==\n{{multiple image\n | align = right\n | direction = horizontal\n | width     = 210\n | header            = Polar topographies\n | header_align      = center\n | header_background = \n | footer            = [[File:Pulse of Snow and Sea Ice.ogv|420px]]{{center|The annual pulse of ice and snow at the poles}}\n | footer_align      = \n | footer_background = \n | background color  = \n | image1    = Globe showing Antarctic 2.png\n | alt1      = \n | caption1  = {{center|The [[Antarctica]] is a frozen landmass<br />surrounded by oceans}}\n | image2    = Globe showing Arctic 2.png\n | alt2      = \n | caption2  = {{center|The [[Arctic]] is a frozen ocean<br />surrounded by landmasses}}\n}}\n\nArctic and Antarctic marine systems have very different [[Marine topography|topographical structures]] and as a consequence have very different food web structures.<ref name=IPCC2001>McCarthy, J.J., Canziani, O.F., Leary, N.A., Dokken, D.J. and White, K.S. (Eds.) (2001) [https://books.google.com/books?id=RT7lQ24quc4C&pg=PA807&lpg=PA807&dq=%22the+Arctic+is+a+frozen+ocean+surrounded+by+continental+landmasses+and+open+oceans,+whereas+Antarctica+is+a+frozen+continent+surrounded+solely+by+oceans%22&source=bl&ots=ot_2WsboLX&sig=ACfU3U35AAabEothGkPYK80gfEQycNz6Pg&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwiTmoa666rnAhXS63MBHUl_DpgQ6AEwBHoECAgQAQ#v=onepage&q=%22the%20Arctic%20is%20a%20frozen%20ocean%20surrounded%20by%20continental%20landmasses%20and%20open%20oceans%2C%20whereas%20Antarctica%20is%20a%20frozen%20continent%20surrounded%20solely%20by%20oceans%22&f=false ''Climate Change 2001: Impacts, Adaptation, and Vulnerability: Contribution of Working Group II to the Third Assessment Report of the Intergovernmental Panel on Climate Change''] Page 807, Cambridge University Press. {{ISBN|9780521015004}}</ref> Both Arctic and Antarctic pelagic food webs have characteristic energy flows controlled largely by a few key species. But there is no single generic web for either. Alternative pathways are important for resilience and maintaining energy flows. However, these more complicated alternatives provide less energy flow to upper trophic-level species. \"Food-web structure may be similar in different regions, but the individual species that dominate mid-trophic levels vary across polar regions\".<ref>Murphy, E.J., Cavanagh, R.D., Drinkwater, K.F., Grant, S.M., Heymans, J.J., Hofmann, E.E., Hunt Jr, G.L. and Johnston, N.M. (2016) \"Understanding the structure and functioning of polar pelagic ecosystems to predict the impacts of change\". ''Proceedings of the Royal Society B: Biological Sciences'', '''283'''(1844): 20161646. {{doi|10.1098/rspb.2016.1646}}.</ref>\n\n[[File:Humpback whale NOAA.jpg|thumb|300px|left|Humpback whale straining krill]]\n\n{{multiple image\n | align = left\n | direction = horizontal\n | header = Penguins and polar bears never meet\n | image1    = Kaiserpinguine mit Jungen.jpg\n | width1    = 275\n | alt1      = \n | caption1  = {{center|The Antarctic has penguins but no polar bears}}\n | image2    = Polar Bear 2004-11-15.jpg\n | width2    = 240\n | alt2      = \n | caption2  = {{center|The Arctic has polar bears but no penguins}}\n}}\n\n{{clear}}\n\n; Arctic\n{{multiple image\n | align = right\n | direction = horizontal\n | header            = Polar bear food webs\n | header_align      = <!-- left/right/center -->\n | header_background = \n | footer            = \n | footer_align      = <!-- left/right/center -->\n | footer_background = \n | background color  = \n | width1    = 300\n | image1    = Arctic marine food web.jpg\n | alt1      = \n | caption1  = {{center|Traditional arctic marine food web with a focus on [[wiktionary:macroorganism|macroorganisms]]}}\n | width2    = 270\n | image2    = Arctic marine food web 2.jpg\n | alt2      = \n | caption2  = Contemporary arctic marine food web with a greater focus on the role of [[Marine microorganism|microorganisms]]\n}}\n\nThe Arctic food web is complex. The loss of sea ice can ultimately affect the entire food web, from algae and plankton to fish to mammals. The impact of climate change on a particular species can ripple through a food web and affect a wide range of other organisms... Not only is the decline of sea ice impairing polar bear populations by reducing the extent of their primary habitat, it is also negatively impacting them via food web effects. Declines in the duration and extent of sea ice in the Arctic leads to declines in the abundance of ice algae, which thrive in nutrient-rich pockets in the ice. These algae are eaten by zooplankton, which are in turn eaten by Arctic cod, an important food source for many marine mammals, including seals. Seals are eaten by polar bears. Hence, declines in ice algae can contribute to declines in polar bear populations.<ref>[https://archive.epa.gov/epa/climate-impacts/climate-impacts-ecosystems.html#ref2 Climate Impacts on Ecosystems: Food Web Disruptions] ''EPA''. Accessed 11 February 2020. {{PD-notice}}</ref>\n\n{{multiple image\n | align = left\n | direction = horizontal\n | header = \n | image1 = Sea angel.jpg\n | width1 = 259\n | alt1   = \n | caption1 = {{center|Pteropod ([[sea angel]])}}\n----\n[[File:Nuvola apps kaboodle.svg|16px]] [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=3-40RU3iSkA Pteropods: Swimming snails of the sea]\n | image2 = Marinomonas arctica.jpg\n | width2 = 172\n | alt2  = \n | caption2 = The bacterium ''[[Marinomonas arctica]]'' grows inside Arctic sea ice at subzero temperatures\n | image3 = Walrus's Floating On Bering Sea Ice Alaska.jpg\n | width3 = 259\n | alt3  = \n | caption3 = [[Walrus]] are keystone species in the Arctic but are not found in the Antarctic.\n}}\n\n{{multiple image\n | align = right\n | direction = horizontal\n | width     = 320\n | header            = Arctic food web with mixotrophy\n | header_align      = <!-- left/right/center -->\n | image1    = Arctic food web with mixotrophy.png\n | alt1      = \n | caption1  = Yellow arrows: flow of energy from the sun to photosynthetic organisms ([[autotroph]]s and [[mixotroph]]s)<br />Gray arrows: flow of carbon to heterotrophs<br />Green arrows: major pathways of carbon flow to or from mixotrophs<br />HCIL: [[heterotrophic]] ciliates; MCIL: mixotrophic ciliates; HNF: heterotrophic nanoflagellates; DOC: dissolved organic carbon; HDIN: heterotrophic dinoflagellates <ref>Stoecker, D.K. and Lavrentyev, P.J. (2018). \"Mixotrophic plankton in the polar seas: a pan-arctic review\". ''Frontiers in Marine Science'', '''5''': 292. {{doi|10.3389/fmars.2018.00292}}</ref>\n}}\n\n{{clear left}}\n\n; Antarctic\n<gallery mode=packed style=\"float:left;\">\nFile:Ice planet and antarctic jellyfish (crop).jpg|Antarctic jellyfish ''[[Diplulmaris antarctica ]]'' under the ice\nFile:Phaeocystis.png| Colonies of the alga ''[[Phaeocystis|Phaeocystis antarctica]]'', an important phytoplankter of the Ross Sea that dominates early season blooms after the sea ice retreats and exports significant carbon.<ref>Bender, S.J., Moran, D.M., McIlvin, M.R., Zheng, H., McCrow, J.P., Badger, J., DiTullio, G.R., Allen, A.E. and Saito, M.A. (2018) \"Colony formation in ''Phaeocystis antarctica'': connecting molecular mechanisms with iron biogeochemistry\". ''Biogeosciences'', '''15'''(16): 4923\u20134942. {{doi|10.5194/bg-15-4923-2018}}.</ref>\nFile:Fragilariopsis kerguelensis.jpg| The [[pennales|pennate]] [[diatom]] ''[[Fragilariopsis kerguelensis]]'', found throughout the Antarctic Circumpolar Current, is a key driver of the global [[Silica cycle#Marine silica cycling|silicate pump]].<ref>Pinkernell, S. and Beszteri, B. (2014) \"Potential effects of climate change on the distribution range of the main silicate sinker of the Southern Ocean\". ''Ecology and evolution'', '''4'''(16): 3147\u20133161. {{doi|10.1002/ece3.1138}}</ref>\nFile:Killer Whales Hunting a Crabeater Seal.jpg| A group of [[killer whale]]s attempt to dislodge a [[crabeater seal]] on an [[ice floe]]\n</gallery>\n\n{{multiple image\n | align = left\n | direction = horizontal\n | width     = 400\n | header    = Importance of Antarctic krill in biogeochemical cycles\n | image1    = Importance of Antarctic krill in biogeochemical cycles.png\n | caption1  = {{center|'''Processes in the biological pump'''}}{{center|<small> Numbers given are carbon fluxes (Gt\u2009C\u2009yr\u22121) in white boxes<br />and carbon masses (Gt C) in dark boxes</small>}}\nPhytoplankton convert CO2, which has dissolved from the atmosphere into the surface oceans into particulate organic carbon (POC) during primary production. Phytoplankton are then consumed by krill and small zooplankton grazers, which in turn are preyed upon by higher trophic levels. Any unconsumed phytoplankton form aggregates, and along with zooplankton faecal pellets, sink rapidly and are exported out of the mixed layer. Krill, zooplankton and microbes intercept phytoplankton in the surface ocean and sinking detrital particles at depth, consuming and respiring this POC to CO2 (dissolved inorganic carbon, DIC), such that only a small proportion of surface-produced carbon sinks to the deep ocean (i.e., depths\u2009>\u20091000\u2009m). As krill and smaller zooplankton feed, they also physically fragment particles into small, slower- or non-sinking pieces (via sloppy feeding, coprorhexy if fragmenting faeces), retarding POC export. This releases dissolved organic carbon (DOC) either directly from cells or indirectly via bacterial solubilisation (yellow circle around DOC). Bacteria can then remineralise the DOC to DIC (CO2, microbial gardening). Diel vertically migrating krill, smaller zooplankton and fish can actively transport carbon to depth by consuming POC in the surface layer at night, and metabolising it at their daytime, mesopelagic residence depths. Depending on species life history, active transport may occur on a seasonal basis as well.<ref>Cavan, E.L., Belcher, A., Atkinson, A., Hill, S.L., Kawaguchi, S., McCormack, S., Meyer, B., Nicol, S., Ratnarajah, L., Schmidt, K. and Steinberg, D.K. (2019) \"The importance of Antarctic krill in biogeochemical cycles\". ''Nature communications'', '''10'''(1): 1\u201313. {{doi|10.1038/s41467-019-12668-7}}.  [[File:CC-BY icon.svg|50px]] Material was copied from this source, which is available under a [https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by/4.0/ Creative Commons Attribution 4.0 International License].</ref>\n}}\n\n[[File:Antarctic marine food web - Potter Cove.png|thumb|upright=1.6|right| {{center|'''Antarctic marine food web'''}} Potter Cove 2018. Vertical position indicates trophic level and node widths are proportional to total degree (in and out). Node colors represent functional groups.<ref name=Cordone2018>Cordone, G., Marina, T.I., Salinas, V., Doyle, S.R., Saravia, L.A. and Momo, F.R.(2018). \"Effects of macroalgae loss in an Antarctic marine food web: applying extinction thresholds to food web studies\". ''PeerJ'', '''6''': e5531. {{doi|10.7717/peerj.5531}}</ref><ref>Marina, T.I., Salinas, V., Cordone, G., Campana, G., Moreira, E., Deregibus, D., Torre, L., Sahade, R., Tatian, M., Oro, E.B. and De Troch, M. (2018). \"The food web of Potter Cove (Antarctica): complexity, structure and function\". Estuarine, Coastal and Shelf Science, 200: 141\u2013151. doi:10.1016/j.ecss.2017.10.015.</ref>]]\n\n[[File:Common-enemy graph of food web.png|thumb|upright=1.6|right| {{center|'''Common-enemy graph of Antarctic food web'''}} Potter Cove 2018. Nodes represent basal species and links indirect interactions (shared predators). Node and link widths are proportional to number of shared predators. Node colors represent functional groups.<ref name=Cordone2018 />]]\n\n{{clear}}\n\n[[File:Sea ice food web and the microbial loop.png|thumb|upright=1.6|right| Sea ice food web and the microbial loop. AAnP = aerobic anaerobic phototroph, DOC = dissolved organic carbon, DOM = dissolved organic matter, POC = particulate organic carbon, PR = proteorhodopsins.<ref>Koh, E.Y., Martin, A.R., McMinn, A. and Ryan, K.G. (2012) \"Recent advances and future perspectives in microbial phototrophy in Antarctic sea ice\". ''Biology'', '''1'''(3): 542-556. {{doi|10.3390/biology1030542}}.</ref><ref>The microbial loop here is re-drawn and abridged from:\n*  Azam, F., Fenchel, T., Field, J.G., Gray, J.S., Meyer-Reil, L.A. and Thingstad, F. (1983) [https://www.jstor.org/stable/24814647 \"The ecological role of water-column microbes in the sea\"]. ''Marine ecology progress series'', '''10'''(3): 257\u2013263.\n* Fenchel, T. (2008) \"The microbial loop\u201325 years later\". ''Journal of Experimental Marine Biology and Ecology'', '''366'''(1-2): 99-103. {{doi|10.1016/j.jembe.2008.07.013}}.</ref>]]\n\n{{clear}}\n\n==Terrestrial comparisons==\n[[File:Numbers Pyramid.svg|thumb|340px| {{center|'''[[Biomass pyramid]]s'''<br />Compared to terrestrial biomass pyramids, aquatic pyramids are generally inverted at the base}}]] \n{{multiple image\n | align = right\n | direction = horizontal\n | header            = Marine producers use less biomass than terrestrial producers\n | header_align      = <!-- left/right/center -->\n | footer            = \n | footer_align      = <!-- left/right/center -->\n | footer_background = \n | background color  = \n | width1    = 230\n | image1    = Prochlorococcus marinus (cropped).jpg\n | alt1      = \n | caption1  = The minute but ubiquitous and highly active bacterium [[Prochlorococcus]] runs through its life cycle in one day, collectively generating 20% of all global oxygen.\n | width2    = 230\n | image2    = Gnarly Bristlecone Pine (crop).jpg\n | alt2      = \n | caption2  = By contrast, a single [[bristlecone pine]] can tie up a lot of relatively inert biomass for thousands of years with little photosynthetic activity.<ref name=\"oldest\">{{cite web|url=http://www.rmtrr.org/oldlist.htm|title=Oldlist|publisher=Rocky Mountain Tree Ring Research|access-date=January 8, 2013}}</ref>\n}}\n\nMarine environments can have inversions in their biomass pyramids. In particular, the biomass of consumers (copepods, krill, shrimp, forage fish) is generally larger than the biomass of primary producers. This happens because the ocean's primary producers are mostly tiny phytoplankton which have [[r-strategist]] traits of growing and reproducing rapidly, so a small mass can have a fast rate of primary production. In contrast, many terrestrial primary producers, such as mature forests, have [[K-strategist]] traits of growing and reproducing slowly, so a much larger mass is needed to achieve the same rate of primary production.\n\nExamples: The [[bristlecone pine]] can live for thousands of years, and has a very low production/biomass ratio. The cyanobacterium ''[[Prochlorococcus]]'' lives for about 24 hours, and has a very high production/biomass ratio.\n\n[[File:Misty Forest (227339925).jpeg|thumb|300px|left| {{center|Mature forests have a lot of biomass invested in [[secondary growth]] which has low [[Productivity (ecology)|productivity]]}}]]\n[[File:Biomass by life form.jpg|thumb|300px|left| {{center|Ocean or marine biomass, in a reversal of terrestrial biomass, can increase at higher trophic levels.<ref>Bar-On, Y.M., Phillips, R. and Milo, R. (2018) \"The biomass distribution on Earth\". ''Proceedings of the National Academy of Sciences'', '''115'''(25): 6506\u20136511. {{doi|10.1073/pnas.1711842115}}.</ref>}}]]\n\nIn oceans, most [[primary production]] is performed by [[algae]]. This is a contrast to on land, where most primary production is performed by [[vascular plants]]. \n\nAquatic producers, such as planktonic algae or aquatic plants, lack the large accumulation of [[secondary growth]] that exists in the woody trees of terrestrial ecosystems. However, they are able to reproduce quickly enough to support a larger biomass of grazers. This inverts the pyramid. Primary consumers have longer lifespans and slower growth rates that accumulates more biomass than the producers they consume. Phytoplankton live just a few days, whereas the zooplankton eating the phytoplankton live for several weeks and the fish eating the zooplankton live for several consecutive years.<ref>{{cite book | last= Spellman| first= Frank R.| title= The Science of Water: Concepts and Applications| year= 2008| publisher= CRC Press| page= 167| url= https://books.google.com/?id=Grivqd7tLuAC&pg=PA167&dq=However,+biomass+pyramids+can+sometimes+be+inverted.&cd=1#v=onepage&q=However%2C%20biomass%20pyramids%20can%20sometimes%20be%20inverted.| isbn= 978-1-4200-5544-3}}</ref> Aquatic predators also tend to have a lower death rate than the smaller consumers, which contributes to the inverted pyramidal pattern. Population structure, migration rates, and environmental refuge for prey are other possible causes for pyramids with biomass inverted. [[Energy pyramid]]s, however, will always have an upright pyramid shape if all sources of food energy are included, since this is dictated by the [[second law of thermodynamics]].\"<ref name=\"Odum05\">{{cite book | last1=Odum | first1=E. P. | last2=Barrett | first2=G. W. | title=Fundamentals of Ecology | edition=5th | publisher=Brooks/Cole, a part of Cengage Learning | year=2005 | isbn=978-0-534-42066-6 | url=http://www.cengage.com/aushed/instructor.do?disciplinenumber=1041&product_isbn=9780534420666&courseid=BI03&codeid=2BF6&subTab=&mainTab=About_the_Book&mailFlag=true&topicName= | url-status=dead | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110820163059/http://www.cengage.com/aushed/instructor.do?disciplinenumber=1041&product_isbn=9780534420666&courseid=BI03&codeid=2BF6&subTab=&mainTab=About_the_Book&mailFlag=true&topicName= | archivedate=2011-08-20 }}</ref><ref name=\"Wang09\">{{cite journal | last1=Wang | first1=H. | last2=Morrison | first2=W. | last3=Singh | first3=A. | last4=Weiss | first4=H. | title=Modeling inverted biomass pyramids and refuges in ecosystems | journal=Ecological Modelling | volume=220 | issue=11 | pages=1376\u20131382 | doi=10.1016/j.ecolmodel.2009.03.005 | year=2009 | url=http://people.math.gatech.edu/~weiss/pub/General_Mechanisms_Final.pdf | url-status=dead | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111007214333/http://people.math.gatech.edu/~weiss/pub/General_Mechanisms_Final.pdf | archivedate=2011-10-07 }}</ref>\n\n{|class=\"wikitable\"\n! colspan=4 | {{centre|Comparison of productivity in marine and terrestrial ecosystems <ref>Field, C.B., Behrenfeld, M.J., Randerson, J.T. and Falkowski, P. (1998) \"Primary production of the biosphere: integrating terrestrial and oceanic components\". ''Science'', '''281'''(5374): 237\u2013240. {{doi|10.1126/science.281.5374.237}}.</ref>}}\n|-\n! style=\"background:rgb(110,110,170)\"| <span style=\"color:white;\">Ecosystem</span>\n! Net primary productivity<br /><small>billion tonnes per year</small>\n! Total plant biomass<br /><small>billion tonnes</small>\n! Turnover time<br /><small>years</small>\n|-\n| style=\"background:rgb(110,110,170); color:white;\"| {{center|Marine}}\n| {{center|45\u201355}}\n| {{center|1\u20132}}\n| {{center|0.02\u20130.06}}\n|-\n| style=\"background:rgb(110,110,170); color:white;\"| {{center|Terrestrial}}\n| {{center|55\u201370}}\n| {{center|600\u20131000}}\n| {{center|9\u201320}}\n|}\n\n{{clear}}\n\n==Anthropogenic effects==\n[[File:Fishing down the food web.jpg|thumb|upright=1.7| {{center|[[Fishing down the food web]] <ref>Maureaud, A., Gascuel, D., Coll\u00e9ter, M., Palomares, M.L., Du Pontavice, H., Pauly, D. and Cheung, W.W. (2017) \"Global change in the trophic functioning of marine food webs\". ''PloS one'', '''12'''(8): e0182826. {{doi|10.1371/journal.pone.0182826}}</ref>}}]]\n\n;Overfishing\n\n;Acidification\n[[Pteropoda|Pteropods]] and [[brittle star]]s together form the base of the Arctic [[food web]]s and both are seriously damaged by acidification. Pteropods shells dissolve with increasing acidification and brittle stars lose muscle mass when re-growing appendages.<ref>{{cite web|title=Effects of Ocean Acidification on Marine Species & Ecosystems|url=http://oceana.org/en/our-work/climate-energy/ocean-acidification/learn-act/effects-of-ocean-acidification-on-marine-species-ecosystems|work=Report|publisher=OCEANA|accessdate=13 October 2013}}</ref> Additionally the brittle star's eggs die within a few days when exposed to expected conditions resulting from Arctic acidification.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.cicero.uio.no/webnews/index_e.aspx?id=11909 | title=Comprehensive study of Arctic Ocean acidification | publisher=CICERO | work=Study | accessdate=14 November 2013 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131210231159/http://www.cicero.uio.no/webnews/index_e.aspx?id=11909 | archive-date=10 December 2013 | url-status=dead }}</ref> Acidification threatens to destroy Arctic food webs from the base up. Arctic waters are changing rapidly and are advanced in the process of becoming undersaturated with aragonite.<ref name=\"biogeosciences\">{{cite web | url=http://www.biogeosciences.net/8/919/2011/bg-8-919-2011.pdf | title=Impact of ocean acidification and elevated temperatures on early juveniles of the polar shelled pteropod Limacina helicina : mortality, shell degradation, and shell growth | publisher=Biogeosciences | work=Report |date=15 April 2011 | accessdate=14 November 2013 |author1=Lischka, S. |author2=B\u00fcdenbender J. |author3=Boxhammer T. |author4=Riebesell U. | pages=919\u2013932}}</ref> Arctic food webs are considered simple, meaning there are few steps in the food chain from small organisms to larger predators. For example, pteropods are \"a key prey item of a number of higher predators \u2013 larger plankton, fish, seabirds, whales\".<ref>{{cite web|title=Antarctic marine wildlife is under threat, study finds|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/nature/20461646|publisher=BBC Nature|accessdate=13 October 2013}}</ref>\n\n{{clear left}}\n\n{{multiple image\n | align = left\n | direction = horizontal\n | header = Effects of ocean acidification\n | image1    = Fis01026 (27555118153).jpg\n | width1    = 170\n | alt1      = \n | caption1  = {{center|Unhealthy pteropod showing effects of ocean acidification}}\n | image2    = FMIB 52630 Ophiopholis aculeata.jpeg\n | width2    = 230\n | alt2      = \n | caption2  = {{center|Ocean acidification causes brittle stars to lose muscle mass}}\n | footer            = &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; [[Pteropod]]s and [[brittle star]]s form the base of Arctic food webs\n | footer_align      = center\n}}\n\n{{clear}}\n\n; Climate change\n\"Our results show how future climate change can potentially weaken marine food webs through reduced energy flow to higher trophic levels and a shift towards a more detritus-based system, leading to food web simplification and altered producer\u2013consumer dynamics, both of which have important implications for the structuring of benthic communities.\"<ref>Ullah, H., Nagelkerken, I., Goldenberg, S.U. and Fordham, D.A. (2018) \"Climate change could drive marine food web collapse through altered trophic flows and cyanobacterial proliferation\". ''PLoS biology'', '''16'''(1): e2003446. {{doi|10.1371/journal.pbio.2003446}}</ref><ref name=ScienceDaily2018>[https://www.sciencedaily.com/releases/2018/01/180109150921.htm Climate change drives collapse in marine food webs] ''ScienceDaily''. 9 January 2018.</ref>\n\n\"...increased temperatures reduce the vital flow of energy from the primary food producers at the bottom (e.g. algae), to intermediate consumers (herbivores), to predators at the top of marine food webs. Such disturbances in energy transfer can potentially lead to a decrease in food availability for top predators, which in turn, can lead to negative impacts for many marine species within these food webs... \"Whilst climate change increased the productivity of plants, this was mainly due to an expansion of cyanobacteria (small blue-green algae),\" said Mr Ullah. \"This increased primary productivity does not support food webs, however, because these cyanobacteria are largely unpalatable and they are not consumed by herbivores. Understanding how ecosystems function under the effects of global warming is a challenge in ecological research. Most research on ocean warming involves simplified, short-term experiments based on only one or a few species.\"<ref name=ScienceDaily2018 />\n\n[[File:Global distribution of anthropogenic stressors to marine species.png|thumb|upright=1.7|left| The distribution of anthropogenic stressors faced by marine species threatened with extinction in various marine regions of the world. Numbers in the pie charts indicate the percentage contribution of an anthropogenic stressors\u2019 impact in a specific marine region.<ref>Luypaert, T., Hagan, J.G., McCarthy, M.L. and Poti, M. (2020) \"Status of Marine Biodiversity in the Anthropocene\". In: ''YOUMARES 9-The Oceans: Our Research, Our Future'', pages 57-82, Springer. {{doi|10.1007/978-3-030-20389-4_4}}.</ref><ref>IUCN (2018) [http://www.iucnredlist.org The IUCN Red List of Threatened Species: Version 2018-1]</ref>]]\n\n[[File:Anthropogenic stressors to marine species threatened with extinction.png|thumb|upright=1.7|right| {{center|Anthropogenic stressors to marine species threatened with extinction <ref>Luypaert, T., Hagan, J.G., McCarthy, M.L. and Poti, M. (2020) \"Status of Marine Biodiversity in the Anthropocene\". In: ''YOUMARES 9-The Oceans: Our Research, Our Future'', pages 57-82, Springer. {{doi|10.1007/978-3-030-20389-4_4}}.</ref><ref>IUCN (2018) [http://www.iucnredlist.org The IUCN Red List of Threatened Species: Version 2018-1]</ref>}}]]\n\n{{clear}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Aquatic ecology]]\n[[Category:Ecological connectivity]]\n[[Category:Trophic ecology]]\n", "name_user": "Epipelagic", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200ePrimary producers:again", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Marine_food_web"}
{"title_page": "Redmi", "text_new": "{{Distinguish|Realme}}{{more citations needed|date=May 2019}}\n{{Infobox company\n| name = Redmi by Xiaomi\n| logo = Redmi by Xiaomi Logo.svg\n| caption = \n| native_name = \u7ea2\u7c73\n| type = Sub-brand\n| key_people = Lu Weibing (General Manager)\n| products = [[Smartphone]]s<br>[[Phablets]]<br>[[Laptop]]s<br>[[Smart TV]]s\n| parent = [[Xiaomi]]\n| foundation = {{start date and age|2013|7|df=y}}<br>({{small|as Xiaomi Redmi series}})<br>{{start date and age|2019|1|10|df=y}}<br>({{small|sub-brand of Xiaomi}})\n| website = https://www.mi.com/\n}}\n\n[[File:Xiaomi Redmi 2.jpg|170px|thumb|Redmi 2]]\n[[File:Xiaomi Redmi Note 3.jpg|thumb|308x308px|Redmi Note 3]]\n'''Redmi''' is a sub-brand owned by the Chinese electronics company [[Xiaomi]]. It was first announced in July 2013 as a budget [[smartphone]] line,<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://thenextweb.com/asia/2013/07/31/xiaomi-launches-red-rice-its-lowest-priced-phone-in-partnership-with-tencent-and-china-mobile/#!qZcQC|title=Xiaomi Launches Red Rice Phone|last=Hong|first=Kaylene|date=2013-07-31|work=The Next Web|access-date=2017-06-17|language=en-US}}</ref> and became a separate sub-brand of Xiaomi in 2019 with entry-level and mid-range devices, while Xiaomi itself produces upper-range and flagship Mi phones. Redmi phones use the Xiaomi [[MIUI]] user interface on top of [[Android (operating system)|Android]]. Models can be divided into the entry-level '''Redmi''' phones with display usually up to 6\" and the mid-range '''Redmi Note''' series with displays exceeding 5\" and equipped with higher-end specifications. The low-end '''Redmi A''' series and '''Redmi Go''' have been marketed in several Asian and European countries. The most significant difference from other Xiaomi smartphones is that they use less-expensive components and thus have lower prices with reduced specification. In August 2014, ''[[The Wall Street Journal]]'' reported that in the second quarter of the 2014 fiscal year,  Xiaomi had a market share of 14% of smartphone shipment rankings in China.<ref name=\"Dou\">[https://blogs.wsj.com/digits/2014/08/04/xiaomi-overtakes-samsung-in-china-smartphone-market/ Xiaomi Overtakes Samsung in China Smartphone Market - Digits<!-- Bot generated title -->]. 4 August 2014. ''[[The Wall Street Journal]]''.</ref> Redmi sales were attributed as a contributing factor toward this gain in shipment rankings.<ref name=\"Dou\"/>\n\nIn 2019, Redmi marks its debut on the flagship market with the introduction of '''Redmi K''' series.\n\n==2013==\nThe first Redmi phone, released in 2013, was first launched on Xiaomi's website, with consumer sales beginning on 12 July 2013.\n\n==2014==\nOn 13 March 2014, Redmi announced that their phones had been sold out in Singapore alone, eight minutes<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.hardwarezone.com.sg/tech-news-xiaomi-singapore-sold-5000-redmi-phones-8-minutes-and-4-seconds|title=Xiaomi Singapore Sold 5,000 Redmi Phones in 8 Minutes and 4 Seconds|access-date=2017-06-17|language=en}}</ref> after being made available to buy on Xiaomi's website. Criticism regarding the release of Redmi phones included the notion that the firm may be exaggerating its sales by releasing them in small batches, causing them to quickly sell out.<ref name=\"Asia One\">{{cite news|url=http://news.asiaone.com/news/digital1/5000-redmi-sold-out-8-minutes|title=5,000 Redmi sold out in 8 minutes|date=14 March 2014|work=The Straits Times|accessdate=12 August 2014}}</ref>\n\nOn 4 August 2014, ''The Wall Street Journal'' reported that in China's smartphone market, Xiaomi overtook Samsung in the second-quarter of the 2014 fiscal year with a 14% market share in smartphone shipment rankings, while Samsung had a 12% market share during this time.<ref>[https://blogs.wsj.com/digits/2014/08/04/xiaomi-overtakes-samsung-in-china-smartphone-market/ Xiaomi Overtakes Samsung in China Smartphone Market]. August 4, 2014. ''[[The Wall Street Journal]]''.</ref> Yulong and Lenovo both had a 12% market share during this time.<ref name=\"Dou\"/> Redmi sales were attributed as contributing to Xiaomi's increased shipment rankings in the smartphone market.<ref name=\"Dou\"/> Conversely, in the first-quarter of 2014, Xiaomi held a 10.7% market share.<ref name=\"Dou\"/>\n\n== 2015 ==\nThe [[Xiaomi Redmi Note 3|Redmi Note 3]] launched on 24 November 2015; unlike its predecessor, it does not have a user-changeable battery or [[Secure Digital#Physical size|microSD]] slot. It uses the Mediatek Helio X10 Octa-core 2.0&nbsp;GHz Cortex-A53 SOC with the PowerVR G6200 GPU. The Snapdragon variant of the phone, released later the same year, is based on the Snapdragon 650 and has microSD support.\n\n==2016==\nIn July 2016, the actors [[Liu Shishi]], [[Wu Xiubo]] and [[Liu Haoran]] became the first ambassadors of the Redmi series in China.<ref>{{cite web|url= http://gsminsider.com/2016/07/xiaomi-unveils-three-ambassadors-of-redmi-series-in-china/ |title= Xiaomi unveils three ambassadors of Redmi series in China |publisher=GSM INSIDER |date= |accessdate=2016-07-12}}</ref> Redmi Pro has appeared as Pro lineup in Redmi series.\n\nOn 25 August 2016, Xiaomi unveiled the Redmi Note 4, powered by MediaTek's Helio X20 deca-core processor clocked at 2.1&nbsp;GHz. The device has 2 GB RAM and 16 GB of internal storage. It has a 5.5-inch Full-HD display and a 13 MP rear camera and 5 MP front camera. It runs on Android 5.1 Lollipop and is powered by a 4,100 mAh battery.\n\nIn November 2016, Xiaomi released its new budget phone, Redmi 4. It has a polycarbonate body, dual-SIM support and runs on MIUI 8 based on Android 6.0.1 Marshmallow. The Redmi 4 has a 5-inch 720x1280 pixels display, is powered by a 1.4&nbsp;GHz octa-core processor, and has 2GB of RAM.\n\n== 2017 ==\nIn January 2017, the Xiaomi Redmi Note 4x based on Qualcomm Snapdragon 625 Chipset became the company's first major launch of 2017.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.xda-developers.com/xiaomi-launches-the-redmi-note-4-snapdragon-625-variant-in-india/|title=Xiaomi Launches the Redmi Note 4 Snapdragon 625 Variant in India|date=2017-01-19|work=xda-developers|access-date=2017-06-17|language=en-US}}</ref> It is an upgraded version of the previously released Redmi Note 4 based on the MediaTek Helio X20 chipset. The device is known as Redmi Note 4 in regions where the original Redmi Note 4 was not released.\n\nIn December 2017, Xiaomi unveiled the [[Redmi 5]] and 5 Plus. They are the first phones in the Redmi series with an 18:9 screen aspect ratio. The [[European Union|EU]] release was set to January 2018 and prices were set to [[Euro|\u20ac]]170 for the Redmi 5 and \u20ac215 for the Redmi 5 Plus.\n\n== 2018 ==\nIn February 2018, Xiaomi unveiled the [[Redmi Note 5]] and 5 Pro. They are the first phones from Xiaomi to feature facial recognition.\n\nIn May 2018, Xiaomi unveiled the Redmi S2.\n\nIn June 2018, Xiaomi unveiled the Redmi 6, 6A and 6 Pro. The [[Xiaomi Mi 2 Lite|Redmi 6 Pro]] is the first phone in the Redmi series with a notch similar to the [[iPhone X]] and a 19:9 screen aspect ratio.\n\nIn September 2018, Xiaomi unveiled the [[Redmi Note 6 Pro]]. It is the first phone in the Redmi series with four cameras (two cameras on the front and two cameras on the back) and constructed using 6000 series aluminium.\n\n== 2019 ==\nOn 10 January 2019, Xiaomi unveiled the Redmi Note 7 and Redmi Note 7 Pro. The Redmi Note 7 and Redmi Note 7 Pro are the first phones in the Redmi series to feature a 48-megapixel rear camera. The Redmi Note 7 has a Samsung GM1 sensor, and the Redmi Note 7 Pro has a Sony IMX586 48MP sensor. The Redmi Note 7 is powered by the Qualcomm Snapdragon 660 Octa-Core Processor clocked at 2.2&nbsp;GHz, while the Redmi Note 7 Pro has an 11&nbsp;nm Qualcomm Snapdragon 675 Octa-Core Processor clocked at 2.0&nbsp;GHz. Redmi then became a sub-brand distinct from Xiaomi. The Redmi Note 7 is available with 3GB RAM with 32GB storage, 4GB RAM with 64GB storage and 6GB RAM with 64GB storage. It has a 4,000mAh battery with QuickCharge 4.0.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.yugatech.com/mobile/xiaomi-redmi-note-7-to-launch-in-the-philippines-on-march-20/#sthash.g1W3TxWG.dpbs#OLYQCcqQK0vpCHkL.97|title=Xiaomi Redmi Note 7 launched in the Philippines|work=Yugatech}}</ref> The Redmi Note 7 series of smartphones is one of the best selling phone by Redmi. Over 20 million devices were sold in 7 months from introduction of phone.\n\nThe Redmi K20 and [[Redmi K20 Pro]] (also marketed as the ''Mi 9T'') are Redmi's first foray into the flagship market. The phone was launched along with the Redmi 7A in China on May 28. The K20 Pro is powered by the flagship [[Qualcomm Snapdragon|Snapdragon 855]] processor while the K20 is powered by the newly released [[Qualcomm Snapdragon|Snapdragon 730]] and Redmi 7A is low range  phone with [[Snapdragon 430|Snapdragon 439]]. Redmi 8A is a budget range device which is the successor of Redmi 7A. Redmi Note 8 and Redmi Note 8 Pro were launched in August 29.\n\n== 2020==\nOn 24 March 2019, Xiaomi unveiled the Redmi K30 Pro. The Redmi K30 Pro has a Sony IMX686 64MP sensor. The K30 Pro is powered by the flagship [[Qualcomm_Snapdragon|Snapdragon 865]]. It's an Octa-Core Processor clocked at 2.84 GHz.\n\nThe Redmi K30 Pro is available with 6GB [[LPDDR4X]] RAM with 128GB [[Universal_Flash_Storage|UFS 3.0]] storage, 8GB [[LPDDR5]] RAM with 128GB [[Universal_Flash_Storage|UFS 3.1]] storage and 8GB LPDDR5 RAM with 256GB UFS 3.1 storage.\n\n==List of devices==\nList is made according to Chinese names if the device has multiple names.\n\n===Redmi===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n! rowspan=\"2\" | Model\n! rowspan=\"2\" | Model number\n! rowspan=\"2\" | Release date\n! rowspan=\"2\" | Display type\n! rowspan=\"2\" | Display size\n! rowspan=\"2\" | Resolution\n! rowspan=\"2\" | [[Long Term Evolution|4G LTE]] support\n! rowspan=\"2\" | [[System on a chip|System on chip]]\n! rowspan=\"2\" | GPU (Integrated with System o